<FILEID>AP-NR-08-30-88 0135EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-PartyMoney     08-30 0557</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Party Money,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Direct-Mail Falloff Causes Decline In Donations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans are giving less to the two major
political parties, and Republicans hold a smaller fund-raising lead
over Democrats than before, the Federal Election Commission says.
   The FEC said in a report released Monday that contributions to
five fund-raising committees operated by each party totaled some
$226 million during the first 18 months of the 1987-88 election
cycle.
   That was well below the $267 million the 10 committees took in
during the corresponding period in 1983-84 when Ronald Reagan was
heading for a second term as president.
   The $226 million also was about $1 million below the combined
take for the first 18 months of the 1985-86 cycle, a
non-presidential election period when contributions usually are
less than in presidential years.
   The FEC said contributions to the five GOP committees totaled
$166.19 million during the 18 months ending June 30, compared with
$59.84 million raised by the five Democratic counterparts in the
same period.
   That left the Republicans in front by $106.35 million, but their
lead was smaller than the $152.7 million bulge during the
corresponding period in 1985-86 and the $147.85 million advantage
for the first three quarters of the 1983-84 election cycle.
   The Federal Election Commission report covered the finances of
the Democratic and Republican national committees; their House and
Senate campaign committees; their national convention funds; and
their state-local finance committees.
   The Republican National Committee saw its 1987-88 receipts fall
to $61.58 million, the lowest point for a similar 18-month period
during the Reagan presidency. Corresponding figures were $64.16
million in 1985-86, $75.23 million in 1983-84 and $65.75 million in
1981-82.
   Kathryn Murray, the committee's communications director, blamed
the falloff on poor response to the GOP's direct-mail solicitations
in the first and second quarters of 1987.
   During this period, the scandals that rocked the television
evangelists hurt direct-mail appeals by the GOP and a variety of
non-political fund-raisers, according to Murray.
   She said that since then, contributions have picked up, with the
second quarter of this year running second only to a three-month
period in 1984.
   The National Republican Senatorial Committee and National
Republican Congressional Committee, which support GOP candidates in
races for Congress, also showed lower receipts in the first 18
months of this election cycle.
   The Senate committee reported contributions of $42.3 million,
down from a 1980s high of $65.81 million in 1985-86. The House
apparatus had receipts of $21.32 million, nearly half the $41.96 it
had in the first 18 months of the 1983-84 cycle.
   On the Democratic side, contributions to the five entities in
the current cycle were only about $98,000 above where they were at
the same period in the last presidential cycle.
   The Democratic National Committee, which relies less than its
Republican counterpart on direct-mail solicitations, had receipts
of $16.85 million, down from the $29.76 million taken in during
1983-84.
   This drop, however, was offset by increased giving to the
Democrats' House and Senate committees and their committees for
state and local party affairs.
   The Senate panel received $11.42 million, compared with a
previous high of $7.56 million in 1985-86. The House panel was at
$9.45 million, up from $8.74 million in 1985-86. The state-local
share was $12.64 million, compared with a previous high of $10.97
million in 1983-84.
</TEXT>
