<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     08-30 0534</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0557</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The business of the Oklahoma Legislature
has gotten in the way of Rep. Steve Lewis' honeymoon again.
   Lewis and his wife, former state Rep. Nancy Virtue, had to put
off their June honeymoon because of delays in adjournment of the
Legislature.
   They got married and re-scheduled the honeymoon to start Monday.
   But Gov. Henry Bellmon called the Legislature back into special
session Monday to solve problems with prison overcrowding.
   Lewis, the Democrat who is chairman of the House Appropriations
and Budget Committee, says the honeymoon plans are on hold again.
   ``I'm beginning to think we may have to wait for our 25th
anniversary,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>EAST LANSING, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pair of entrepreneurs turned
rejection into a profitable business venture by creating a
fraternity that anybody can join, even women, and everybody is
president.
   ``Fraternities are elitist organizations,'' said Ronald
Southwick, cofounder of Sigma Phi Nothing. ``We feel that everyone
should be special.''
   Southwick, 24, his 21-year-old partner, Joe Toth, launched Sigma
Phi Nothing after an unhappy rush week at one of Michigan State
University's fraternity houses.
   ``I got in and Joe didn't and that kind of upset us both. So I
decided not to join,'' Southwick said.
   Later, they figured, the rejection signified nothing, sparking
the Sigma Phi Nothing idea.
   So the two invented their own fraternity, created a logo, and
held a ``Don't rush, relax'' party. They brought 48 Sigma Phi
Nothing T-shirts, which quickly were sold at $10 a shirt.
   As their story spread, they sold more than 300 shirts in a few
weeks.
   Then a marketing company expressed interest in selling the
fraternity idea nationwide. The two have spent the summer
developing plans for selling the T-shirts at Big Ten schools this
fall.
   So far, the fledgling company has expanded its inventory to
include sweatshirts, corduroy caps and bumper stickers. And the
T-shirt price has risen to $11.
   The two budding businessmen, meanwhile, are taking some time off
from Michigan State to pursue their fraternity.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A current Beach Boys hit extols ``Kokomo''
as a tropical paradise, which makes sense only after you learn the
group had never heard of the land-locked Indiana city.
   Beach Boys fans looking for ``bodies in the sand'' and a
``tropical drink melting in your hand'' won't find it in the
real-life Kokomo, an auto industry town about 50 miles north of
Indianapolis.
   The Beach Boys _ Mike Love, Carl Wilson, Al Jardine and Bruce
Johnston _ performed at the Indiana State Fair on Friday night.
There, they learned Kokomo does exist somewhere else besides in
their song.
   ``Kokomo'' is one cut on the soundtrack to the Tom Cruise movie
``Cocktail.'' The soundtrack went gold last Tuesday, having sold
half a million copies. The ``Kokomo'' single, released about eight
weeks ago, is climbing the adult-contemporary chart, reaching No.
11 this week.
   The Beach Boys said they thought they were singing of a
make-believe place.
   ``It was just a made-up ... it was a nice-sounding name,'' Love
said. ``The writer is John Phillips (of Mamas and Papas fame). He
started it and it wouldn't stop; it was out of control.''
</TEXT>
