<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico-Politics, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0729,0467</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Electoral College Approves Congressional Seats</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 2 grafs with Electoral College postponing decision
on remaining lawmakers until Tuesday night. Picks up 3rd pvs, `The
Electoral ...'
^By CHRIS ANGELO</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Electoral College on Monday ended a
23-hour session by approving the last of 300 congressmen elected
directly to the Chamber of Deputies during balloting in July that
the opposition says was fraudulent.
   The body then postponed until Tuesday night its certification of
the elections of 200 other deputies assigned to the different
parties according to a proportional representation formula.
   The Electoral College, made up of the newly elected members of
the Chamber of Deputies, began its marathon session at 1 p.m.
Sunday and ended it shortly after noon Monday.
   Protests from opposition parties, accusing the governing
Institutional Revolutionary Party, known as the PRI, of fraud in
the July 6 elections, delayed the certification process.
   The delay raised the small possibility there would not be a
quorum for the opening session of Congress on Thursday and
threatened President Miguel de la Madrid's state of the nation
speech that day.
   Under the constitution, the president must attend the opening
session and by tradition that is when he delivers the state of the
nation address.
   If the PRI does not have the 251 seats for a majority in the
500-member Chamber of Deputies an opposition boycott could cancel
the session.
   The Electoral College began the certification process, seat by
seat, on Aug. 15 and in the results announed Monday the PRI won 235
of the 300 seats. The conservative National Action Party had 36 and
leftist parties backing presidential candidate Cuauhtemoc Cardenas
received 29.
   An earlier official vote count by the Federal Election
Commission gave the PRI 247 seats in the 500 member chamber and
opposition parties 227 with 26 in dispute.
   The PRI has dominated Mexican politics since 1929 and this year
for the first time it will not have the two-thirds majority
required to amend the constitution.
   Opposition parties claim the Election Commission has not
released results from about 25,000 polling places. They say those
would show that Carlos Salinas de Gortari, the PRI presidential
candidate, did not win the 50.36 percent of the vote awarded him in
official results.
   Cardenas received 31.12 percent of the vote in the official
results and Manuel J. Clouthier, the candidate of the National
Action Party, 17.07 percent.
   In early September the Electoral College of the Chamber of
Deputies is to confirm Salinas as president-elect.
   The Senate's Electoral College has finished certifying all its
members. Parties backing Cardenas won four of the 64 seats, marking
the first time the PRI had lost any seats in the upper house.
</TEXT>
