<FILEID>AP-NR-08-30-88 0220EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Burma-Chaos     08-30 0654</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Burma-Chaos,0678</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Analysts: Authorities May be Sowing Chaos to Retake Control</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENIS D. GRAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Burma's besieged government and
military may be deliberately pushing the country toward anarchy in
an attempt to reassert control after 26 years of authoritarian
rule, diplomats and other analysts say.
   Remaining silent since Aug. 19, the government has withdrawn
troops and police from the streets while looting and other crimes
reportedly go unchecked. Civilian administration has ceased to
function in many areas.
   There have been increasing reports and some witness accounts of
military agents seeking to provoke tensions. The state media has
reported nine almost simultaneous prison uprisings in widely
different areas of the country and the escape or release of nearly
9,000 inmates.
   ``My impression is it is strongly possible that this chaos is
being planned by state authorities to give them good reasons to
intervene eventually,'' said a Japanese diplomat in Rangoon, the
Burmese capital.
   However, others, also speaking on condition of anonymity,
caution that with virtually no access to the current leadership
analysts can at best make educated guesses on its intentions.
   One Western diplomat watching developments from Bangkok said the
drift towards chaos may simply reflect confusion within the
leadership coupled with an ``arrogance, an unwillingess to accept
that they have to give up.''
   ``There's an obvious vacuum with students and others trying to
find some leadership. The obvious people to step into the vacuum
are the military, conspiratorially or not,'' an Asian diplomat in
Bangkok said.
   The leadership withdrew into itself following the announcement
Aug. 19 _ after months of bloody anti-government rioting in which
hundreds were killed _ that civilian lawyer Maung Maung had
replaced the widely hated Sein Lwin as president and head of the
sole political party.
   Maung Maung's promise of a referendum on Sept. 12 that would
pave the way for democracy did not quiet the protests that have
erupted throughout Burma in the past month.
   Unsatisfied opposition leaders demanded an interim government
and the end of one-party rule. A number of Burmese and some
outsider observers believed that Ne Win, who formally retired in
late July after wielding almost absolute power for 26 years, was
still pulling strings behind the scenes along with loyal military
officers.
   Leaders have urged that demonstrations remain peaceful so the
government cannot take advantage of the turmoil.
   ``The public must be united and well disciplined ... people must
be alert to prevent machinations of destructive elements to create
anarchy in the country,'' a former defense minister, Tin Oo, told
an anti-government rally last week.
   In Rangoon and other areas, ``democracy centers'' and block
committees have replaced judicial and civil authorities to maintain
law and order.
   Whether such makeshift measures will stop the growing
lawlessness, widespread strikes, soaring commodity prices and food
shortages remains a crucial question.
   One Swedish journalist and Burma expert, Bertil Lintner, notes
that Ne Win and his military followers used the pretext of domestic
turmoil and threats to national security to seize power from a
democratic government in 1962.
   ``The government can't control the situation so they are letting
things get worse. They hope the people will beg them to come back.
It's vicious,'' Lintner said, quoting a Burmese proverb that
translates: ``If you can't eat the beef yourself, throw sand on
it.''
   One Bangkok-based diplomat said the students and other
anti-government forces might react dramatically to keep up their
hitherto remarkable momentum.
   ``The students have been the engine of change and used a lot of
imagination. But now they have to take a new initiative,'' he said.
   ``There appears to be a paralysis in the government. A hiatus
has set in and nobody knows what to do next,'' the diplomat said.
   Referring to Ne Win, he added: ``In every dictator there is an
element of contempt for the people. He can't accept that the people
no longer want him.''
</TEXT>
