<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Seals     08-30 0440</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Seals,0452</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Canine Virus Believed To Be Seal Killer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL VERSCHUUR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PIETERBUREN, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A virus common in dogs has
killed more than 11,000 seals in Western Europe's coastal waters
this summer and humans can do little to stop the spread of the
disease, a Dutch biologist says.
   Up to 80 percent of the seals in the North Sea and Kattegat
waters between Denmark and Sweden might die, Ab Osterhaus told a
news conference Monday.
   ``Canine distemper virus, or a closely related virus, is the
primary cause of the seal deaths,'' said Osterhaus in this northern
Dutch village, which has Western Europe's largest seal nursery.
   The virus causes infections of the respiratory and central
nervous systems and the digestive tracts. Osterhaus said no
specific cure exists for seals with the virus.
   Distemper may have spread to seals when one was bitten by a dog,
said Osterhaus, who works for the Dutch National Institute for
Public Health and Environmental Protection.
   Specialists in Western Europe who have been investigating the
seal deaths have speculated that pollution has played a role in the
killer epidemic.
   Osterhaus said research is still being conducted to determine if
the massive pollution of Western European waters could have
accelerated the epidemic by weakening seals' immune systems.
   ``We know that certain substances we find in the seas today ...
can affect the immune system,'' he said. ``Pollution may have
triggered the thing but it was not the cause as such.''
   Osterhaus said antibodies to canine distemper virus were found
in all of the dead seals he examined: ``The development of these
antibodies coincided clearly with the surfacing of symptoms'' of
the disease.
   A similar report was made at a news conference Monday in
Stockholm, Sweden, by patholigist Anders Bergman of Stockholm
University's veterinary school. He said he began suspecting in June
that the canine distemper virus was linked to the seal deaths.
   Bengt Klingeborn, a virologist at the veterinary school, said he
believed the 25 percent of Western European seals that have
survived so far will live through the epidemic because they have
developed antibodies.
   Osterhaus noted that there had been an outbreak of the canine
distemper virus among dogs in Greenland shortly before the epidemic
broke out among seals early this year. Each summer, thousands of
seals migrate from Greenland to Western European waters.
   Osterhaus said his team had developed an experimental vaccine
against the canine distemper virus but added ``it will not be
possible to carry out preventive vaccinations in the wild.''
   Sweden has reported 3,400 dead seals, Denmark nearly 3,000, West
Germany 3,900, Norway 600 and the Netherlands 175.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
