<1ST_LINE>r i PM-CantoneseHoods     08-30 0363</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cantonese Hoods,0374</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report: Young Toughs Abound In Canton</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gangs of high school students are roving the
industrial city of Canton, committing an increasing number of
violent crimes, an official newspaper reported today.
   The Legal Daily (Fazhi Ribao) said students have murdered,
raped, robbed and are ``imitating feudal and underworld practices
by forming illegal gangs.''
   In another story, the paper called on the police to protect
railway passengers from bands of teen-agers who raid trains and
steal food and luggage.
   ``Let's deal with these little railroad guerrilla bands,'' the
paper said.
   Although the report on Canton did not say how many crimes had
been committed by the young hoodlums, it did say that 769 students
were convicted of violent crimes last year, a 78.4 percent increase
over 1986.
   The paper said the students took to a life of crime mainly
because they didn't have sufficient political education.
   ``Some teachers these days are more willing to give three
classes in math and literature than one class in political
studies,'' the paper quoted one school principal as saying.
   The paper also said pornographic and violence-oriented
literature and videocassettes were to blame for encouraging
students to break the law.
   In addition, it said an increasing number of students are
leaving school early to work. The paper said the dropouts exert a
bad influence on their friends still in school.
   China is in the midst of economic reforms that are transforming
the social stucture of the nation. Violent crime, especially
robbery, and corruption have risen dramatically in the past few
years. Canton, because it is in the forefront of the reforms, is
changing most rapidly.
   In the report on the ``railroad guerrillas,'' the paper related
an incident that occurred on June 19 as a train entered a station
in Hunan province.
   ``Several dozen youngster ran to the train and began walking by
the windows, occasionally looking in,'' the report said.
   ``Just as the train began moving, these children shoved their
hands in the windows and grabbed food, beer bottles, cans, luggage
and then fled with the goods.''
   Said the report: ``All the victims could do was curse.''
</TEXT>
