<HEAD>Stocks, Dollar Rise On Tokyo Exchange</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices rose moderately on the Tokyo Stock
Exchange Tuesday, while the dollar inched up against the Japanese
yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, a 299.81-point
loser Monday, rebounded to close Tuesday's trading at 27,511.65.
The market's main barometer erased marginal early losses and added
132.55 points or 0.48 percent.
   The dollar, which opened at 134.57 yen, closed at 134.39, up
0.19 yen from Monday's close of 134.20 yen. It ranged between
134.30 and 134.60 yen.
   Stock market participants were continuing to stay on the
sidelines amid lackluster trading, according to an analyst with a
major securities firm in Tokyo.
   ``Because investors were still in a wait-and-see mood, trading
was thin,'' he said on condition of anonymity. ``Any notable change
is unlikely before the scheduled U.S. report on employment figures
Friday.''
   He said investors were also acting cautiously ahead of the Tokyo
Stock Exchange's plans to begin a new system of forward
transactions. Press reports have said the new system will begin
Sept. 3 and offer investors opportunities to earn profit with less
risk.
