<HEAD>Reagan Appoints Two To Short Terms On Labor Relations Board</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan appointed two men to the
National Labor Relations Board, including one opposed by
right-to-work advocates.
   The appointments, because they were made while Congress is not
in session, do not require congressional approval but will be
effective only until January 1990, when the next session of
Congress ends.
   Reagan on Monday reappointed Wilford W. Johansen, a board member
since 1985 and formerly head of the NLRB's regional office in Los
Angeles, and John E. Higgins Jr., 48, NLRB deputy general counsel.
   Reagan had nominated Higgins last February, but opposition from
Sen. Jesse Helms had stalled the nomination.
   Right-to-work leaders opposed Higgins because of his office's
approval in 1986 of a contract between General Motors and the
United Auto Workers to use UAW members as the chief source of
workers for GM's new Saturn auto plant in Tennessee.
