<HEAD>Labor Department: One in Four Workers is College Grad</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of every four U.S. workers is now a
college graduate, compared with just one in every five 10 years
ago, the Labor Department says.
   An additional 20 percent, up from 16 percent a decade ago, have
completed one to three years of college, according to a report
released Monday by the Bureau of Labor Statistics.
   At the same time, the proportion of workers without a high
school diploma has declined from 24 percent in 1978 to 15 percent
today, the report says. The share of the work force ending their
formal education at the completion of high school is reported
unchanged at 40 percent.
   While differences in the proportion of college graduates still
exist among whites, blacks and Hispanics, all three groups have
shown significant increases in the past 10 years, the bureau says.
</TEXT>
