<2ND_LINE>PM-Korea-Journalist,0227</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Intelligence Generals Arrested In Knifing Of Journalist</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Military authorities said today that
two army intelligence generals were arrested for alleged roles in a
knife attack on a journalist critical of what he called military
dominance in South Korea.
   Two brigadier generals _ Lee Kyu-hong and Kwon Ki-dae _ from the
Army Intelligence Command were imprisoned and charged with
instigating the Aug. 7 attack on Oh Hong-kun, city editor of the
Joong-Ang Economic News, according to military officials.
   A major and three non-commissioned officers of the intelligence
command also were arrested for allegedly slashing Oh's thigh with
knives.
   The four soldiers admitted to attacking Oh in retaliation for
articles he wrote criticizing the military as blocking democratic
development, according to military officials, who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   They said several other intelligence officers have been
questioned to determine whether they were involved. Those
questioned included Maj. Gen. Lee Jin-baek, who headed the
intelligence command, according to the officials.
   The military at first denied soldiers were involved in the
attack, but pressure from the opposition forced the government to
order an investigation.
   The opposition has demanded that all military personnel linked
to the case be punished, saying it indicates a hard-line trend
against dissent among government officials and the army.
</TEXT>
