<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0238</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Rises Slightly, Stocks Rise In Tokyo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar inched higher against the Japanese yen
in Tokyo today, while stock regained some of their lost ground.
   After opening at 134.57 yen, the dollar edged down in moderate
trading but closed at 134.39 yen, up 0.19 yen from Monday's finish.
The U.S. currency stayed within a narrow range between 134.30 yen
and 134.60 yen, with spot volume estimated at $4.8 billion.
   Traders said the dollar held strong as Japanese life insurance
companies, investment trusts and securities firms bought the U.S.
currency.
   However, after it hit 134.60 yen, the currency started inching
down when institutional investors and exporters sold dollars in
profit-taking, they said.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues reversed a morning decline and recouped 132.55
points, or 0.48 percent, closing at 27,511.65. During the morning
session, the index lost 57.63 points.
   Although trading on the market's first section was estimated at
a sparse 450 million shares due to a wait-and-see mood still
remaining in the market, prices recovered gradually toward the end
of the day, said Yoshio Shimoyama of Nikko Securities Co.
   ``Some investors finally tried to test the water and began
buying in the afternoon session. I guess they'd been a little too
cautious,'' he said.
   Among the issues that attracted investors were steels and oil
issues.
</TEXT>
