<HEAD>Dollar Mostly Higher, Gold Falls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar inched up against most foreign
currencies in early European trading today, but exchange dealers
predicted gains would be limited by fears of central bank
intervention and a lack of market-affecting news.
   Gold prices fell.
   ``After last week's activity, this is going to be a week of
consolidation,'' said Derek Walker, treasury economist at Midland
Bank in London.
   The dollar fell last week following interest rate hikes in
several European countries and heavy central bank intervention.
   Traders in Rome said they were looking ahead to important
economic indicators due out later in the week to suggest what the
dollar's near-term trend might be, in particular, U.S. August
unemployment figures to be released Friday.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends as Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose 0.19 yen to a closing 134.39. Later, in London, it
was quoted at 134.45 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Monday:
   _1.8707 West German marks, up from 1.8693
   _1.5775 Swiss francs, up from 1.5772
   _6.3505 French francs, up from 6.3500
   _2.1124 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1120
   _1,390.45 Italian lire, up from 1,389.50
   _1.2405 Canadian dollars, up from 1.23935
   In London, one British pound cost $1.685, slightly more
expensive for buyers than $1.684 dollars quoted in Europe late
Monday. London's financial markets were closed Monday for a bank
holiday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $429.70 a troy ounce,
down from $431.40 bid late Friday, prior to the three-day holiday
weekend. At midmorning, the city's five major bullion dealers fixed
a recommended price of $429.40.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $428, down from $432 dollars bid
late Monday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $2.68 an ounce from Friday to
close at a bid $432.56. Hong Kong's financial markets were also
closed Monday for a national holiday.
   Silver was quoted in London Monday at a bid $6.53 a troy ounce,
down from Friday's $6.64.
