<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Continental-BlackBox     08-30 0437</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Continental-Black Box,0453</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Recording Reveals Joking, No Snowfall Discussion Prior To Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A ``black box'' tape recording from an ill-fated
Continental Airlines flight shows the pilots joked about a flight
attendant's dating habits but failed to discuss the falling snow
before the jet crashed, killing 28 people, a newspaper reported.
   In the nearly three minutes of pilot conversation omitted from a
National Transportation Safety Board transcript released earlier,
discussion between the pilot and co-pilot centered around whether a
woman flight attendant dated pilots, the Denver Post reported today.
   There was no discussion about de-icing the jet or of the snow
falling at Stapleton International Airport in the minutes before
the Nov. 15, 1987, crash, the newspaper said.
   The Union of Flight Attendants has filed a statement with the
transportation board, saying the tape shows the pilots discussing
``unnecessary and unprofessional topics.''
   But Continental spokesman Bruce Hicks said Monday the black-box
recording shows the pilots operated a ``highly skilled,
well-disciplined, professional cockpit.''
   Continental, he added, agreed with the transportation board that
the unreleased section of tape was not pertinent to the accident
investigation.
   The fact that the pilots didn't comment on the snow indicates
they didn't feel it was a problem, Hicks said.
   ``What it means is that they were human beings who had some
conversations,'' he said. ``But at no point did they neglect their
duties. ... Pilots aren't robots.''
   Transportation officials are investigating the possibility that
the DC-9's wings were not adequately de-iced prior to takeoff.
   The board also is studying the experience level of the pilots,
who both died in the crash, and turbulence from a plane landing on
the next runway as possible causes of the crash.
   The recording shows the plane taxied into position near the end
of the runway and was prepared to take off at 2:05 p.m.
   In the minutes that followed, there was confusion in the
Stapleton control tower about the identity of Flight 1713, and the
tower cleared another plane to take off first.
   In the conversation between pilots that followed, the newspaper
said Frank Zvonek, the 43-year-old captain, mentioned a flight
attendant.
   ``She said she doesn't date pilots,'' Zvonek was quoted as
saying. ``She doesn't go for one-night stands.''
   Co-pilot Lee Edward Bruecher, 26, reportedly asked, ``How come
she doesn't date pilots? Is it the same reason why I don't date
flight attendants? ... (laughter)
   ``She seems real nice.''
   Minutes later, Flight 1713 was cleared for takeoff and began
rolling down the runway. At 2:15 p.m., the plane climbed into the
air.
   Ten seconds later, Bruecher shouted an obscenity. The DC-9
flipped and crashed.
</TEXT>
