<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FinancialFlight     08-30 0309</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Financial Flight,0318</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fugitive Financial Planner Charged With Embezzlement, Mail Fraud</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fugitive financial planner who sent notes of
apology to his clients after he allegedly stole $25 million of
their funds has been charged with embezzlement and mail fraud.
   Complaints filed Monday in U.S. District Court allege that Henry
Gherman, 52, masterminded a 10-year scheme that may have swindled
nearly 50 investors, said U.S. Attorney Dexter Lehtinen.
   Authorities do not know where Gherman is hiding, Miami FBI
spokesman Paul Miller said. He did not reveal his location in
telephone calls to his wife and her attorney.
   Gherman is accused of illegally transferring clients' money to a
Miami bank account since 1978 and issuing false statements
indicating investments in money-market funds and certificates of
deposit, said a statement by Lehtinen and FBI agent William Wells.
   The federal complaints cite five counts of embezzlement and two
counts of mail fraud, Lehtinen said, adding other charges were
possible. The case could be brought before a federal grand jury
next month, he said.
   Gherman faces 35 years in prison and fines in excess of $1.5
million if convicted on all counts, Lehtinen said.
   Gherman had a ``longstanding pattern of embezzlement'' from
about 25 professional associations handling pension funds and other
assets for members, Lehtinen said. Gherman's scheme could have
affected nearly 50 investors, ranging from prominent Miami Beach
doctors and smaller investors such as clerks and nurses.
   Gherman sent hand-written notes of apology to his clients Aug.
10 when he dropped out of sight.
   Larry Torrence, assistant special agent for the FBI, said most
of the clients' losses were not insured.
   Torrence said Gherman is the only defendant in the case, but
``that could change'' as the probe continues.
   A group of Gherman's former clients has filed a lawsuit in Dade
Circuit Court seeking return of their money.
</TEXT>
