<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BirthControlSentence     08-30 0295</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Birth Control Sentence,0305</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mother Ordered To Practice Birth Control Is Pregnant, Lawyer Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A teen-age mother of three ordered by a judge to
practice birth control for the rest of her child-bearing years
after she abandoned her sons for three days is expecting another
child, her attorney said.
   Debra Ann Forster, 18, was sentenced by Judge Linsay Ellis
Budzyn in May to lifetime probation and ordered to use birth
control after pleading guilty to two counts of attempted child
abuse.
   Ms. Forster was charged after she left her sons, William, then
18 months old, and Scott, then 6 months old, alone for three days
in a Mesa apartment in May 1987.
   Garrett Simpson, a deputy public defender representing Ms.
Forster, said Monday that Ms. Forster's pregnancy was confirmed
early last week when she went to St. Joseph's Hospital and Medical
Center for a pregnancy test. The baby is due in April, he said.
   Simpson refused to say whether Forster was practicing any form
of birth control when she became pregnant.
   He asked Ms. Budzyn whether abortion is a form of birth control
and whether Ms. Forster should obtain one to abide by the terms of
her probation.
   The judge said that she ``would never make such a ruling.''
   Ms. Budzyn also said that because no birth-control device is
``100 percent foolproof,'' she will not revoke Forster's lifetime
probation.
   ``I'm not going to send her to prison because she is pregnant,''
she said.
   Ms. Forster had a third child, a daughter, while awaiting trial
this year. The girl has since been adopted, according to court
records.
   The two boys were placed in foster homes and court records show
that Ms. Forster signed papers allowing the children to be offered
for adoption.
</TEXT>
