<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel     08-30 0559</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel,0577</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Infiltration Attempt Foiled, Four Arabs Wounded</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN IZENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lebanese Christian villagers joined by Israeli
troops today blocked a guerrilla squad trying to infiltrate Israel
from south Lebanon and at least one guerrilla was wounded, Israel
radio said.
   It was the first time Israel has reported that Lebanese
villagers helped thwart a border crossing. The infiltration attempt
was the 17th since the Palestinian uprising broke out in
Israeli-occupied territories almost nine months ago.
   In the West Bank and Gaza Strip, Palestinians went on strike to
protest the planned deportation of 25 fellow Arabs.
   Israeli troops shot and wounded four Palestinians in the West
Bank city of Nablus during a protest, hospital officials said. The
army said it was checking the report.
   Israel radio said the attempted infiltration today occurred near
the village of Khalata, about 2{ miles north of the Israeli border.
   It said a villager spotted the guerrilla squad walking out of a
ravine and moving across a field near the village. The villagers
alerted others and 10 Lebanese men armed themselves and stopped the
squad, it said.
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin, speaking on the radio, said the
Israeli-backed South Lebanon Army initially encountered the
guerrillas.
   ``The IDF (Israeli Defense Forces) soldiers joined them,'' he
said. ``To the best of my knowledge, there were no people wounded
on our side.''
   Israel ended a three-year occupation of Lebanon in the summer of
1985, but maintains about 1,000 soldiers in a self-declared
security zone to back up the mostly Christian South Lebanon Army.
   In other developments, the Supreme Court turned down two appeals
by Faisal Husseini, head of the banned Arab Studies Center, to open
his court hearings to the public and to make secret prosecution
documents available to his attorneys.
   Husseini, whose case is currently before the Jerusalem District
Court, is being held for the third time under emergency regulations
which permit detention for up to six months without trial.
   The United States has called on Israel either to release
Husseini or bring him to trial. Israel maintains Husseini is a key
Palestine Liberation Organization leader in the occupied
territories.
   At the Jneid Prison near Nablus, a military appeals board today
began a closed hearing on the appeals of 15 Palestinians slated for
deportation. Another 10 face deportation orders.
   Thirty-three Arabs have been expelled since the ``intefadah,''
or uprising, began. During that time 255 Palestinian have been
killed, most of them by army gunfire. Four Israelis also have died.
   Curfews were in effect today on the Jabaliya, Bureij and
Nusseirat refugee camps in Gaza.
   A military spokesman said the curfews were ``preventive
measures'' because previous general strikes _ a main tactic of
resistance _ had triggered violent protests in the camps.
   In Nablus, the largest city in the West Bank with over 100,000
residents, the army lifted a five-day curfew but streets remained
deserted because of the general strike. Outlawed Palestinian flags
flew from the city's largest mosque and others were draped on
electricity poles.
   Jewish settlers in the occupied territories, meanwhile,
complained angrily after police confiscated a handgun from a
settler at Kedummim, near Nablus.
   The settler, Eliezer Shochat, fired in the direction of
Palestinian youths who stoned his car Sunday in the West Bank.
Israel radio reported Shochat may have hit two Palestinians and
said police were investigating.
</TEXT>
