<1ST_LINE>r a PM-InformantShot     08-30 0338</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Informant Shot,0346</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reputed Gambino Associate Killed Outside Home</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A reputed member of the Gambino crime family who
reportedly served as a government informant for years was killed
outside his Brooklyn home.
   ``I think his days were numbered from the day'' his informer
status was made public in March 1985, said a federal source who
spoke on the condition his identity not be revealed.
   The victim, Wilfred (``Willie Boy'') Johnson, was a co-defendant
in a racketeering trial at which he and John Gotti, reputed head of
the Gambino family, were acquitted in April 1987.
   An FBI agent testified in court that Gotti's faction had put out
a murder contract on Johnson.
   Johnson, 53, was shot several times, including in the back of
the head, with a .380-caliber automatic shortly after 6 a.m.
Monday, said Detective Louis Llanes, a police spokesman. Several
spent shells were found between Johnson's home and his car, which
was parked a block away.
   ``I don't think there was any doubt that it was
Gotti-sanctioned,'' said the source. ``One bullet in the head would
have done the job, the 13 other ones were meant as a message.''
   The government said Johnson, whose criminal record dated to
1952, had been jailed for 18 months before the trial for his own
safety because he had been on the FBI payroll from 1966 to 1974 and
then resumed working as an unpaid snitch in 1980.
   A prosecutor said in court papers that Johnson had passed the
FBI details of the Gambino family hierarchy and its activities in
gambling, loansharking, hijacking and murder.
   But his lawyer, Richard Rehbock, denied that Johnson was ever an
informant and said he was denied bail in an unsuccessful government
attempt to make him cooperate and discredit him with his
co-defendants.
   Prosecutors offered Johnson a place in the federal witness
protection program before his informer status was revealed, but
Johnson refused, saying he would never testify against his
associates, according to court documents.
</TEXT>
