<FILEID>AP-NR-08-30-88 0856EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-Shepard     08-30 0195</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Shepard,0199</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Actor-Playwright Makes Feature Film Directing Debut</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pulitzer Prize-winning playwright Sam Shepard
says he learned to direct his first feature film the way he learned
everything else: just doing it.
   ``You can study things until they're over the hill _ read a lot
of books, see a lot of films,'' Shepard says in the September issue
of Vogue. ``But the only way to learn something is simply to do it.
Just step across the fence.''
   Shepard has acted in several films but ``Far North,'' due out
next month, is his first directorial effort. It stars Jessica
Lange, his live-in lover, and was shot entirely in northern
Minnesota, where she was born and grew up.
   Shepard, whose plays include the 1979 Pulitzer Prize-winning
``Buried Child,'' ``True West,'' ``Fool for Love'' and ``A Lie of
the Mind,'' says he doesn't get very excited about acting.
   ``But filmmaking I can get passionate about because it's a
natural extension of writing,'' he said. ``It's everything you wish
writing could be: you can visualize things, and there they are; you
can extend shots, change the colors, put wind in when the wind
isn't there.''
</TEXT>
