<FILEID>AP-NR-08-30-88 0901EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Lebanon-Hostages     08-30 0407</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon-Hostages,0420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bishop Meets With Sunni Cleric In Effort To Free Hostages</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA ABU-NASR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Church of England bishop met today with
Hassan Khaled, spiritual leader of Lebanon's Sunni Moslems, as part
of an effort to free foreigners held captive by Moslem extremists.
   The Right Rev. John Brown, bishop of the Persian Gulf and
Cyprus, arrived in Christian east Beirut on Sunday seeking word on
the fate of four missing Iranians. He had been in Tehran earlier
this month.
   Iranians leaders have said they will use their influence with
Shiite Moslems holding hostages in Lebanon to free their captives
if the Church of England helps determine what happened to the
Iranians, who disappeared in Christian Lebanese territory six years
ago.
   Four Britons are missing in Lebanon, along with nine Americans,
an Indian, an Italian, a West German and two unidentified
foreigners. Most are believed held by Shiite groups.
   Brown, who is based in Cyprus, said he was very optimistic about
the progress of his discussions in Beirut.
   ``It's just a feeling, but we're optimistic,'' he told reporters
after a 45-minute meeting with Hassan. Brown declined to elaborate.
   It was Brown's second visit to Lebanon in a month as
representative of Archbishop of Canterbury Robert Runcie, primate
of the Church of England.
   The Iranians disappeared while driving in the Christian
heartland north of Beirut after the Israeli army invaded Lebanon in
June 1982. They were presumed to have been kidnapped, but there was
no claim of responsibility. There have been unconfirmed reports
they were killed.
   Brown was asked if Iran would keep its promise to help free the
foreign hostages if he received confirmation the four Iranians are
dead.
   ``I simply don't know what effect it will have on the government
because I'm not a government man. I'm a churchman,'' Brown replied.
   Brown, who speaks Arabic, also sought word on the Iranians' fate
Sunday when he met with Mar Nasrallah Butros Sfeir, spiritual head
of Lebanon's Maronite Catholics.
   Brown said he had some leads, but declined to give any details.
   In a telephone interview Monday, Brown predicted Anglican Church
envoy Terry Waite, missing since Jan. 20, 1987, will be released.
Brown stressed he did not know when, however, and declined to
elaborate.
   Waite disappeared after leaving his west Beirut hotel for a
meeting with Islamic Jihad, a pro-Iranian Shiite faction that holds
two Americans, Terry Anderson and Thomas Sutherland.
</TEXT>
