<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--MissLiberty     08-30 0182</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Miss Liberty,0186</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Statue Of Liberty Replica To Be Moved</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BIRMINGHAM, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Miss Liberty, the largest replica in the
United States of the Statue of Liberty, will come down from her
rooftop perch and hit the road for a July 4, 1989, celebration.
   ``An additional 8 million people a year will see the statue,''
said John S.P. Samford, president of Liberty National, a subsidiary
of Torchmark Corp., an insurance and financial services company.
   The statue has stood atop the Liberty National Life Insurance
Co. headquarters in downtown Birmingham for 30 years.
   The statue will be moved to a six-acre site near Interstate 459
just south of Birmingham.
   Miss Liberty's new site will include a large viewing plaza and a
grassy slope suitable for picnics. The statue will be placed on a
granite pedestal 61 feet tall, which will sit in the center of the
plaza.
   At 31 feet tall and 20,000 pounds, Miss Liberty is one-fifth the
size of the Statue of Liberty in New York harbor. Like the original
Statue of Liberty, the replica was cast in France.
</TEXT>
