<1ST_LINE>r i PM-DirtyWarOrphan 2ndLd-Writethru   08-30 0486</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dirty War Orphan, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0490,0496</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Drama Reminiscent of ``The Official Story'' Played Out</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS name of Buenos Aires suburb to Moron, graf 3. Picks
up graf 4 pvs, `Jose and ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VICENTE LOPEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 10-year-old daughter of a
couple presumed killed by security forces during Argentina's
``dirty war'' was ordered taken from her natural grandparents and
returned to her adoptive parents.
   Federal Judge Alfredo Sanudo, who handed down the decision,
``doesn't deserve to live,'' said Ruben Fontana, Juliana's maternal
grandfather.
   Fontana vowed to appeal the order, issued Monday in a
closed-door hearing in the Buenos Aires suburb of Moron.
   Jose and Carmen Trevino adopted the dark, chubby-cheeked Juliana
after she was found as an infant in the doorway of a building and
taken to an orphanage. They did not comment on the ruling to
reporters outside the courtroom.
   The ``Juliana Case,'' as it is called in South America, is
reminiscent of ``The Official Story,'' the Oscar-winning 1985
Argentine film about a family that adopts the child of a woman
killed by security forces.
   In the 1970s, at least 9,000 people vanished in Argentina and
were presumed abducted and killed by security agents in the ``dirty
war,'' which was ordered by the military dictatorship to quell the
leftist opposition. Several military leaders have been tried,
convicted and sentenced for their role in the terror.
   The Trevinos _ unlike other families who didn't question where
their children came from _ adopted Juliana legally, told her she
was adopted, and tried for years to track down her biological
parents.
   Jose Trevino, a journalist, recently told The Associated Press:
   ``From the first moment, we told Juliana she was adopted .... If
her real parents appeared, my wife and I told ourselves we would
rip up the documents'' and return the child.
   The Trevinos brought Juliana to the attention of her natural
grandparents earlier this year, when they gave a sample of her
blood to a clinic set up to match children with parents who had
``disappeared.''
   The blood sample proved Juliana was the daughter of Pedro Fabian
Sandoval and Liliana Fontana _ who was pregnant when the couple was
arrested on July 1, 1977 _ and the granddaughter of Ruben and
Clelia Fontana.
   On June 23, the day the Trevinos received the news from the
blood bank, they were ordered to appear in court. Former Federal
Judge Juan Ramos Padilla gave them two choices: return Juliana to
her grandparents, or give her to a foster home.
   The Trevinos chose the former, but filed an appeal arguing that
they had followed the legal requirements to adopt Juliana and were
better suited to care for her than the grandparents.
   Sanudo, who replaced Ramos Padilla after the latter retired,
overturned his predecessor's ruling.
   The military, which staged a 1976 coup, turned over power to
elected civilian President Raul Alfonsin in 1983.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880830-0051 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-30-88 0936EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Burma     08-30 0523</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Burma,0541</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Appeals For End of Rail Strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SEIN WIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government appealed to Buddhist monks
and the public today to help end a five-day-old railway strike that
has paralyzed transportation nationwide.
   ``The stoppage of rail service, which is the cheapest mode of
transportation, has caused hardship to the people and also caused
the price of food to spiral,'' state-run Rangoon radio said.
   ``The government, therefore, appealed to the Buddhist monks and
the public to help solve the rail transportation problem,'' the
brief broadcast said.
   Monks are an influential element of Burmese society. They and
activist students have been in the vanguard of mass pro-democracy
demonstrations that began July 23 when 77-year-old Ne Win resigned
after 26 years of authoritarian rule and was replaced by hardliner
Sein Lwin.
   The nation's railroad workers went on strike last Friday,
shutting down the most affordable form of long-distance
transportation and making it difficult to move food into the cities.
   Union Burma Airways suspended all domestic and international
operations, and bus service was severely reduced. Private buses
have since raised their fares from 8 to 50.
   Strikes also closed oil refineries in Syriam across the Rangoon
River and in Mann in central Burma, crippled most factories of the
Industries Ministry and left foreign ships waiting at Rangoon port,
officials said.
   Gasoline became scarce and its price soared. With most gas
stations closed, the black market price rose from about $4.17 to
$16.67 per gallon.
   That sent people running to buy bicycles, which were selling
today at 15 percent above their normal price.
   Bicycles imported from Thailand and China sell for about
$600-$700 in Burma. Those produced at government-run factories sell
for about $133 but are in short supply, and today the black market
price jumped to $416.
   As part of Burma's continuing turmoil, student leaders on Sunday
announced the formation of a student union. On Monday, dock workers
said they too had formed a union and 21 elder statesmen announced
formation of a Committee for Democracy.
   After Ne Win led the 1962 military coup that ended Burma's
experiment with democracy, he outlawed all political parties,
unions and associations except for the ruling Burma Socialist
Program party. The unions and the new Committee for Democracy are
illegal under Burma's present constitution.
   Burma's leadership disintegrated following the Aug. 19
announcement that civilian lawyer Maung Maung had replaced the
hated Sein Lwin as president and head of the sole political party.
   Maung Maung's promise of a referendum Sept. 12 that would pave
the way for democracy did not quiet the demonstrations, in which
hundreds of people have died in the past month.
   Reports reaching Rangoon Monday said the governments of at least
eight cities have stopped operating and Buddhist monks, residents
and some striking policemen have organized protection of their
neighborhoods. The reports said many offices of the Socialist
Program Party were closed, while some were destroyed by protesters.
   The cities included Mandalay, Sagaing, Monywa, Minbu and Magwe
in northern Burma, Taunggyi in Shan State, Moulmein in Mon State
and Bassein in the Irrawaddy Delta. The reports gave no details.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
