<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0439,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Seeking To End Talk of Stalled Campaign</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 7 grafs new with morning event; pick up 4th graf pvs bgng
``For Dukakis...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis today countered George
Bush's criticism of him on defense issues and said the next
president can't have it all if he's serious about erasing the
federal deficit.
   The Democratic nominee also hinted he was approaching the point
at which he would respond more aggressively to Republican attacks,
saying it would be ``unfortunate'' but necessary to reshape the
election debate.
   Dukakis, meeting with western Massachusetts editors on the final
day of a two-day visit to the region, fired back quickly when asked
about Bush's assertions that Dukakis would endanger national
security because of his foreign policy inexperience.
   ``Mr. Bush says he wants them all,'' Dukakis said after listing
his opposition to building MX missiles on railroad cars, two new
supercarrier task forces and deploying the Star Wars space defense
system.
   ``You can't have them all,'' Dukakis said. ``Not if you're
serious about providing the resources our conventional forces need
and not if you're serious about getting that deficit down.''
   Dukakis, who has been trying to dispel talk that his campaign
has stagnated, has blamed such talk on the media attention given to
Bush and his running mate, Indiana Sen. Dan Quayle, following the
Republican convention and to reports about unsubstantiated rumors
about Dukakis and his wife.
   ``If it continues you have to respond,'' he said. ``I think
that's unfortunate but I think it's very clear what kind of a
campaign the Republicans are running and I think we're going to
have to deal with it.''
   For Dukakis, Monday was a bizarre day in which he first canceled
a news conference after aides complained network television was
ignoring his speeches but later met with reporters armed with
questions about whether his campaign was in a state of confusion.
   ``Back by popular demand,'' he joked as he walked into a
rescheduled news conference.
   The confusion comes at a time when many Democratic strategists
inside and outside the Dukakis campaign are concerned that Dukakis
has allowed Bush to seize control of the debate with attacks on the
Democrat's patriotism, views on defense and gun control and the
furlough program.
   Dukakis told reporters he was ``trying to get this campaign up
where it belongs'' by discussing his economic positions. He came to
western Massachusetts to highlight that region's economic
resurgence.
   The governor said face-to-face debates were the best place to
respond to Bush's attacks but then offered a preview by countering
the vice president's attacks on the furlough program, which until
amended last year extended eligibility to first-degree murderers.
   Dukakis said he wanted to ask Bush about the 16,000 furloughs
granted to federal prisoners last year, ``some lasting 45 days and
many to convicted drug pushers Mr. Bush says he wants to execute.''
   In a speech before the news conference, Dukakis also attacked
Bush's support for a reduction in the capital gains tax.
   ``We're not going to accept Mr. Bush's suggestion that the way
to build opportunity for our citizens is to cut taxes for the
wealthy again, this time with a $40 billion handout, 70 percent of
which would go to those making $200,000 a year or more,'' he said.
   Dukakis also called for an end to questions about Quayle's
military and academic records in favor of issues-related media
coverage.
   ``Let's put the last few weeks behind us,'' Dukakis said. ``The
dog days of August are almost over. The curtain is going up on the
greatest exercise of political freedom the world has ever known.''
   Dukakis said time was too short to engage in personal attacks.
   ``Ten weeks from tomorrow, America will choose a new
president,'' he said. ``The campaign is a golden and historic
moment to define our nation's future. My friends, let us not waste
this opportunity.
   ``Because the issue in this campaign is not how well Mr. Bush
did one night in New Orleans or how well I did one night in Atlanta.
   ``The issue is not whose speechwriter should get an Emmy. The
issue is whose values should get into the White House.
   ``The American people aren't interested in the grades that some
of us might have gotten while we were in college; they care about
whether their children will have the chance to go to college.''
</TEXT>
