<HEAD>29 Arrested For Giving Free Beans, Melons To Homeless</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to move up reference to charges and detail
specific charges; Picks up 6th graf, ``We don't ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ANTHONY MARQUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twenty-nine people arrested while trying to
give food to homeless people in Golden Gate Park chanted ``arrest
hunger, not free food'' as police led them away.
   Police cited the activists for illegal distribution of food,
demonstrating and leafleting without a permit and creating a public
nuisance.
   ``By sending the police here, the mayor's saying it's illegal to
feed people,'' said Stephanie Hedgecoke, an organizer for a group
called ``All Peoples Congress.''
   The arrests were made Monday after about 100 members of the
group called ``Food Not Bombs'' marched through the Haight-Ashbury
district to the park, carrying boxes of food, chanting slogans and
banging pots and pans.
   When they reached the corner of the park just before noon, the
members began to set up two tables with plates of beans, melons and
other food.
   About 50 police officers, half clad in riot gear, surrounded the
group and arrested members after issuing a warning.
   ``We don't want to have a confrontation,'' said Keith McHenry,
spokesman for Food Not Bombs. ``We have been doing this for eight
years in other cities.''
   McHenry, who was also arrested, said his group supported
diverting funds for military arms to humanitarian causes.
   ``Our political message is that money should be spent on food
and housing,'' he said.
   The city had warned group members they would be arrested if they
attempted to give away food in the park, something they had done
for several months. The group said the police crackdown was the
result of complaints from local businesses.
   One resident who watched the arrests said she was disgusted by
the police action.
   ``As a citizen of the city, I was offended that this was going
on in my neighborhood,'' said Marjorie Antenore, a teacher and
12-year resident of the neighborhood. ``I was shocked by the
attitude and the riot gear.''
   The mayor's office did not return telephone calls for comment.
</TEXT>
