<FILEID>AP-NR-08-30-88 1026EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-UN-WesternSahara     08-30 0502</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UN-Western Sahara,0521</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Polisario, Morocco Agree Conditionally To U.N. Peace Plan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Morocco and the Polisario guerrillas said today
they had agreed conditionally to a U.N. peace plan aimed at ending
their 13-year conflict in the Western Sahara.
   U.N. spokesman Francois Giuliani said both sides ``accepted with
remarks and comments'' the Aug. 11 peace plan for a cease-fire and
a U.N.-monitored referendum in the phosphate-rich desert territory.
The text of the proposal has not been made public.
   The Marxist-led Polisario has fought for Western Sahara's
independence since 1975, when Spain's colonial forces gave up the
northwest African territory and Morocco annexed it.
   Algeria has backed Polisario's campaign, but Morocco and Algeria
restored diplomatic relations in May after years of tension verging
on war over the territory.
   In Madrid, Spanish Foreign Minister Francisco Fernandez Ordonez
told Spanish National Radio Spain that he viewed as ``very good
news'' the announcement.
   ``We expect this process to lead to the establishment of peace
and prosperity in this region of great importance to Spain,'' the
minister said.
   Giuliani said Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar expects
to begin a U.N. peacekeeping operation in the Western Sahara before
the end of the year. The U.N. is considering sending about 2,000
peacekeeping troops to the remote, sparsely populated territory,
authorities say.
   Perez de Cuellar will also be appointing a special
representative to supervise the peace process, Giuliani told
reporters.
   ``Through the two replies, the conflict in the Western Sahara
enters a new phase, with difficulties still to be settled,''
Polisario delegation leader Bechir Mustapha said.
   ``We have accepted with certain conditions,'' Mustapha added.
   Moroccan Foreign Minister Abdellatif El-Falali said there ``is
an accord in principle to work together with the secretary-general
for the implementation of his proposals.''
   ``A referendum can be held in the relatively near future,'' the
foreign minister said.
   Announcement of the tentative agreement followed last-minute
meetings between Perez de Cuellar and the two sides. Their deadline
for submitting responses to the peace plan was Thursday.
   Perez de Cuellar's detailed proposals included a cease-fire and
a referendum calling for the region's independence or affiliation
with another nation, most likely Morocco.
   Western Sahara covers about 110,000 square miles but had only
about 76,000 inhabitants in the last Spanish census in 1975. Most
of its people have fled to Moroccan-held cities or to refugee camps
around the Algerian oasis of Tindouf.
   The major remaining dispute now likely is to be over who has the
right to vote in a referendum.
   Polisario claims about 165,000 Western Saharans live around the
Tindouf oasis, but Morocco says most of them are not Western
Saharans.
   Polisario also claims that two-thirds of the 150,000 inhabitants
of the Moroccan-held areas are immigrants not eligible to vote, but
Morocco claims 90 percent of them are Western Saharans.
   Morocco's army has kept Polisario from major gains, mainly by
building a series of defensive walls in the desert. But King Hassan
II's war effort has been costing up to $2 million a day in recent
years.
</TEXT>
