<2ND_LINE>PM-Wildfires-Manpower, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0478,0531</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Forest Service Is Looking For A Few Good Firefighters</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 3rd graf, `But the ...,' to UPDATE with
governors in Idaho and Wyoming calling up National Guardsmen to
help firefighters.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Wildfires-Commander, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN GALLAGHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOISE, Idaho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As forest fires spread through the West, the
U.S. Forest Service is spreading the word: Help!
   The Forest Service has put out a call for temporary firefighters
to battle the hundreds of blazes scorching the West's timberlands.
   But the emergency help must endure backbreaking labor, smoke and
flame. And only local people need apply.
   Meanwhile, governors in Idaho and Wyoming called up National
Guardsmen today to help fight fires in their states.
   The Boise Interagency Fire Center has notified Forest Service
regions affected by the dozens of out of control fires that
temporary firefighters may be hired on a contingency basis, said
Mike Ferris, information officer for the center that coordinates
fire suppression in the West.
   The temporary ``emergency firefighting hires,'' or ``casuals,''
must have the physical and mental capacity to work on the fire
lines, including long days of shoveling and chopping on steep
hillsides very near burning timber, Ferris said.
   ``The job carries with it a lot of drama and romance,'' Ferris
said. ``But somedays you've got to ask yourself, `Why am I doing
this?'''
   ``What we're doing is only hiring from the local community,'' he
said. ``I've had people calling from all over the country, and some
wanting to volunteer. I've had people wanting to take their
vacation and work, if you can believe that.''
   Ferris said those interested should contact their local national
forest office, not the Boise center and not the Forest Service in
Washington, D.C.
   Applicants will undergo an aerobic stress test, which measures
the ability of the heart to recover from exertion.
   While some fire officials have set the total number of temporary
workers needed at 4,000, Ferris said each national forest must
determine its requirements and the cost of employing those extra
people.
   ``We're making assessments about our needs in the situation.
We're not saying we're going to hire 4,000 or 8,000,'' he said.
   The emergency labor is a unique situation in a unique fire year.
   Late last week, the fire center estimated that 66,000 fires had
scorched more than 3.3 million acres, mostly in Alaska.
   There are 547 20-member crews, or 10,940 regular firefighters,
battling the West's fires, Ferris said.
   Nearly 1,600 water pumper trucks are manned by 15,213 people, or
an average three crew members per vehicle. About 630 people are
flying in helicopters for aerial observation or water drops. And
2,400 soldiers have been called to the lines, Ferris said.
   That does not include the scores of people who have contracted
to cut timber, cater meals at fire camps or bulldoze lines.
   The Forest Service does not expect to have the ``casuals''
trained and fitted for fighting fires until Friday, Ferris said.
   ``We will not put them in a situation that is more than what
they can bite and chew,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
