<FILEID>AP-NR-08-30-88 1031EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Techno-Bandit     08-30 0452</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Techno-Bandit,0465</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officials Give Details Of Failed Escape Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACKIE HALLIFAX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The mysterious helicopter that swooped
into a federal prison yard where an international ``techno-bandit''
was waiting to escape actually belonged to the government, because
the plot was no secret.
   Werner Bruchhausen didn't know government agents were aware of
his plan, and he ran and walked toward the aircraft as it hovered
above the empty softball field at the Federal Correctional
Institution Saturday evening, officials said Monday.
   The helicopter belonged to the U.S. Customs Service and was
flown by a Customs agent. And Bruchhausen only got to within about
20 feet of the aircraft before he was arrested by an FBI agent and
four prison officers.
   ``Possibly 2{ weeks ago we received information at the
institution from an unnamed source that Mr. Bruchhausen was talking
about escaping from the institution,'' said prison warden Bob
Honsted.
   ``Through the monitoring of telephone conversations we were able
to piece together, along with the other agencies, certain elements
of the plot,'' Honsted said.
   Officials released some details of the foiled escape attempt at
a news conference Monday but refused to answer many questions,
citing a continuing investigation.
   After the thwarted escape attempt, the West German citizen
convicted in Los Angeles of selling high-tech products to the
Soviet Union and Eastern European countries was transferred to the
federal penitentiary in Atlanta.
   Bruchhausen, who has been at the medium- to minimum-security
facility since May 1987, was willing to pay for his escape, Honsted
said.
   ``It's our belief that a sum of money, approximately or possibly
as high as a quarter of a million dollars, was mentioned,'' the
warden said. ``There was actually $5,000 that was received in
Tallahassee as partial payment.''
   Bruchhausen could face additional charges of attempted escape
and conspiracy to escape, U.S. Attorney Mike Moore said Monday.
Those charges have not yet been filed, but a conspiracy charge has
been filed against an individual still at large whom Moore refused
to identify.
   Bruchhausen and three others were indicted in August 1981 in Los
Angeles on charges of conspiracy and violating the Export
Administration Act, the Arms Export and Control Act and federal
income tax laws.
   He was arrested May 1985 in London, extradited and convicted of
wire fraud in 1987.
   Bruchhausen allegedly smuggled a microwave receiver system,
semiconductor manufacturing equipment, a computer system and other
military and scientific items to the Soviet bloc through dummy
corporations in California and West Germany, said Customs Service
Commissioner William von Rabb.
   Von Rabb in 1981 called Bruchhausen ``one of the world's top
techno-bandits'' and said he was ``deceiving and defrauding
American businesses by selling potential high technology to the
Soviets.''
</TEXT>
