<2ND_LINE>PM-Breakfast-Lunch,0226</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Students In Crowded School Get Lunch For Breakfast</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MARIETTA, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some students at crowded Lassiter High
School complain that spaghetti, fish, hot dogs and pizza are not
exactly what breakfast is supposed to be. But when you eat it at
9:33 a.m., what else do you call it?
   Because only so many of Lassiter's 2,100 students can fit into
the lunchroom at one time, that's when the first lunch period
begins.
   ``It stinks,'' said Heather Harrison, 17. ``When you get up in
the morning and eat breakfast, when you go to lunch you're full.
And when you get home you pig out.''
   Last year, when the Cobb County school in the Atlanta
metropolitan area had 2,500 students _ 500 over capacity _ lunch
started even earlier.
   ``We have improved,'' joked principal Doug Allen. ``We were
serving at 9:13 a.m.; now it's 9:33.''
   From a nutritional standpoint, there's nothing wrong with lunch
for breakfast, said food service assistant Joan Greaves. ``They're
given food groups that they need to give them energy during the
day,'' she said.
   Some students don't appreciate that.
   ``They should serve grits and pancakes,'' said Michele Ramsey,
17.
   Allen said the school tried adding brunch items last year, but
the novelty wore off and students went back to the fast-food line.
</TEXT>
