<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Israel-UN     08-30 0232</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-UN,0241</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israel Objects to Secretary-General's Reference to Palestine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel objected today to a statement by U.N.
Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar referring to
Israeli-occupied territories as Palestine.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Alon Liel said he planned to convey
Israel's displeasure through diplomatic channels before the
convening of the U.N. General Assembly next month.
   At a news conference in Geneva on Saturday following a meeting
with Palestine Liberation Organization chief Yasser Arafat, Perez
de Cuellar referred to the West Bank and Gaza Strip as Palestine.
   ``These are occupied territories for me and everybody with the
exception, of course, of the Israeli government. We call them
Palestinians and call the land Palestine,'' Perez de Cuellar said.
   Liel said: ``This terminology is unacceptable to us. The future
of the territories should be decided in negotiations. Until the
situation is determined, the terminology acceptable to us is the
administered territories.''
   Perez de Cuellar was quoted last week as saying he hoped to help
negotiate an end to the Arab-Israeli conflict in the same way he
help achieve a cease-fire and peace talks in the Persian Gulf war.
   Israel seized the West Bank from Jordan and the Gaza Strip from
Egypt in the 1967 Middle East war. The territories are home to 1.5
million Palestinians.
   The area now known as Israel was called Palestine until the
Jewish state was created in 1948.
</TEXT>
