<FILEID>AP-NR-08-30-88 1119EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-GulfTalks 2ndLd-Writethru   08-30 0764</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gulf Talks, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0504,0784</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Troop Withdrawal, Maritime Cease-Fire Said Stumbling Blocks</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto GEV3</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New grafs 5-9 beginning ``In an interview...'' to update with
new quotes from Velayati, editing for transition. Picks up 7th graf
pvs ``U.N. spokesman...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.N. secretary-general today blamed
disagreements over an immediate troop withdrawal and a maritime
cease-fire for stalling formal Iran-Iraq peace talks.
   ``We are trying to clear the first part (of a U.N. peace
resolution) on an immediate cease-fire and a troop withdrawal
without delay ... The cease-fire at sea is part of the problem,''
Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar said.
   Formal sessions between Foreign Ministers Ali Akbar Velayati of
Iran and Tariq Aziz of Iraq have been suspended since Friday. Plans
for a formal session Monday were shelved without explanation, and
no formal talks were planned today.
   Low-level talks with Iran and Iraq were continuing.
   In an interview today, Velayati told The Associated Press that
Iran would not grant Iraq any concessions which it had failed to
win in the 8-year-old war. He blamed Iraq for lack of progress in
the talks.
   Velayati said Iraq was facing many internal difficulties, adding:
   ``We think this is the main reason they are looking for some
advantage, some concessions. But if they couldn't get any
concessions during this long war with a lot of casualties, of
course they will not be able to get any concessions or anything
beyond their legal rights during the peace talks.''
   Tehran Radio today quoted Velayati as saying Iraq had raised
``unnecessary or out-of-place issues to disrupt the talks.''
   In the interview with Tehran Radio monitored in Nicosia, he said
he hoped Perez de Cuellar, the U.N. Security Council and other
nations can pressure Iraq and ``put a stop to this deviating course
... or force them to come back to the correct path.''
   U.N. spokesman Francois Giuliani said Perez de Cuellar met with
representatives of the five permanent members of the Security
Council _ the United States, Britain, China, France and the Soviet
Union _ on Monday to brief them on the negotiations.
   Giuliani did not comment on the discussions. But diplomats
speculated that the U.N. chief was hoping the five nations would
help get the talks moving.
   Iraq has been insisting on an early reopening of the
Shatt-al-Arab waterway, which has been blocked by sunken ships
since early in the war. Iran has said clearing the waterway _
Iraq's only outlet to the sea _ should come later after a permanent
cease-fire and troop withdrawal.
   Talks reportedly faltered at the ministerial level because of
the dispute over the Shatt-al-Arab. Baghdad claims sovereignty over
the entire Shatt-al-Arab. Iran claims rights to half of it. The
issue is central to the talks because the U.N. peace plan calls for
troop withdrawal to internationally recognized boundaries.
   Perez de Cuellar said today: ``You all think that everything is
the Shatt-al-Arab _ this is not quite true. This is one of the
difficulties we are facing and not the only one.''
   Aziz said Monday that it would be impossible to advance to other
points until Iran agreed that the cease-fire extended over all
Persian Gulf waters.
   ``It is a very difficult problem and it cannot be expected that
this will be resolved in a few days,'' Perez de Cuellar said.
   The talks began Thursday to try forge a peace treaty and a
timetable for troop withdrawal and prisoner exchange under a
U.N.-mediated Aug. 20 cease-fire.
   The two countries have in the past often ignored previous
agreements on the Shatt-al-Arab waterway, a point of friction since
the days of the Persian and Ottoman empires.
   A Western diplomat trying to settle the question in 1914 called
it ``a phenomenon of procrastination unparalleled in the chronicles
of oriental diplomacy.''
   Five days before Iraqi troops invaded Iran in September 1980
after weeks of border clashes, President Saddam Hussein of Iraq
tore up the latest treaty on the waterway, the Algiers Agreement of
1975, during a televised speech.
   The agreement between Hussein, then foreign minister, and the
late Shah of Iran set the border between the two nations in the
middle of the 125 mile-long waterway, instead of its Iranian bank _
a dividing line in a 1969 agreement.
   Velayati said Monday that Iraq could not unilaterally abrogate
the 1975 treaty. But Aziz told reporters that it was ``Iran that
always abrogated previous agreements, imposing new ones by force.''
   ``This reflects the situation in the 17th, 18th, 19th and early
in the 20 centuries, right up to present times,'' he added.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
