<1ST_LINE>r i PM-LakeSwimmer 1stLd-Writethru   08-30 0339</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lake Swimmer, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0494,0347</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Marathon Swimmer Crosses Last Of Great Lakes
^Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 4th pvs, She waded, to UPDATE with
quotes from swimmer. Pick up 5th pvs, During her.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 27-year-old swimming instructor waded out of
Lake Ontario today, the first person to swim all five Great Lakes.
   Canadian marathoner Vicki Keith took just less than 24 hours to
make the 31-mile crossing _ much faster than her original estimate
of 36 hours _ despite using the difficult butterfly stroke for most
of the swim.
   She began at Niagara-on-the-Lake, Ontario, and was supposed to
finish her swim at the Canadian National Exhibition grounds in
Toronto, but strong currents pushed her about three miles east.
   She waded out of the lake at 6:03 a.m. EDT.
   ``I feel good. I'm glad it's over, though,'' said Keith, visibly
tired and disoriented.
   ``It was really tough because of the butterfly,'' she said, her
teeth chattering. She was taken away quickly in a van.
   During her crossing, Keith claimed a women's world distance
record for the butterfly stroke, bettering her 1984 mark of 12
miles after just six hours in the water.
   She swam the butterfly stroke for 23.6 miles across the lake _
nearly doubling her record.
   Before the crossing, Keith said she planned to switch to the
easier freestyle stroke shortly after breaking her record for the
butterfly.
   But the Kingston, Ontario, woman didn't seem to feel the strain
of the awkward butterfly _ which involves throwing both arms over
the head and doing a dolphin-like kick simultaneously.
   She started her five-lake marathon in July in Lake Erie, crossed
sections of Lake Huron and Lake Michigan later that month and
completed a 21-mile arm of Lake Superior on Aug. 15.
   The swims were organized as part of a fundraising drive to help
pay for a swimming pool for the disabled in Toronto. She has raised
half of her $243,000 goal.
   Last summer, Keith became the first person to swim across Lake
Ontario and back.
</TEXT>
