<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Jackson-NYSE     08-30 0207</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jackson-NYSE,0212</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Booed at Exchange; Says He Was Only Slow</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rev. Jesse Jackson was booed this morning
after being accorded the honor of ringing a bell to kick off the
trading day at the New York Stock Exchange.
   Jackson had a ready explanation for the chilly reception _ he
said he was a few seconds late on the ringer.
   The civil rights leader, who is in New York for three days of
meetings with local officials and black activists, spent the early
part of the morning addressing a fund-raising breakfast of black
securities executives. Proceeds were to go to Jackson's Rainbow
Coalition.
   Then he was escorted to the exchange to start trading promptly
at 9:30 a.m. After the bell rang, apparently not promptly enough, a
handful of cheers by traders were nearly drowned out in a chorus of
boos.
   Jackson then took a walk around the floor of the exchange,
shaking hands with the traders, most of whom were already engaged
in the frantic business of the day.
   Speaking to reporters afterward, Jackson said he had been told
it was traditional to boo anyone who started the trading day late.
Anyway, he said, ``Cheers and jeers are part of Americana.''
</TEXT>
