<FILEID>AP-NR-08-30-88 1134EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Marcoses-Slaying     08-30 0410</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Marcoses-Slaying,0421</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Orders Marcoses to Stand Trial in Wrongful Death Suit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Philippines President Ferdinand Marcos and
his wife, Imelda, must stand trial to determine whether they had a
part in the slaying of two union leaders in 1981, a federal judge
ruled.
   In a decision she said was certain to be appealed, U.S. District
Judge Barbara Rothstein denied a request Monday by the deposed
leader and his wife to be dismissed from a wrongful death suit
filed by relatives of the slain unionists. The case is scheduled to
go to trial next year.
   Silme Domingo and Gene Viernes, anti-Marcos reform leaders in
the overwhelmingly Filipino Alaska Cannery Workers Union, were
gunned down at the union hall on June 1, 1981.
   Their survivors filed suit the next year, claiming in part that
the Marcos regime ordered the shootings. The Marcoses claimed
head-of-state immunity.
   A second federal judge dismissed the Marcoses as defendants in
the lawsuit in December 1982, while Marcos was still president. In
1987, after the Marcoses fled the Philippines, Ms. Rothstein ruled
they had to stand trial, and her decision Monday reaffirmed that
ruling.
   ``Head-of-state immunity serves to safeguard the relations among
foreign governments and their leaders _ not as the Marcoses assert,
to protect former heads of state regardless of their lack of
official status,'' the judge ruled.
   ``This court believes it is neither inequitable nor disturbing
that a foreign official who takes refuge in the United States must
defend the legality of private acts committed in the United
States,'' she added.
   Other defendants in the case include the Republic of the
Philippines; Leonilo Malabed, a San Francisco doctor, and three men
who were convicted on state criminal charges in the case. The suit
says Malabed controlled a fund from which $15,000 was paid for the
slayings.
   The Marcoses fled the Philippines for the United States in
February 1986 when Corazon Aquino was sworn in as president. They
now live in Hawaii.
   In an interview Monday, Malabed said he and Marcos have been
close friends for many years. He denied that he or Marcos had
anything to do with the shootings.
   ``I have no doubt even if he stood trial in Seattle that he
would win the case because there is no evidence,'' Malabed said.
   George Greer, a local attorney representing the Philippines in
the case, said he had yet to see evidence linking Marcos or the
Philippine government to the killings.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
