<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MedicareMixUp     08-30 0248</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Medicare Mix Up,0255</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Computer Error Poses `Life and Death' Problem For Sisters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHILDRESS, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two sisters with similar names and
Social Security numbers had to fight with the government for 18
months before it would admit they were not ``Medicare dead'' and
``nonexistent.''
   Chloie and Chleo Larmon didn't get anywhere with the Social
Security Administration until their congressman stepped in.
   The trouble started when Chloie needed surgery for a broken hip.
When she was dismissed from the hospital, a Medicare clerk struck
the ``deceased'' code instead of ``dismissed.''
   When Chloie filed for Medicare payments, she was told ``since
you have been declared legally dead, the executor of your estate
must send legal papers.''
   Chleo also ran into problems when she tried to apply for a
Medicare payment.
   ``They informed me I had no Medicare file,'' Chleo said. She
told Medicare officals: ``But Chloie is the one you have labeled
deceased, I'm not.''
   The sisters have almost identical Social Security numbers, with
only one digit differing.
   Finally Chleo told Childress Index publisher Morris Higley about
the situation and he advised them to contact U.S. Rep. Beau
Boulter, R-Texas.
   Within three weeks, Chloie and Chleo were alive and well in the
Medicare computer, and their checks were on the way.
   ``The Social Security Administration has corrected their records
and no longer show Ms. Larmon as deceased,'' the agency said. ``We
apologize for the delay in processing these claims and regret any
inconvenience it may have caused.''
</TEXT>
