<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Mayor-Impeachment 1stLd-Writethru a0523 08-30 0576</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mayor-Impeachment, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0523,0587</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Impeachment Trial Begins For `Voodoo' Mayor</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 4th graf, ``It's my ...' to UPDATE with
supporters carrying placards; SUBS 8th graf, `Attorney General ...'
to conform.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GARRY MITCHELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANDALUSIA, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mayor accused of ``voodoo'' antics
undermined the legal process by granting pardons to repeat
offenders and pocketed payments of some fines, the city attorney
testified at his impeachment trial.
   Larry Grissett, the city attorney, testified Monday at the trial
of Florala Mayor H.T. Mathis that he had warned the 85-year-old
official about abusing his legal authority to grant pardons.
   Charges against Mathis, who is accused of incompetence and
damaging his small town's reputation with ``voodoo'' antics,
include wholesale pardoning of convicted drunken drivers.
   ``It's my turn (today),'' the mayor said Monday at the
conclusion of the first day of his trial in Covington County
Circuit Court.
   Early today, three of the mayor's supporters stood outside the
courthouse carrying placards that said ``Impeach Don Siegelman,''
the state attorney general who rarely appears at trials but joined
his aides at this one.
   Grissett also testified that the town of 5,000, located near the
Florida border, was forced to file suit against the mayor to
prevent him from accepting payments of some fines and depositing
them in his personal account.
   ``He was taking partial payments outside court on the
installment basis,'' Grissett told the jury. He said Mathis
deposited $225 in fines in his personal account and did not return
the money ``until I filed suit.''
   Mathis' attorney, James Prestwood, questioned Grissett about the
mayor's authority to grant pardons. The attorney conceded that
Mathis had that power, but contended that he had abused it by
granting pardons to repeat offenders.
   Siegelman and a county grand jury accused Mathis of misusing his
office by granting too many pardons for drunken drivers. The mayor
is accused of willful neglect of duty, incompetency in office and
corruption.
   Mathis, whose four-year term expires Oct. 3, attracted national
attention by sprinkling so-called ``voodoo dust'' around City Hall
and later proclaiming ``National Voodoo Week'' in Florala. He says
he sprinkled the powder as a joke.
   In opening arguments, Prestwood portrayed Mathis as the victim
of a political struggle with the City Council.
   But Councilman Lewis Collins testified that the ``voodoo''
dusting incident had damaged the town's reputation and that the
mayor offered no explanation except to say, ``When it works, he
would let us know.''
   Collins said the council had to obtain a court order to halt the
mayor from releasing people from jail.
   ``He would order the dispatcher to turn people out of jail,''
Collins said. Later, the mayor began granting pardons to those in
custody.
   In other testimony, several Florala residents who had been
arrested on minor offenses said they had pawned their cars to the
mayor in exchange for payment of fines. They said they later
reimbursed Mathis in amounts larger than the fines to get their
cars back.
   In one instance, however, Rachael Aplin said the mayor had
already sold her car to the daughter of a city councilman and she
was unable to get the vehicle back.
   Alabama officials found guilty of impeachment charges are only
removed from office, not fined or sent to jail. However, they can
face another trial for the same crimes. An official thrown out of
office can appeal the verdict directly to the state Supreme Court.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
