<2ND_LINE>PM-South Africa-Angola, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0529,0710</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South Africa Completes Troop Withdrawal From Angola</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede JOHANNESBURG</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs on withdrawal. Picks up 5th graf pvs ``An
estimated...''. Changes byline.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   RUNDU, South-West Africa (AP) _ The last South African troops
withdrew today from Angola after fighting for more than a year in
support of anti-Marxist guerrillas.
   The armed forces chief of staff, Lt. Gen. Ian Gleeson, said at a
ceremony that nearly 1,000 soldiers crossed into South-West Africa
during the day as part of a regional peace accord.
   ``As of this moment, we are out of Angola,'' Gleeson said.
   South African and foreign journalists were flown to Rundu, on
the Angolan border, to witness what the final stages of the
withdrawal of South African forces. They saw 50 military vehicles
cross a pontoon bridge over the Okavango River before the bridge
was dismantled.
   In South-West Africa, also known as Namibia, military officials
said security forces in the past week killed 14 guerrillas fighting
to end South African rule over the territory. South African forces
also staged their first amphibious landing exercise today on the
Namibian coast.
   South African forces have been in Angola since early 1987. The
pullout from Angola is part of a cease-fire agreement that is
intended to clear the way for withdrawal of about 50,000 Cuban
troops from Angola and independence for Namibia.
   An estimated 2,500 South African troops in Angola have been
leaving since a cease-fire was declared Aug. 8.
   The Cuban troops support Angola's Marxist government in its
13-year-old war against guerrillas of UNITA (National Union for the
Total Independence of Angola). South Africa and the United States
back UNITA.
   UNITA is not party to the cease-fire and was excluded from
recent peace talks held by South Africa, Cuba and Angola under U.S.
mediation.
   There have been unconfirmed reports that South Africa has been
reinforcing its line of bases in northern Namibia.
   The amphibious landing exercise was conducted on a beach near
Walvis Bay, a South African enclave that serves as Namibia's only
commercial port. High-speed landing craft carried marines and
paratroopers ashore as part of a six-week exercise involving about
2,500 military personnel.
   The South-West African People's Organization, the main
pro-independence movement in the territory, contends Walvis Bay
should become part of a sovereign Namibia. South Africa's deputy
defense minister, Wynand Breytenbach, said Monday the port would
remain under South African control and continue to serve as a
military base.
   The South African-led territorial army said today that 14 SWAPO
guerrillas have been killed in the last week. SWAPO, considered
likely to take power if independence elections are held, has said
it will observe a cease-fire in Namibia starting Thursday if South
Africa reciprocates.
   South Africa says it will begin withdrawing from Namibia on Nov.
1 and allow the territory to hold independence elections next June
1 if Cuban troops leave Angola by the latter date.
   The four countries involved in the negotiations met last week in
Brazzaville, Congo, but failed to agree on a timetable for Cuban
withdrawal from Angola and Namibian independence. More talks are
planned next week.
   South Africa has intervened in Angola regularly since 1975 when
it invaded the country on the eve of Angolan independence from
Portugal. South Africa advanced several hundred miles up Angola's
west coast before turning back.
   South African forces returned to Angola several times in the
early 1980s, but in May 1985 announced a complete withdrawal.
Several weeks later, two South African commandos were killed and a
third was captured in northernmost Angola.
   Thousands of South African troops entered Angola in 1987 to
assist UNITA. South African generals said their maximum strength in
Angola was 3,000 men, although other reports claimed the force was
twice that size during heavy fighting last October.
   In November, South Africa said its forces again had begun
withdrawing, but most of the troops remained until this month.
   Dozens of white South African troops, most of them conscripts,
have been killed in Angola the past year. Black units, including
Angolans fighting for South Africa, are believed to have suffered
heavier casualties, but no comprehensive figures have been released.
</TEXT>
