<2ND_LINE>PM-Northrop,0215</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Agents Seize Documents at Northrop</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal investigators have seized documents
at Northrop Corp., apparently in a continuing investigation of the
aerospace company's MX missile contracts with the U.S. Air Force, a
newspaper reported today.
   The search was conducted last week at Northrop's Hawthorne plant
by agents from the Federal Bureau of Investigation and the Defense
Criminal Investigative Service, according to the Los Angeles Times.
   Northrop officials confirmed the search Monday, saying
investigators had taken ``contractural documents between Northrop
and the Air Force.'' Such papers related to the company's
production of a key component of the missile's sophisticated
electronic guidance system.
   However, other sources told the newspaper the documents included
``a recent internal audit report detailing purchasing problems,''
and details of failure records for the guidance component _
basketball-sized device with 19,401 parts, known as the inertial
measurement unit, or IMU.
   Investigators have been looking into allegations that Northrop
overcharged the military for the components, used defective parts
in the devices and delivered them behind schedule.
   Northrop has been charged by the government with $3 million in
civil fraud, but no criminal charges.
   Officials with the FBI and U.S. Attorney's Office here refused
to comment on last week's search or any investigation.
</TEXT>
