<HEAD>Four Killed in Major Refinery Fire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fire engulfed an oil refinery in
northern India on Tuesday, killing four people and seriously
injuring five, a government minister said.
   Among the dead was an engineer working with the Indian Oil
Corp., India's largest oil company, and a day laborer, according to
Brahm Dutt, the federal minister for petroleum.
   The fire broke out at the refinery at Mathura at a railway
siding where a train was being loaded with naphtha, Dutt told
Parliament. Mathura is 80 miles south of New Delhi.
   An investigation has been ordered into the cause of the fire,
which was brought under control in four hours, said Indian Oil
Corp. chief K.L. Khosla.
   Traffic along the national highway, where the refinery is
located, was blocked for several hours, said Manavendra Singh, a
legislator for Mathura.
   The refinery has been criticized by environmentalists because
its sulfur emissions threaten to discolor the Taj Mahal, India's
most famous monument at Agra, 45 miles away.
</TEXT>
