<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Mandela-Guns,0194</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Policeman Tells Court Of Finding Weapons At Mandela Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A rapid-fire pistol and an
automatic rifle were found last year at the home of Winnie Mandela,
wife of jailed black leader Nelson Mandela, a police officer
testified Tuesday.
   Lt. A. Kritzinger appeared in Johannesburg Supreme Court at the
trial of five blacks charged with two counts of murder and with
illegal possession of weapons.
   No charges have been filed against Mrs. Mandela.
   Kritzinger said he and other policemen, in two visits to Mrs.
Mandela's house in the black township of Soweto in February 1987,
found a Soviet-made AK-47 rifle in a bedroom and a Czech-made
Scorpion machine pistol.
   The lieutenant said police asked Mrs. Mandela and her daughter
Zindzi, where the pistol came from ``and got no positive response.''
   Kritzinger said such weapons normally are brought into South
Africa by guerrillas of the outlawed African National Congress
after military training abroad.
   Mandela led the ANC's military wing prior to his arrest in 1962.
The ANC has waged a bombing and sabotage campaign since 1961 aimed
at ending white minority rule.
