<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Chile 1stLd-Writethru a0466 08-30 0577</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Chile, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0466,0589</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pinochet Expected To Be Nominated For Re-Election Until 1997</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New grafs 1-11 with meeting begining, new quotes. Picks up
10th graf pvs: ``If a majority ... </NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN NOBLET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The four-man junta met today to nominate
the sole candidate _ expected to be President Augusto Pinochet _ in
a presidential referendum that could extend Pinochet's rule until
1997.
   National police troops cordoned off the Defense Ministry
building where army commander Gen. Pinochet, navy chief Adm. Jose
Merino, air force commander Gen. Fernando Matthei and national
police director Gen. Rodolfo Stange began their nomination session
at noon behind closed doors.
   Their selection will be presented for ratification or rejection
in an October referendum.
   Under the election rules established by the military government,
Pinochet _ who deposed the elected president in a bloody 1973
military coup _ and the other three junta members were to name a
single nominee and voters will vote ``yes'' or ``no'' on that
candidate.
   Pinochet, Merino, Matthei and Stange, all in dress military
uniforms, arrived one at a time at the ministry building, entering
on a thick red carpet rolled out for the occasion. None made any
remarks.
   While the other commanders arrived by car, the 72-year-old
Pinochet and his entourage of aides and bodyguards came on foot
from the government palace directly across Santiago's central
boulevard. He was both cheered and booed by bystanders.
   Both pro-and anti-Pinochet groups planned demonstrations in
connection with the nomination.
   Gen. Oscar Torres, national police sub-director, said ``we have
certainly taken some special security measures, especially in the
slums, where some day there might be problems.
   ``We don't expect serious problems,'' he added.
   Interior Undersecretary Alberto Cardemil told reporters ``there
is total and complete calm throughout the country. And I don't
think the government will need to take any extraordinary measures.''
   On Monday, police used water cannons to scatter a downtown
demonstration by women chanting anti-government slogans and urging
voters to vote ``no'' in the referendum. Witnesses said about 25
people were arrested.
   If a majority of Chile's 7.2 million registered voters cast
``yes'' ballots in the referendum, the nominee will begin an
eight-year term March 11. If a majority reject him, an open
election will be held in 1990, with Pinochet remaining in power
until then.
   The 1980 Constitution gives the junta 48 hours to nominate a
candidate. Were the commanders to fail to reach a unanimous
decision within that time, the Constitution calls for nomination by
majority decision of an eight-man National Security Council, which
includes Pinochet, navy chief Adm. Jose Merino, air force commander
Gen. Fernando Matthei and national police director Gen. Rodolfo
Stange. It also includes four other officials, three of whom are
appointed by Pinochet.
   Opposition leaders said they had little doubt that Pinochet
would win a quick nomination and called on followers to bang empty
pots and pans inside their homes tonight in protest.
   ``It will be the noisiest pot-banging ever heard,'' predicted
Ricardo Lagos, a socialist and co-leader of a 16-party opposition
coalition.
   Members of the youth wings of several opposition parties and a
communist-controlled slum dwellers organization planned street
demonstrations in central Santiago.
   The defense minister, Adm. Patricio Carvajal, warned Monday that
``the government will not allow any violent demonstrations. They
will be suppressed by police.''
   Pinochet led the coup that ousted the elected government of
Marxist President Salvador Allende in September 1973.
</TEXT>
