<1ST_LINE>u a PM-DefenseProbe-Documents     08-30 0130</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Defense Probe-Documents,0132</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Says Documents Must Remain Sealed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge today rejected a request to
unseal search warrants and other court documents used in the search
of the homes of three men in connection with the government's probe
of defense contractors.
   The decision by U.S. District Chief Judge Alexander Harvey was a
setback for The Washington Post which had persuaded a U.S.
magistrate to unseal some of the documents in July.
   In overturning the magistrate's ruling, Harvey agreed with the
government that making the papers public could impede the
government's probe.
   Harvey also said the three Maryland men, whose homes were
searched under the warrants, had not been criminally charged. Since
they were merely under investigation, Harvey said they had a right
to privacy.
</TEXT>
