<FILEID>AP-NR-08-30-88 1305EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Quayle     08-30 0312</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Quayle,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quayle: `Accustomed To Fighting Fires' That Plague His Candidacy</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Dan Quayle told a group of firefighters
Tuesday that since he became the Republican vice presidential
nominee he has grown ``very accustomed to fighting fires'' that
have erupted over his candidacy.
   ``Where were you when I needed you?'' Quayle asked the
International Association of Fire Chiefs.
   Since he became George Bush's running mate, Quayle has been the
subject of intense media scrutiny over allegations that he and his
wealthy publishing family pulled strings to get him into the
National Guard during the Vietnam War and into law school after a
poor college performance. Those issues, among others, have at times
threatened to overwhelm his campaign.
   ``Believe me, I feel that I am very accustomed to fighting fires
these last couple of weeks,'' Quayle said, as the group erupted in
laughter.
   Quayle, who is in Washington preparing for this week's Southern
campaign swing, said firefighters are ``heroes to America'' because
of the lives and property they save.
   ``You are really considered the heartbeat of America _
volunteers, people willing to put their lives on the line, people
that believe in themselves, people that make this country still the
greatest country in the world,'' said the Indiana senator.
   He told the group that he and Bush support increasing death
benefits for fallen firefighters as well as a strong national
defense.
   ``National defense and defending our freedom, there is no higher
cause,'' Quayle said.
   Quayle was presented with a fire chief's hat, and told the
group, ``This is going to be prominently displayed on my airplane
... right in front of where the press is sitting.''
   Quayle leaves aboard his campaign plane, dubbed ``Hoosier
Pride,'' on Wednesday for a trip south. He will stop in Louisiana,
Arkansas, Mississippi, Georgia, Alabama, Florida and South Carolina.
</TEXT>
