<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Yugoslavia-Press     08-30 0159</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Yugoslavia-Press,0163</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Lifts Ban on Newspaper That Lampooned Party Chief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An appeals court lifted a ban
Tuesday on the Aug. 28 edition of a popular local daily that had
lampooned Yugoslavia's Communist Party chief, the official Tanjug
news agency reported.
   The district court in Split, a city on the central Adriatic
coast, rejected the demand for a permanent ban of the edition of
Nedeljna Dalmacija, ruling there were no grounds to support it, the
news agency said.
   The temporary ban was imposed by the Split public prosecutor's
office, because of a commentary that lampooned party chief Stipe
Suvar, president of the party's ruling Presidium, and other top
officials.
   ``It is hypocritical to forbid publications making fun of our
top leaders, when jokes about them are constantly being told'' by
the people, said the news agency quoted the court ruling as saying.
   It was not clear whether the prosecutor's office would appeal
the verdict.
</TEXT>
