<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Tito     08-30 0303</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tito,0312</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Portrait of Tito Used by Albanian as Weapon Against Police</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Albanian demonstrator used a
portrait of the late President Tito to attack a policeman in a town
in southern Yugoslavia, the state Tanjug news agency reported
Tuesday.
   It said police arrested 13 of the estimated 200 Albanians who
hurled stones at them in Kumanovo, 260 miles south of Belgrade, on
Monday night.
   The demonstrators were protesting the introduction of compulsory
bilingual education in secondary schools in the region, which
belongs to Yugoslavia's southern republic of Macedonia.
   The clash occurred after 500 ethnic Albanians gathered in front
of the town hall and demanded that schools form separate classes in
which the Macedonian language would not be used for ethnic
Albanians, who are a minority.
   The authorities, who earlier this year disbanded such classes in
favor of bilingual education, described the demonstrations as ``the
work of Albanian nationalists and separatists.''
   The protesters carried a portrait of Tito and shouted ``Better a
grave than a slave!'' and ``We want freedom and justice!''
   ``The perfidy and transparency of slogans used by the
demonstrators was unmasked when a demonstrator attacked a policeman
with the portrait of Comrade Tito,'' said Tanjug.
   Demonstrators in Yugoslavia regularly invoke the name or carry
portraits of Tito, who is still venerated, as a moral shield
against the security forces.
   The demonstration is one of the largest by ethnic Albanians
since 1981, when at least nine people died in ethnic rioting in the
neighboring province of Kosovo, where nearly 90 percent of the
population is Albanian.
   The minority Slav population of the province has recently held a
series of rallies demanding that authorities put a stop to what
they describe as discrimination by Albanians, whose actions, they
claim, are forcing them to move out of Kosovo.
</TEXT>
