08-30 0389</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-NIreland-Explosives, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0506,0397</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three Men Killed In Northern Ireland</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to update with three men killed. Picks up
2nd graf pvs ``The bombs...''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDONDERRY, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three men were shot and
killed today a few miles from the site of an IRA bombing that left
eight British soldiers dead and 27 injured.
   Independent Television News said without attribution that the
three men _ apparently armed _ were believed to have been killed by
British security forces.
   A police spokesman said the men shot to death in Omagh, 50 miles
west of Belfast, at about 4 p.m. were not members of the security
forces.
   He said the shootings occurred on the main road from Omagh to
Carrickmore, a few miles from the place an Irish Republican Army
bomb blew up July 20 near a British army bus. The officer spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   The bus bomb dealt the British army in Northern Ireland its
worst blow since 1982, and brought to 26 the military death toll in
a summer of IRA attacks in the British province, mainland Britain
and continental Europe.
   This morning, four mortar bombs and 25 pounds of explosives were
found aboard a bus crossing the border from the Republic of
Ireland, police in Londonderry said.
   The bombs and Czechoslovakian-made Semtex explosives were
discovered on a bus owned by the Lough Swilly Co., a private bus
service, when it was stopped and searched at a border checkpoint, a
police spokesman said.
   They were found in luggage in the passenger compartment, said
the spokesman, who also spoke on condition of anonymity.
   He said the bus driver and passengers were being questioned but
no arrests had been made.
   The discovery followed a weekend of bombings, shootings, riots
and other violence in Belfast, Londonderry and Newry which was
sparked by the extradition from Ireland to Northern Ireland of a
convicted guerrilla and jail escapee.
   The Irish Republican Army, which is fighting to oust British
troops from the province of Northern Ireland, led the violent
protests over Robert Russell's extradition, police said.
   Security forces in Northern Ireland have said the IRA received
Semtex, a lightweight and difficult to detect explosive, in arms
shipments from Libya. Britain has held discussions with
Czechoslovakia about making it more difficult for the IRA to obtain
Semtex.
</TEXT>
