<HEAD>Council OKs $1 Cab Discount For Rides To Church</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HIGH POINT, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Taxicab passengers headed for church can
put an extra dollar in the collection plate _ or their pockets _ on
Sundays thanks to a new fare discount approved by the City Council.
   But they'd better be serious about praying.
   ``If it's abused, like if some people get out and walk around
the back of the church, then the mayor said the rebates will
stop,'' City Attorney Bryant Aldridge said Tuesday of the new
$1-off-on-Sundays deal.
   The heavenly discount was offered last week by the city's only
cab company, Red Bird Cab Co., when it received approval for a rate
increase, Aldridge said.
   At that time, council member David Baker requested the discount
for people who ride taxicabs to church because buses don't run on
Sundays in the central North Carolina city, the attorney said.
   The dollar-off deal applies only during Sunday morning church
hours and may be denied if the cab driver suspects the rider is not
going to church, Mayor Roy Culler said.
