<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Nicaragua-War     08-30 0716</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua-War,0743</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sandinista Troops On Alert During Fragile Cease-Fire</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RIO BLANCO, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sandinista troops are patrolling in
rural areas, undergoing intensive training and staying on the alert
during a fragile cease-fire with Contra rebels.
   The government's combat units have spent time regrouping, and
farmers in this combat area about 80 miles northeast of Managua
said they have been able to plant crops despite lingering tension.
   Each side has charged the other with violating the cease-fire
during the five months it has been in effect, but the Sandinistas
recognize their advantage. ``The Contras don't have much of a
possibility of major attacks,'' said Defense Ministry spokeswoman
Maj. Rosa Pasos in a recent interview in Managua.
   Most of the Contras trying to overthrow the Sandinistas have
holed up in Honduras and they are continuing to train new fighters
and ask for weapons from the United States.
   Each side says the other is planning for renewed combat, and
Roman Catholic Cardinal Miguel Obando y Bravo recently charged both
sides with preparing to renew the almost seven-year war.
   The 9-year-old Sandinista government and Contra leaders signed a
cease-fire agreement March 23, three weeks after the U.S. Congress
cut off military aid to the rebels. Talks to define the pact, which
called for democratic reforms and an end to rebel attacks, broke
off June 9.
   Contra officials and Sandinistas estimate that some 2,000 rebels
remain inside Nicaragua, mostly in the rugged northern mountains.
   Peasants in eastern Matagalpa, a northern province that has seen
heavy combat during the war, said Contra rebels ambushed several
civilian cars and military vehicles recently on the remote dirt
roads.
   Many motorists venturing along the rutted 20-mile stretch from
Matiguas to Rio Blanco, a longtime Contra route, fly white flags to
mark their neutrality while journeying through the area.
   ``This road runs along the Contra corridor to the north to
Honduras,'' a Sandinista military officer, Jose Ortega, said at the
Rio Blanco base overlooking steep hills. ``Here you can't say any
road is safe.''
   Ortega said the rebels, most in torn uniforms or civilian
clothes, kidnapped more than a dozen civilians recently.
   In the town of Matiguas, several residents said the combat in
the region was sharply reduced but that an air of tension remained.
   ``It's quiet by comparison,'' said farmer Jose Sequira. ``But we
just wait and see.''
   The farmer and government officials said the lull in the war
meant many peasants planted crops this spring for the first time in
several years.
   ``But we don't know if we'll be able to reap the harvest,'' said
Sequira.
   A series of informal talks started by Sandinista troops with
Contra combatants ended in May. An army officer said the rebels
responded to messages with bullets.
   Contra leader Enrique Bermudez said recently the chats were
``part of a Sandinista trick to dismantle us one by one.''
   Contra officials report that most of their forces fled during
the past four months to tent camps in eastern Honduras, where more
than 9,000 combatants are receiving U.S.-supplied food and uniforms.
   Rebel commanders said recently they are prepared to return to
the battlefields in Nicaragua but needed weapons, denied by the
U.S. Congress since Feb. 29. Many are now armed with rusted
Soviet-designed Kalashnikov rifles.
   The Sandinistas, supplied by the Soviet Union, last year
received $505 million in war supplies, according to the Pentagon.
The Nicaraguan Defense Ministry spokeswoman said shipments were
arriving this year ``as usual,'' but declined to elaborate.
   Army troops, Pasos said in an interview, were moving into areas
where Contra presence had been strong and were seeking civilian
support by backing health and educational services.
   At rebel base camps in Honduras, Contra officials said the
Sandinistas are getting ready for an attack aimed at finishing the
Contras once and for all.
   The Sandinista troops, Pasos said, were refining combat skills,
looking at new tactics to counter Contra ambushes and staying in
the field.
   ``Our combat troops are in position,'' Pasos said.
   Asked about any plans to reduce Nicaragua's 80,000-strong armed
forces, the largest in Central America, she replied: ``For what?
The war hasn't ended.''
   More than 26,000 people have been killed since the fighting
started in 1981, a 18 months after the Sandinistas overthrew
dictator Anastasio Somoza.
</TEXT>
