<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Brezhnev     08-30 0374</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brezhnev,0383</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brezhnev Son-In-Law Could Be Sentenced to Death, Spokesman Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The son-in-law of the late Soviet leader Leonid I.
Brezhnev could be sentenced to death if convicted next week of
giving and accepting hundreds of thousands of rubles in bribes, a
government spokesman said Tuesday.
   The trial of Yuri Churbanov and eight other former government
officials starts Monday in Moscow and is expected to last 1{ to two
months, Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady I. Gerasimov said at a
regular news briefing.
   The group will be tried before the military collegium of the
Supreme Court, and 200 witnesses are scheduled to testify,
according to Gerasimov.
   The investigation of Churbanov and the others has become a
sensation in the press, which for more than a year have taken
advantage of Mikhail S. Gorbachev's policy of glasnost, or
openness, to report widespread corruption, nepotism and organized
crime. The reports usually center around Churbanov, who married
Brezhnev's daughter, Galina, in 1971, and a crime racket with which
he was allegedly involved in the republic of Uzbekistan.
   The Communist Party daily Pravda published a detailed report on
the case Tuesday.
   Pravda described Churbanov, appointed deputy interior minister
in 1980, as a power-hungry man who used family connections for
criminal purposes. It said he thrived during the rule of Brezhnev,
who served as leader from 1964 until his death in 1982.
   ``A phenomenon of the stagnation years was the practice of
making decisions in private about nomination of people to the
highest positions, and a person was judged by his family status and
the ability to please this or that clan, and not by his business
qualities,'' the newspaper said.
   The Tass news agency has reported that Churbanov is accused of
accepting bribes totaling more than $1.1 million, equivalent to 270
years' pay for the average Soviet factory worker.
   Gerasimov said Churbanov could face execution by firing squad
because he is charged with serious economic crimes. He noted that a
new version of the criminal code being drafted would reduce the use
of capital punishment for economic crimes, but that this change had
not yet taken effect.
   Selected foreign reporters will be allowed to attend the first
and final days of the trial, he said.
</TEXT>
