<DOCNO> AP880830-0104 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-30-88 1431EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Bush 2ndLd-Writethru a0495 08-30 0804</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0495,790</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede NASHVILLE</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bush Happy With Combative Style of Campaigning</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: TOP 5 grafs new with Bush comments; picks up 3rd graf pvs,
`He railed.'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROCKY MOUNT, N.C.(AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican nominee George Bush said
today that the United States should avoid gambling with its future
by electing Michael Dukakis, who is ``another liberal governor
coming out of nowhere.''
   The vice president, who continued his strong defense theme of
recent days, sought to depict his Democratic rival as inexperienced
and weak on defense.
   During a tour of a Bendix defense plant, which Bush said ``keeps
the muscle of our defense strong,'' the GOP nominee suggested that
Dukakis favors ``unilateral cuts in the muscle of the United
States.''
   Later, as he addressed a $500-a-ticket party fund-raiser in a
private residency, Bush said that while he didn't ``want anything
to do with tearing down'' the character of his Democratic rival,
``We should not gamble America's future on another liberal governor
coming
   On Monday afternoon, the feisty, tough-talking Bush was in high
gear, firing up a college crowd at Middle Tennesse State University
in nearby Murfreesboro.
   He railed against Dukakis, accusing him of being weak on
defense, soft on crime, in favor of new taxes and guilty of poor
judgment and a ``liberal bias.''
   Using an applause line that he has all but worn out since the
Republican National Convention two weeks ago, he said that if
Congress ever tried to insist that as president he raise taxes, he
would say, ``Read my lips _ no new taxes.''
   When he went down to shake hands in the front of the outdoor
rally of some 3,000 to 4,000, the crowd surged forward, hands
reaching out excitedly.
   ``I thought that was good,'' Bush later told reporters when
asked how he felt about the enthusiasm of his supporters.
   The combative and buoyant George Bush has been delighting
supporters in city after city since the New Orleans GOP convention,
as he speaks with a confident voice that seems to have been waiting
until after the convention to project itself.
   His apparent ease with the new image stood in contrast with a
Monday morning speech in which he slipped into his old low-key
style addressing employees of a defense contracting plant near St.
Louis.
   While some of the new rhetoric was there, the tone was more
measured, recalling a style that was prominent in the primary
campaign.
   Bush's chief of staff, Craig Fuller, said that was because Bush
wanted to lay out substantive material on the differences between
himself and Dukakis, mostly on defense.
   ``I think there will be times when he'll give more serious
speeches, particularly when we move off of one set of issues into
another,'' Fuller said.
   But for now Bush is having a good run with the more feisty
style, which, coupled with improved standings in the polls, has him
in a relaxed, good mood.
   Fuller said the campaign has not conducted polling yet to see
how the new tough image is working, but ``We've certainly noted a
lot more enthusiasm in the crowds.''
   ``Now that we're in this phase of the campaign it certainly
helps to build up enthusiasm,'' he said.
   Fuller said the campaign looked at the convention as ``designed
to be a break with the past and the convention was an opportunity
to move from being Vice President George Bush to candidate George
Bush.''
   ``As a candidate he's felt compelled to draw distinctions
between himself and his opponent,'' Fuller said.
   And so Bush has turned up the heat meter on Dukakis, sharpening
his rhetoric and raising his voice as he tells audiences it's
important to show the ``enormous differences'' in their positions.
   Furthermore, Bush told reporters on Monday morning, he doesn't
intend to be ``stampeded'' into conforming to a debate schedule
favored by Dukakis.
   ``I say, `Explain your views on defense,''' he said. ``The
response is,`How about debates?' _ totally irrelevant.''
   Bush's campaign chairman, James Baker, was meeting today with
his counterpart in the Dukakis campaign, Paul Brountas, to discuss
the debate matter. Bush headed to North Carolina for a one-day
campaign trip.
   Campaigning at a defense plant near St. Louis, Bush belittled
Dukakis for his opposition to a number of weapons systems.
   ``Sometimes he give me the impression he's against every new
weapons system since the slingshot,'' he said.
   Bush said it didn't bother him a bit that he and running mate
Dan Quayle differ on some policy issues and that the Indiana
senator didn't know Bush headed a presidential panel on drug
interdiction.
   ``We're so much in sync on broad issues, you don't expect
everybody to be in agreement on every single `t' being crossed or
`i' being dotted,'' he said when asked about positions he espouses
that Quayle voted against in Congress.
</TEXT>
