<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CampaignAbroad     08-30 0884</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Campaign Abroad,0905</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Comment Abroad on Quayle, Bush and Dukakis</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   This is one of a series of periodic reports
compiled by Associated Press bureaus on how the U.S. presidential
election campaign is viewed abroad.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>By The Associated Press</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Here is some of the editorial commentary appearing recently in
newspapers overseas on Sen. Dan Quayle, the Republican vice
presidential nominee, and the two main contenders in the U.S.
presidential race, Republican George Bush and Democrat Michael
Dukakis.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>ON QUAYLE</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _Toronto Globe and Mail, Canada (independent): ``None of Mr.
Quayle's sins is mortal, but their cumulative effect is
considerable. As the sharks go to work, the shreds of evidence
indicate that Mr. Quayle is a man of modest talents who has failed
to impress teachers and colleagues.
   ``Mr. Bush and the Republicans face more heavy weather about Mr.
Quayle's fitness to stand a heartbeat away from the most important
job in the world. They deserve it.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   _The Independent, Britain (independent): ``America's and the
world's first question about George Bush's running mate _ Dan who?
_ has been comprehensively answered. ... The ... more important
question _ can we image, or could we trust, a President Quayle? _
will not vanish so easily. Three of the last nine presidents were
replaced by their deputies before the end of their term. ...
   ``The furore about the Indiana senator's decision to join the
National Guard rather than go to Vietnam in 1969 is beginning to
subside. ... It is not, however, the 22-year-old but the
41-year-old Quayle whom the American people are being asked to
elect. Far more disturbing than his response to a messy moral
choice two decades ago is his reaction ... to personal crisis and
the pitiless logic of politics in the big league. The most serious
charges against Mr. Quayle _ callowness and shallowness _ were
suggested by his first arm-flapping, finger-jabbing appearances
alongside George Bush in New Orleans, before the Vietnam issue
fully emerged. They have been confirmed by his evasive and
disjointed responses to the Vietnam question, essentially seeking
to make the issue one which it is not: the honor of the National
Guard. The qualities the United States, and the world, has most
reason to wish for in the American president are courage and
coolness under fire. Dan Quayle has shown little of either so far.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>ON BUSH VS. DUKAKIS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _Las Ultimas Noticias, Santiago, Chile (conservative): ``George
Bush has ahead of him the task of convincing voters that he is a
capable leader. It's an uphill job. ...
   ``Bush must also fight to keep the support _ and the
contributions _ of the Republican Party's most conservative groups
which do not fully trust him because they see him as a
representative U.S. East coast liberal wing.
   ``His strategy is to show Dukakis as a representative of the
Democrats' most liberal wing whose policies include to increase
spending and taxes.
   ``Bush trusts that, in the end, voters will seek the security of
keeping in power a party and a man promising them to maintain
economic growth, a curbed inflation and unchanged taxes. That is
why in his speech accepting the nomination he said Dukakis
represents `the liberal ideology that has failed'.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   _Le Figaro, Paris (conservative): ``George Bush's adversary is
Michael Dukakis. But his real problem is Ronald Reagan. After eight
years and two terms, the president is still loved by the crowds;
the vice president has only the esteem of the experts. Reagan
electrifies the man in the street with his patriotic speeches,
makes him laugh with gaffes which are generally forgiven right
away, draws tears from his eyes by reducing the grand events of
history to tales full of good sentiments. Serious and measured,
informed and didactic, Bush puts his listeners to sleep. ...
   ``Bush therefore cannot win in November except by setting
himself off from Reagan. Expert in the art of nuance, he must prove
his firmness. Instinctive partisan of compromise, he must show he
can make tough decisions.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   _The Times of London (independent): ``Mr. Dukakis has made much
of his managerial image. This seems to appeal to the country after
Mr. Reagan's hand-off rule _ and its damaging outcome in the
Iran-Contra affair. In a Bush presidency, policy is more likely to
be managed by the president, and not left in the hands of the Foggy
Bottom foreign policy establishment. Mr. Bush has, after all, done
much more managing. His problem is that the appearance belies that
fact. Prosperity at home ought also to be a strong card for Mr.
Bush. The fact that after last October's Black Monday the U.S.
economy did not plunge into a recession or soar with inflation can
be seen as a victory for the management of the economy. But
American confidence in a prosperous fugure is not strong. Mr.
Dukakis can claim to be able to do better, and lumber the vice
president with some of the less attractive economic leftovers of
the Reagan years. ... Bush is not built for presidential
campaigning. He has no clear saleable identity. He is not quick. He
is not even consistenly clear. ... But he does understand the
dangers of the world in which he aspires for leadership. From here
that is no small thing in his favor.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
