<DOCNO> AP880830-0109 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-30-88 1634EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     08-30 0216</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0224</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright & Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALLIANCE, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fund-raising idea to help repair a
50-year-old fountain generated a cascade of coins totalling nearly
$19,000.
   About 5,000 people lined up Sunday to place coins, mainly
quarters, on masking tape laid by volunteers for 11 blocks along
Box Butte Avenue to the fountain.
   On Monday, Eva Knight said the official total for the Coins for
the Fountain drive was $18,911.83, but said additional pledges
would help fund-raisers to exceed their $20,000 goal.
   Now, said City Parks Superintendent Lyle Shaughnessy, the next
step is to get estimates for the work. Mrs. Knight is already
planning the fountain's lighting ceremony for next May.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SEEKONK, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the comics, Superman may leap tall
buildings. But John Wooten, who bills himself the world's strongest
man, moves them.
   Wooten, 40, pulled a 14-ton mobile home atop a flatbed truck
about 100 yards across the Rhode Island-Massachusetts border Monday.
   The feat took about one minute. When it was done, a red-faced
Wooten said, ``It was a little easier than I thought. I think I
could have almost gone for two houses.''
   Wooten, 6-foot-1 and 274 pounds, said he considers himself to be
one of the last old-time strong men, the type who ``uses
entertainment to show his strength.''
</TEXT>
