<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Housing-Homeless     08-30 0448</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Housing-Homeless,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Blocks HUD Sale Of Foreclosed Homes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM SEPPY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge temporarily blocked the
Department of Housing and Urban Development on Tuesday from selling
foreclosed single-homes across the nation to the highest bidder.
   U.S. District Judge Harold H. Greene said his temporary
restraining order would remain in effect until Sept. 14 while Judge
Oliver Gasch, who has jurisdiction over the case, schedules further
deliberation.
   Greene said, ``Clearly, HUD did not comply with (housing
laws).'' He said challengers of the sales would ``likely be
successful on the merits.''
   He said his order would apply nationwide, but would not affect
HUD sales previously entered into with buyers.
   The suit was brought by a coalition of advocates for the
homeless as part of a broader effort to force the federal
government to make the federal government's inventory of 47,000
foreclosed houses available to the homeless.
   Florence Wagman Roisman, representing the National Housing Law
Project, said the restraining order was sought because HUD planned
to sign contracts to sell 170 homes in the Washington, D. C.,
metropolitan area on Wednesday. Last week, the project blocked HUD
from selling 200 homes in Michigan.
   Greene accepted the project's arguments that HUD had violated
the Homeless Assistance Act of 1987, requiring HUD to survey all
federal buildings and properties to ``identify which ... are
suitable to assist the homeless.''
   The project also said the legislation stipulates that HUD must
then make properties in excess of the agency's need available to
the homeless.
   Greene said HUD also violated the National Housing Act, which
calls for ``the realization as soon as feasible of the goal of a
decent home and a suitable living environment for every American
family.''
   ``We don't want HUD to sell off these units to speculators and
investors,'' said Roisman. ``They have 47,000 units available. Even
if they had 80,000, it would be a drop in the bucket. There are
800,000 families on a waiting list for housing around the country.''
   W. Robert Irwin, a Justice Department attorney representing HUD,
said there is no need for the court to block any house auctions.
``There is a continuing recycling of houses into and out of the HUD
inventory,'' he said.
   Under the restraining order, Irwin said, ``The houses will
remain vacant. They will be the subject of vandalism and there will
be a loss of property values, depending on the length of the suit.''
   Roisman said the houses do not have to remain vacant because, in
just the Washington area, there are 700 families with 2,500
children living in hotels and motels. ``They would be very happy to
move into a home,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
