<1ST_LINE>u i AM-AirShow 1stLd-Writethru a0664 08-30 0856</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Air Show, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0664,0874</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Death Toll Rises, Burned Children Feared Orphaned</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 7-9 pvs with 5 grafs to UPDATE more on returning
Americans, CORRECTS Italian pilot's mistake to arrival too soon and
too low, sted too fast and too high; </NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RAMSTEIN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The death toll in the worst crash
at an air show rose to 49 Tuesday, and officials feared some
children hospitalized with severe burns had been orphaned because
no one had inquired about them.
   The Pentagon said six Americans were among those killed when
three Italian jets collided Sunday at the U.S. Air Base in
Ramstein, one hurtling into the crowd in flames.
   West German officials said two people died of burns Tuesday,
raising their death toll to 49. They said 14 had been identified,
including the three Italian pilots. None of the 14 was a U.S.
citizen.
   Chief Pentagon spokesman Dan Howard said the latest U.S. count
put the number of confirmed fatalities at 40, including six
Americans, four Germans, three Italians and 27 people of unknown
nationality. Of the six Americans, two were active-duty military
personnel, three were dependents and one is unknown, Howard said.
   The Defense Department was trying to resolve its conflicts in
the casualty counts, he said.
   The latest Pentagon count also showed 363 individuals injured,
of whom 41 were Americans and 322 were Germans, Howard said.
   Four U.S. burn victims were flown to the Brooke Army Medical
Center in San Antonio, Texas, for further treatment. Surgeons and
other medical staff took nearly an hour to move the blanket-covered
patients from a military ambulance onto a C-141 U.S. Air Force
transport plane.
   As the four were being loaded onto the transport, a fighter jet
screamed overhead.
   The decision to move them from the Landstuhl hospital was made
after the San Antonio team headed by two surgeons examined them
Monday and Tuesday.
   The West German Bild and Abendpost newspapers said at least
three children had been hospitalized with serious burns but no one
had inquired about them, leading to speculation their parents had
been killed in the accident.
   In Udine, Italy, the commander of the Italian stunt-flying team
said that the team's soloist, Lt. Col. Ivo Nutarelli, had caused
the crash when he reached the point were the jets intersected too
soon and too low.
   Lt. Col. Diego Raineri, who was coordinating the team's
movements from a control tower when the collision occurred, spoke
to reporters shortly before the remains of the three pilots killed
in the crash arrived home. About 2,000 people were at the airport
when the bodies arrived.
   Some Italian politicans called for a parliamentary investigation
of the crash and for the resignation of the defense minister and
the Air Force commander.
   In downtown Ramstein, about 100 members of the leftist Greens
Party and their supporters took part in a vigil Tuesday evening.
They expressed shock over the accident and called for a permanent
ban on military air shows.
   ``The mood here has changed. Now they see the danger is a
reality ... it has happened,'' said Gabrielle Schellanner, a local
party spokeswoman. ``Before, when we warned about it, people didn't
take it seriously _ they thought it was just a political thing.''
   Authorities said they were being deluged with pleas from people
seeking information on family members.
   Juergen Dietzen, spokesman for the Rhineland Palatinate state
government, said police had received more than 400 reports of
missing people following Sunday's disaster. He said some people
were listed in more than one report.
   ``There are even cases of people from as far away as America who
have said `My relative has been on vacation there for three weeks,
and we haven't heard a word. Is it possible they were at
Ramstein?''' said Dietzen.
   West Germany's ARD television showed pictures of a special
missing persons bureau set up after the disaster in the town of
Kaiserslautern near Ramstein.
   ``I'm looking for my sister,'' said a German man whose name was
not given. ``The whole family didn't come home.'
   Officials said that of the 282 people still hospitalized, about
20 to 30 were so badly burned and disfigured that they also were in
danger of dying.
   The Bild newspaper said authorities have searched in vain for
the parents of two badly burned girls _ 6-year-old Nadine and
10-year-old Melanie _ who are being treated at a hospital in
Oggersheim.
   ``Their faces and their bodies are burned _ 70 percent _ and
their hair is singed,'' the newspaper reported.
   Bild quoted head surgeon Dr. Rudolf Zellner as saying it was
possible the parents of both girls were dead since no one inquired
about them.
   One young boy thought to be about 13 with burns on 95 percent of
his body has still not been identified because he is in deep shock,
the Frankfurt Abendpost newspaper said.
   The boy has not regained consciousness since he was brought to
the Offenbach hospital near Frankfurt ``and no one has asked about
him,'' Dr. Roberto Avalos was quoted as saying, adding it was
suspected his parents were dead.
</TEXT>
