<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Vietnam     08-30 0340</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Vietnam,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vietnam to Renew Cooperating on Accounting for MIAs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vietnam has agreed to resume cooperating with
the United States on accounting for the more than 1,700 American
military personnel still missing in the Vietnam War, ending a
boycott that lasted less than a month, the State Department said
Tuesday.
   A U.S. technical team will meet with Vietnamese authorities in
Hanoi to work out details for a joint field survey and excavation
activities in Vietnam, department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley said.
The meeting is tentatively set for Sept. 9-12.
   ``We welcome this resumption of cooperation and anticipate that
the joint field activities will make a major contribution in
achieving the fullest possible accounting for Americans still
missing in Vietnam,'' she said.
   She said a U.S. team also will visit Hanoi on Sept. 5-8 to
discuss a plan to allow private American organizations to treat
Vietnamese with war-related disabilities.
   On Aug. 3, Vietnam suspended cooperation with the United States
on the accounting effort. Foreign Minister Nguyen Co Thach said his
government was retaliating against a ``hostile policy'' the United
States was pursuing against Vietnam.
   His statement was prompted by testimony in late July in which
Assistant Secretary of State Gaston Sigur reaffirmed the
longstanding U.S. policy of maintaining diplomatic distance from
Hanoi until its troops are withdrawn from Cambodia.
   The United States has agreed to discuss humanitarian issues with
Vietnam but says there can be no trade or diplomatic relations
between the two countries until the Cambodian issue is resolved.
   Sigur said the Reagan administration was opposed to a proposal
by several members of Congress to establish a small U.S. diplomatic
mission in Hanoi.
   Mrs. Oakley said Vietnam has not agreeed to resume discussions
on resettlement in the United States of former political detainees
who were associated with the former U.S.-backed government in
Saigon.
   She expressed disappointment there will be no discussions on
that issue but said the administration hopes the two September
meetings ``will initiate a period of increased cooperation on all
humanitarian issues of mutual interest.''
</TEXT>
