<FILEID>AP-NR-08-30-88 1615EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-GulfTalks Bjt   08-30 0676</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf Talks, Bjt,0697</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran Rules Out Concessions as Talks Remain Stalled</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto GEV3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEX EFTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iranian Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati said
Tuesday that his country would make no concessions to Iraq as peace
talks to end their 8-year-old war remained stalled for a fourth day.
   ``That is Iraq's dream ... but if they couldn't get any
concessions during this long war with so many casualties, of course
they will not be able to get any concessions or anything beyond
their legal rights during the peace talks,'' Velayati told The
Associated Press in an interview.
   U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar, who is
conducting the negotiations between Velayati and his Iraqi
counterpart Tariq Aziz, said the talks were stalled over immediate
troop withdrawal and freedom of navigation.
   ``We are trying to clear the first part (of a U.N. peace
resolution) on an immediate cease-fire and a troop withdrawal
without delay ... the cease-fire at sea is part of the problem,''
he said on arrival at the Palais des Nations.
   Formal talks have been suspended since Friday, and low-level
talks have been held without the participation of Velayati and Aziz.
   U.N. spokesman Francois Giuliani told an evening news briefing
that technical experts from the two delegations continued to work
at the Palais, but a top-level meeting was not planned. ``If there
is a formula, then there will be a (top level) meeting,'' he said.
   The secretary-general met Monday with the ambassadors of the
five permanent members of the Security Council _ Britain, China,
France, the Soviet Union and the United States _ to discuss how to
get the talks going again.
   In Tehran, spiritual leader Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini declared
Tuesday that the war with Iraq was not over yet. He accused the
United States and the Soviet Union of plotting against his country,
official Tehran radio reported.
   The radio, monitored in Nicosia, said Khomeini urged Iranians to
man the front lines but also called for a national effort in Iran's
post-war reconstruction.
   The 88-year-old religious patriarch, who said last month that
Iran's acceptance of a U.N. cease-fire resolution was ``more deadly
to me than poison,'' declared: ``We must not take it that the war
has ended.''
   ``Our enemy, be it big enemies such as America and the Soviet
Union or their surrogates such as (Iraqi President) Saddam
(Hussein) and others, are constantly plotting because they have
seen how Islam has become a major force in the world,'' Khomeini
was quoted as saying.
   Velayati blamed Iraq for blocking the peace talks. ``The main
problem is the raising of new preconditions by Iraq,'' he said.
   He said the preconditions included a demand for the immediate
clearing of the disputed Shatt-al-Arab waterway, Iraq's only outlet
to the sea, and Baghdad's unilateral abrogation of the 1975 Algiers
treaty.
   The treaty places the border between the two countries down the
middle of the waterway. Iraq demands full sovereignty over the
waterway.
   Velayati said Iraq was ``facing a lot of internal difficulties
because people ask them, why did you start this 8-year-old war, for
what reason?''
   ``We think this is the main reason they are looking for some
advantage, some concessions,'' he said.
   The Shatt-al-Arab has been blocked by sunken ships since the
outbreak of the war.
   Aziz said Monday the waterway should be cleared as soon as
possible to balance the advantage gained by Iran when Iraq stopped
attacks on Iranian shipping under the terms of an Aug. 20
cease-fire.
   Aziz also complained of Iran's continued searches of Iraqi-bound
vessels in the Persian Gulf.
   Velayati said the clearing of the Shatt-al-Arab should come ``at
an appropriate time, after all the provisions of the cease-fire
have bneen implemented.''
   ``We do not think that a deadlock has been reached,'' the
Iranian minister said. ``We do hope that the secretary-general can
find a solution for such difficulties.''
   He said he would remain in Geneva ``as long as the
secretary-general will be here and asks us to remain here.'' Aziz
made a similar declaration the previous day.
</TEXT>
