<FILEID>AP-NR-08-30-88 1934EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-JacksonVideo     08-30 0326</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson Video,0336</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Out-of-Court Settlement Reached IN Jackson Video Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH SHOGREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former presidential hopeful Jesse Jackson has
reached an out-of-court settlement with a company that sold
thousands of videotapes of his address to the Democratic National
Convention, attorneys said Tuesday.
   ``Yes, there has been a settlement,'' said Eric Cohen, an
attorney for MPI Home Video. ``But I believe the terms are
confidential.''
   Jackson's attorney, Henry Mason, also refused to discuss the
agreement, and both sides refused to say whether it would allow the
sale or distribution of more MPI tapes of Jackson's speech.
   ``The parties have reached an agreement in principle,'' Mason
said. ``We hope to wrap it up in the next 10 days or so.''
   The settlement avoided a trial, which had been scheduled to
begin Tuesday, over whether MPI had the right to profit from tapes
of Jackson's July 19 speech in Atlanta.
   MPI sold about 7,500 of the videotapes, at $14.95 each, before
U.S. District Judge James B. Zagel's temporary order July 29
brought a halt to the sales, said Robert Breisblatt, another
attorney for Oak Forest-based MPI. Breisblatt said he did not know
exactly how long the videotapes had been on sale before then, but
he estimated it was less than week.
   Mason said Jackson's camp, which had gone to court to block the
sales, was pleased with the settlement.
   MPI had contended that the black leader's speech was news and
unprotected by copyright law. But Jackson argued that the
videotapes exploited his name as well as his literary and
oratorical skills.
   He testified at an earlier hearing that MPI's tape, which he did
not authorize, hurt his livelihood by limiting the marketability of
a videotape of the speech that he planned to sell.
   Zagel, in his order halting the sales, agreed.
   ``There is ... more than negligible probability that (Jackson)
earns part of his living ... on his oratory,'' the judge said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
