<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Missiles     08-30 0230</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Missiles,0236</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Military Inspectors Complete Review of Missile
Destruction</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. inspectors ended a series of visits to Soviet
military bases under the Intermediate-Range Nuclear Forces missile
treaty, expressing pleasure with the openness the Kremlin afforded
them, Tass reported Tuesday.
   Brig. Gen. Roland Lajoie, director of the Pentagon's On-Site
Inspection Agency, said at a Moscow news conference te reception
accorded his team exceeded his expectations, the official news
agency said.
   Lt. Col. Laurence Kelly, another team member, said 15
inspections were made since July 1. In all in the East bloc,
American inspectors were scheduled to visit 133 sites as stipulated
in the treaty signed in December by President Reagan and Soviet
leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   The treaty requires both superpowers to eliminate their arsenals
of nuclear weapons with ranges of 300- to 3,400 miles.
   Soviet inspectors visited bases in West German, Belgium,
Britain, the Netherlands and the United States during the July
1-Aug. 29 inspection period.
   Lajoie said the inspectors looked at Soviet military facilities
to check on sites of deployment, and numbers and classes of
missiles to be destroyed, according to Tass.
   The Soviet Union has destroyed 22 medium-range and more than 50
shorter-range missiles so far under the treaty. The United States
is to destroy its first missile under the treaty on Sept. 8 at the
Longhorn Army Ammunitions plant near Marshall, Texas.
</TEXT>
