<2ND_LINE>AM-Air Show-Soviet,0228</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet MiG-29s Fly to Britain For Air Show, Escorted By RAF</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Air Show, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FARNBOROUGH, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Soviet MiG-29s did an impromptu
aerobatic display as they arrived in Britain on Tuesday for their
first public display in the West at an air show next week.
   Two British Tornado F3s intercepted the newest Soviet fighters
100 miles out over the North Sea and escorted them to Farnborough
in tight formation. The Tornados then peeled off to allow the
Soviets to carry out their short display before landing.
   The British and Soviet crews greeted each other on the ground
with warm smiles, handshakes, and pledges that safety would come
first at the Farnborough air show, following Sunday's fatal
accident at an exhibition at the U.S. Air Base at Ramstein in West
Germany.
   ``We consider safety to be the most important aspect of all,''
said Anatoly Kvotchur, chief test pilot with Mikoyan, the MiG-29's
makers, and the first to land in England.
   Wing Cmdr. Euan Black, 42, who welcomed the Soviet fighters to
Britain in his Tornado jet, agreed that safety was paramount.
   The Soviets have shown the MiG-29 privately in Finland but its
public debut in the West will be at Farnborough. Moscow is hoping
its twin-tailed, twin-engined fighter will impress the
international arms buyers visiting the week-long show.
</TEXT>
