<2ND_LINE>AM-Cow Theft,0227</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Military Rounds Up Rustlers After Popular Calf Sculpture Stolen</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ABILENE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rustlers who stole a little metal calf
didn't get far before a posse corralled them at the main gate of
Dyess Air Force Base.
   The calf is the smallest member of the popular ``Herd of Cows''
sculpture grazing near a fire station in this west Texas city.
   Valued at $1,000, the calf wasn't easy to steal. It was anchored
into concrete with large bolts that apparently were ripped loose.
The calf's left front ankle was bent, possibly during the theft
Monday.
   Two airmen were charged with third-degree felony theft, police
said Tuesday. The men, who posted $5,000 bail each, were Ricky
Cameron, 21, of Tempe, Ariz., and Carl David Edmondson, 22, whose
hometown was not known.
   The men were arrested and jailed overnight after police got a
call that two men in a white pickup were trying to siphon gas from
and damage vehicles at a hotel and apartment complex, Police Capt.
Ray Portalatin said.
   A witness noted the truck's license number and gave it to
police, who forwarded the number to the main gate at the air base.
   Military police stopped a pickup when it tried to drive onto the
base, Portalatin said. ``Lo and behold, there was a cow in it,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
