<DOCNO> AP880830-0140 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-30-88 2017EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Cubans     08-30 0494</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cubans,0506</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>More than 2,200 Cubans Released; Role of Riots Debated</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 2,200 Cuban detainees have been
released since last fall's riots at federal prisons in Atlanta and
Oakdale, La., and one advocate for the Cubans credits the uprisings
for their freedom.
   A former federal official, however, denies that the riots
speeded up the releases.
   ``It's unfortunate that it came to (a riot). But 2,200 of the
3,800 (in custody before the riots last November) have been
released because of the public attention the riot attracted,'' said
Gary Leshaw, an Atlanta attorney who advised the Cubans. ``The
lesson is that the government should have instituted a legitimate
review plan years before it did.''
   But Randy Levine, a former associate U.S. attorney general who
helped set up the review process that decides the detainees' fates,
said that a repatriation agreement reached last fall by the United
States and and Cuba would have had a similar effect without the
riots.
   ``It would have been set up anyway, and I think the speed (of
the releases) would have been maintained,'' he said.
   ``To say that the riot had no impact in bringing this to the
public's attention would be wrong. But to say that the riot set the
review process in place is not fair,'' Levine said.
   Final appeals are scheduled to begin this week in Washington for
the first of 73 Cuban detainees who were found to be deportable
through the review process.
   George W. Calhoun, director of the Justice Department's Mariel
Cuban review program, said he expects some cases to be decided by
late September. That could mean the deportation of some Cubans
within six weeks.
   The detainees were among more than 125,000 Cubans who came to
the United States in the 1980 Mariel boatlift. They were jailed
after their arrival because they committed crimes or were
considered risks for other reasons.
   Although more than 2,200 Cuban detainees have been released
since the riots, an additional 1,000 have been taken into federal
custody, most of them after serving time in state prisons.
   More than 2,500 Cubans are in federal custody, and the
Immigration and Naturalization Service has decided that more than
1,500 of them are too dangerous to return to society.
   Even among those inmates, few are in imminent danger of being
deported, however. Cuba has agreed to take back only people named
on a list which was compiled in 1984 and is considered outdated now.
   Calhoun said only about 500 of 2,746 people on the list are
still being held by federal authorities. Duke Austin, an INS
spokesman, said Cubans who are not on the list can be deported only
after further negotiations with the Cuban government.
   Austin said the detainees being released are not being given an
immigration status but are being ``re-paroled.'' ``As long as they
don't commit a crime, they could conceivably remain here in the
United States for the rest of their days,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
