<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel     08-30 0683</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel,0709</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lebanese Villagers Help Israelis Repel Guerrillas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MASHA HAMILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lebanese villagers helped Israeli troops and
local militia drive back a Palestinian guerrilla squad trying to
infiltrate Israel Tuesday, the army and Israel radio said. Two
guerrillas were captured and two escaped.
   In the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip, Palestinians began a
two-day strike to protest deportations. Arab hospital officials
said troops wounded 12 Palestinians in West Bank clashes, 10 of
them in Nablus.
   The infiltration attempt was the 17th reported since
Palestinians began rebelling against Israeli rule nearly nine
months ago.
   The uprising has killed 255 Palestinians and four Israelis since
Dec. 8.
   Israel radio identified the guerrillas as members of a small
pro-Syrian Palestinian faction, the Popular Struggle Front.
   A firefight broke out after Lebanese villagers from Khalata, 2{
miles north of the Israeli border, spotted the squad walking out of
a ravine and moving across a field, Israel radio and military
sources said.
   Ten Lebanese men in the village armed themselves and villagers
summoned Lebanese militiamen from the mostly Christian South
Lebanon Army, who were backed by Israeli troops from border zone
patrols, the reports said.
   The army said two guerrillas were captured and two escaped, one
after being wounded.
   Two Lebanese militiamen were slightly wounded, the radio said.
   It was the first time Israel has reported that Lebanese
villagers helped thwart a border crossing.
   An army statement said an investigation showed ``the terrorists
planned to take hostages in one of the settlements in the northern
Galilee.''
   The intruders carried barbed wire cutters, three Soviet-made
rifles, a pistol with a silencer, four hand grenades, three
rocket-propelled grenade lauchers and food and medical supplies.
   Israel ended a three-year occupation of Lebanon in 1985 but
maintains about 1,000 soldiers in its self-declared security zone
to lend support to the South Lebanon Army.
   The army said youths stoned an Israeli car in the West Bank
village of Anabta, slightly wounding one passenger in the head. In
Husan, near Bethlehem, troops rounded up residents and searched
homes after villagers stoned an Israeli bus, Arab reports said. The
army said it was checking the report.
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir personally intervened to have a
submachine gun returned to a Jewish settler in the West Bank.
Police confiscated the weapon last week after the man fired in the
air to disperse Palestinians stoning his car near a West Bank
refugee camp.
   Shamir ``believes that people who live in Judea and Samaria
(biblical names for the West Bank) should be allowed to carry
weapons for self-defense,'' said Shamir aide Avi Pazner.
   Israel radio on Tuesday quoted Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin as
saying that recently introduced plastic bullets would ease the
frustration of soldiers trying to quell violent protests. Rabin
addressed a closed-door session of Parliament's Defense and Foreign
Affairs Committee.
   A defense official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
live ammunition can be used only in self-defense, but officers may
fire plastic bullets in ``hot pursuit'' of Palestinian
demonstrators or to incapacitate ringleaders. Plastic bullets
penetrate the body but generally cause less serious injuries.
   Tuesday's strike in the occupied territories and east Jerusalem,
seized by Israel in the 1967 Middle East war, was the fifth such
protest in 10 days.
   Nablus was the scene of the most violent protests after a
five-day curfew was lifted at dawn.
   Troops trying to disperse stone-throwers shot and wounded 10
Palestinians, including two who were in serious condition, hospital
officials said. The army said five Arabs were hurt.
   Two Palestinians were wounded in two other West Bank clashes,
hospital officials said.
   The strike was to protest deportations of 33 Palestinians since
the uprising began, and Israeli orders to expell 25 others.
   In Jerusalem, about 150 Israeli leftists demonstrated near the
Supreme Court to protest deportations.
   The army clamped curfews on three refugee camps and a village in
the occupied lands, confining more than 100,000 Palestinians to
their homes.
   The army said Tuesday that 5,116 Palestinians now are being held
in Israeli jails, including 2,516 held for up to six months without
trial.
</TEXT>
