<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Stanley-Protests 1stLd-Writethru a0625 08-30 0408</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Stanley-Protests, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0625,0416</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former SBC Head Says Abortion Protesters Should Use Lawful Means</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Adds 1 graf to include Falwell's stand.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former president of the Southern Baptist
Convention said that while abortion is ``an abomination before
God,'' he opposes tactics of the anti-abortion protesters that have
led to hundreds of arrests this summer.
   The Rev. Charles Stanley, pastor of the First Baptist Church of
Atlanta, issued the two-page treatise Sunday saying abortion should
be protested only through lawful means.
   The leaflet, ``A Biblical Perspective on Civil Disobedience,''
said it represents the ``carefully studied view of the pastoral
staff and deacons'' of the church, the state's largest Baptist
congregation.
   In the leaflet, the ministers reaffirmed the Southern Baptist
stance against abortion, saying, ``We strongly oppose abortion as
an abomination before God. We also advocate all lawful means of
protesting abortion.''
   More than 700 demonstrators have been arrested in Atlanta in
protests organized by the New York-based Operation Rescue since the
group arrived during the Democratic National Convention in July.
   The leaflet, which Stanley read from the pulpit, cites biblical
grounds for disobeying the law and concludes that Operation
Rescue's tactics fail in three areas:
   _Protesters have been charged with criminal trespassing,
obstructing rights of way or other similar ordinances _ not for
directly preventing abortions. ``If certain anti-God protesters
blocked the entrance to (the church) so we could not enter to
worship, we would use the same ordinance to have them arrested!''
   _The U.S. Supreme Court decision legalizing abortion ``neither
requires abortions nor prohibits them, but makes them permissible
with certain restrictions.''
   _Women are ``free moral agents responsible before Almighty God
for their actions, including the exercise of the rights of their
innocent, unborn child.''
   Operation Rescue leader Randall Terry, who has directed his
demonstrations mostly with the help of clergy and supporters from
outside Atlanta, responded:
   ``We are glad Dr. Stanley agrees that abortion is murder. We
wish he could also see that Operation Rescue is not about protest
or civil disobedience. It is about saving the lives of babies
scheduled to be murdered.''
   Stanley had been silent on the issue of civil disobedience since
watching a protest several weeks ago where his friend Jerry
Falwell, the Moral Majority founder and an independent Baptist,
appeared and offered his endorsement. Falwell, who gave Operation
Rescue $10,000, said he would return to be arrested and had
predicted that Stanley would join the protests.
</TEXT>
