<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Pepper-Bush     08-30 0305</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pepper-Bush,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congressman Dubs GOP `Uncola' Ticket</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Rep. Claude Pepper borrowed
Tuesday from Madison Avenue as he went to work for the Democratic
ticket, telling senior citizens that Vice President George Bush and
running mate Sen. Dan Quayle are ``the Un-COLA team.''
   Pepper told more than 200 people that Quayle in the past seven
years voted eight times to freeze or cut Social Security
cost-of-living-adjustments, while Bush, in his role as head of the
Senate, in 1985 cast the tie-breaking vote to freeze ``COLAS'' in a
budget resolution.
   ``You might call this Republican team the Un-Cola team of
America, and you know Americans like colas,'' Pepper said, taking
off on the soda pop advertising in a speech that marked the
beginning of his planned nationwide campaigning for the Democratic
ticket of Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis and Sen. Lloyd Bentsen.
   He said Dukakis lobbied for the ``Pepper bill,'' defeated in
June in the U.S. House, to provide long-term home health care for
the chronically ill. Dukakis has pledged to seek its passage as
president, Pepper said, while Bentsen sponsored similar legislation
in the Senate.
   Pepper called Bush ``a very fine gentleman'' with ``a lovely
wife,'' but said Bush ``has to carry on his shoulders a Reagan
administration without Reagan.''
   He recalled that at a meeting in Philadelphia in 1980, candidate
Reagan promised not to cut senior programs, but didn't keep his
word. Pepper said Bush followed an administration philosophy that
has hurt millions of people.
   He said Quayle's voting record ``is just totally opposite of the
best interests of senior citizens.''
   The crowd, led by Miami Beach Mayor Alex Daoud, serenaded Pepper
with ``Happy Birthday.'' He turns 88 on Sept. 8, and promised a
public birthday celebration Sept. 10 at Miami's Bayfront Park.
</TEXT>
