<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Laos-Drugs     08-30 0474</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Laos-Drugs,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Praises Laos for Drug Crackdown</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department praised the Laotian
government Tuesday for its recent arrest and conviction of 48
persons on drug smuggling charges.
   While crediting Laos with ``strong action against drug
traffickers,'' department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley said some
Laotian authorities may be promoting narcotics trafficking with the
support of the central government.
   She said that among those convicted was a member of the
Communist Party Central Committee who also served as a provincial
governor. He was given a seven-year sentence.
   The department's position Tuesday differed from its conclusion
in a report prepared last spring that Laos was the only nation
``for which the preponderance of information suggests that the
government promotes drug trafficking as a matter of policy.''
   The report, which covered several countries suspected of
involvement in drug smuggling, was dated May 1. The National
Security Council ordered it withheld from members of Congress until
last week because it contained sensitive information. The study was
released to the media Tuesday.
   One U.S. official, who spoke only on condition of anonymity,
said recent actions by Laotian authorities indicates their attitude
on the drug issue may be changing.
   The May report said there was coordinated participation among
Laotian government officials in drug smuggling and suggested this
could not have taken place without the approval of authorities in
Vientiane.
   ``Specifically, the U.S. finds that Laotian officials have
become involved directly in the processing of opium and marijuana,
including three marijuana processing centers run by government
organizations and at least four sanctioned heroin laboratories,''
the report said.
   The government also allows independent traffickers to operate on
Laotian territory, said the study, which observed that large
portions of the country are not under Vientiane's effetive control.
   It said the Northern Lao Import@Export Co. is a government
agency suspected of marketing narcotics abroad. The Mountain Area
Development Co., described as a state enterprise controlled by the
military, is alleged to be the chief agency involved in narcotics
trafficking, the report said.
   Governments found to be engaged in drug smuggling are subject to
U.S. sanctions prescribed by Congress. But no action was taken
against Laos because President Reagan decided that Laotian
cooperation in accounting for missing American servicemen might
otherwise be impaired.
   In any case, sanctions imposed against Laos would be largely
symbolic because Laos receives no U.S. assistance.
   The administration has concluded that Panamanian leader Gen.
Manuel Antonio Noriega, commander of Panama's Defense Forces, has
engaged in drug smuggling activities. But the report said Noriega
``is not a senior official'' of Panama because the United States
regards the ousted government of President Eric Arturo Delvalle as
the legitimate authority in Panama.
   Therefore, Noriega was considered beyond the scope of the
report, which is aimed primarily at government officials who engage
in drug trafficking.
</TEXT>
