<1ST_LINE>r w AM-CropLoans     08-30 0306</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Crop Loans,290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Agriculture Dept. Says Some Support Loans Won't Be Extended</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department said Tuesday it
will not extend certain crop price support loans made to farmers,
including some that begin to come due on Aug. 31.
   Milton Hertz, executive vice president of the department's
Commodity Credit Corp., said the action is consistent with loan
extension decisions that the Agriculture Department announced in
January and March.
   The proposal leading up to the decision has been criticized as
heavy-handed by some farm groups, and is involved in a legal
challenge by a group of farmers in U.S. District Court in St. Paul,
Minn.
   In the past, the department has frequently allowed farmers to
extend their regular nine-month price support loans for an
additional year or longer as a way of keeping surplus grain off the
market.
   When ``locked up'' in the loan program, or in the farmer-owned
reserve or FOR, grain cannot be sold on the market until the loan
is settled. When the loans come due, farmers have the option paying
the loans in full or forfeiting their crops to the Commodity Credit
Corp.
   Hertz said the following loans will not be extended:
   _1987 and subsequent crop price support regular loans for feed
grains, rice, soybeans and wheat.
   _1985 and 1986 crop extended loans of wheat, barley, oats and
soybeans.
   _1983 and prior crop-year loans for commodities in the FOR.
   _Special producer loans.
   Hertz said the following loans can be extended at the producer's
option for one year:
   _1985 and 1986 crop corn and sorghum extended loans which mature
on March 31 through Dec. 31 this year.
   _1984 crop FOR loans which mature on March 31 through Dec. 31
this year.
   In addition, he said, 1987 crops of wheat and feed grains will
not be permitted to enter the FOR.
</TEXT>
