<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0341</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Showers Along the East Coast As Seasonably Mild Weather Continues</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Most of the nation enjoyed pleasant weather in the 70s and 80s
Tuesday, but showers and a few thunderstorms were scattered along
the southern Atlantic coast and in parts of Texas and Colorado.
   In the East, rain fell along a cold front stretching from the
Carolinas to the Gulf Coast, with thunderstorms along the North
Carolina coast and in west-central and southeast Georgia and
northeast Florida.
   More than a quarter-inch of rain fell at the Naval Air Station
near Key West, Fla., and at Bluefield, W.Va., in the six hours
ended at 2 p.m. EDT.
   Showers and isolated thunderstorms also developed over
west-central Texas and in central Colorado. With thunderstorms
expected once again over the mountain and desert areas of Southern
California, the National Weather Service posted a flash flood watch
for the area until evening.
   Farther north, light rain showers moved from eastern Iowa across
southern Wisconsin and northern Illinois.
   Temperatures were seasonably mild, in the 70s and 80s across
much of the country, though lower in the northern Great Lakes
region and parts of New England and in the Pacific Northwest.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 55
degrees at Arcata, Calif., to 103 degrees at Palm Springs, Calif.
The low in the nation Tueday morning was 32 degrees at Jackson, Wyo.
   For Wednesday, scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecast
from the southern Atlantic states across Florida and the Gulf
Coast. Showers and thunderstorms were expected to develop in the
afternoon west of the southern Rockies, across the mountains and
into western Texas, as well as over eastern Minnesota and northwest
Wisconsin.
   Temperatures were expected to be higher than Tuesday's _ in the
80s or 90s across much of the nation, but in the 70s from the upper
Great Lakes through the upper Ohio Valley and central Appalachians
into New England and between 100 and 110 in the desert Southwest.
</TEXT>
