<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Soviet,0214</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet MiG-29s Fly Into Britain For Air Show, Escorted By RAF</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FARNBOROUGH, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Soviet MiG-29s did some
impromptu aerobatics Tuesday as they arrived for their first public
performance in the West at next week's Farnborough air show.
   Two British Tornado F3s met the newest Soviet fighters 100 miles
out and escorted them from the North Sea to Farnborough in tight
formation. The Tornados peeled off to let the Soviets put on a
brief show before landing.
   British and Soviet crews greeted each other on the ground with
smiles, handshakes and pledges that safety would come first after
Sunday's air show disaster at the U.S. Air Force base at Ramstein,
West Germany.
   ``We consider safety to be the most important aspect of all,''
said Anatoly Kvotchur, chief test pilot for MiG-29 manufacturer
Mikoyan and the first Soviet to land.
   Wing Commander Euan Black, 42, who welcomed the Soviet fighters
in his Tornado jet, agreed that safety was paramount.
   The Soviets have shown the MiG-29 privately in Finland but its
public debut in the West will be at Farnborough. Moscow hopes its
twin-tailed, twin-engined fighter will impress the hundreds of
international arms buyers at the week-long exhibition, the most
important on this year's international aerospace calendar.
</TEXT>
