<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon,0283</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Car Bomb Explosion Kills Boy, Wounds Seven Children in Bekaa</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Bank name cq</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RIMA SALAMEH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A car bomb exploded Tuesday in Chtoura, a
Syrian-controlled market town in east Lebanon, killing a 7-year-old
boy and wounding seven other children aged 3 to 8, police said
reported.
   The white Volvo exploded at 1 p.m. near a bank office on the
Beirut-Damascus road, the main route used by the Syrian army to
supply its forces in Lebanon.
   No one claimed responsibility for Lebanon's the 12th car bomb of
the year. By police count, the earlier bombings killed 103 people
and wounded 371.
   Police said the children were playing behind a tree when 44
pounds of TNT inside the car detonated. The explosion broke windows
in shops and apartment buildings and five other parked cars ablaze.
   Syria is the main power broker in Lebanon and keeps 40,000
soldiers in east Lebanon's Bekaa Valley, north Lebanon and in
Moslem west Beirut.
   Tuesday's explosion appeared to be one of several in the past
two weeks aimed at discrediting Syria's peacekeeping role while
Lebanon chooses a new president. At least nine explosive charges
have gone off near Syrian army checkpoints in west Beirut, causing
damage but no casualties.
   President Amin Gemayel's six-year term expires Sept. 23 and he
cannot seek a new term. Parliament was to elect a new president
Aug. 18, but the election was postponed for lack of a quorum and no
new date was set.
   The deadlock caused political turmoil and threatened to rekindle
a 13-year-old sectarian civil war that has been largely dormant for
the past 18 months.
</TEXT>
