<2ND_LINE>AM-Salvador-Duarte,0204</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Duarte Resumes Duties in Palace</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Jose Napoleon Duarte,
convalescing from cancer, resumed his duties Tuesday and received
the credentials of the new U.S. ambassador.
   Duarte looked gaunt and tired as he posed briefly for
photographers with Ambassador William Walker. He made no comment to
journalists and spent 10 minutes with Walker, who replaces Edwin
Corr.
   The 62-year-old president, who has incurable liver cancer, has
had two week-long chemotherapy sessions at Johns Hopkins Hospital
in Washington since the diagnosis in June. He has lost 35 pounds
this month and has been in bed since returning Aug. 10.
   A week after returning, he took a turn for the worse because of
complications caused by diabetes but his doctors and government
spokesmen have said the crisis was overcome.
   When the cancer was diagnosed, Duarte's doctors gave him between
six and 18 months to live. His presidential term ends June 1, 1989.
   Foreign Minister Ricardo Acevedo Peralta told journalists
outside the palace Duarte was ``in good spirits'' but also ``weak,
naturally.''
   He said the president will gauge how much work he can handle and
try to make a manageable schedule.
