<2ND_LINE>AM-Air Show-Survivors,0333</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four American Survivors Flown Home</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Air Show Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RAMSTEIN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four Americans who suffered severe
burns but survived the Ramstein air show disaster left for Texas
Tuesday aboard a special U.S. Air Force transport plane.
   ``These are the most badly burned Americans survivors able to be
moved,'' said Maj. Kathy White, a spokeswoman for the U.S. Air
Force base at Ramstein. They were the first American victims of
Sunday's tragedy evacuated to the United States.
   The Air Force said three were soldiers and the fourth was a
woman ``dependent of an American serviceman.''
   It identified the soldiers as Air Force Master Sgt. Stephen
Hull, 32; Army 1st Lt. Kim Strader, 30; and Army Pfc. Myron Riggs,
24, and the woman only as Anderea Delarosa. No hometowns were given.
   Surgeons and other medical personnel clad in blue and yellow
surgical gowns and wearing masks took nearly an hour to move the
four victims from a military ambulance onto a giant C-141 transport.
   ``The C-141 is a heavy transport plane especially adapted for
medical evacuations,'' Maj. White said.
   It left at about 7 p.m. (1 p.m. EDT) on the 13-hour flight to
the Brook Army Medical Center at San Antonio, Texas, which
specializes in treating burn injuries.
   The patients, with intravenous bottles held over them, were
covered with blankets as they were carried aboard the plane on
stretchers.
   Reporters and television crews were kept at a distance and Air
Force guards ringed the aircraft. Medical edquipment was loaded
aboard the plane.
   A five-member medical team flown from San Antonio to Ramstein on
Monday night accompanied the victims and five other medical
personnel were on the aircraft, including two doctors.
   The four victims were brought from the U.S. Army's Landstuhl
hospital, about 2{ miles from the air base. They arrived in a blue
Air Force bus, converted into a stretcher carrier, with a police
escort.
</TEXT>
