<2ND_LINE>AM-Irish, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0705,0704</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soldiers Fatally Shoot Three Armed Men Near IRA Bombing Site</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 13 grafs to UPDATE with Sinn Fein saying the dead
were IRA members, other details; picks up 7th pvs: The bus...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDONDERRY, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soldiers fatally shot three
armed men in a car Tuesday, a few miles from the spot where an
Irish Republican Army bomb killed eight soldiers on a bus and
injured 27 others.
   The IRA's legal political wing Sinn Fein issued a statement
saying the dead were IRA members, Brian Mullen and brothers Gerard
and Martin Harte.
   Mullen was a brother of one of eight men held for questioning
following the Aug. 20 bus bombing. All those questioned were
released without charge on Monday.
   The shooting in Omagh, 50 miles west of Belfast, was seen as
part of a stepped-up British response to the IRA's summer campaign
against the army and police, which has killed 27 members of the
security forces and triggered a wave of outrage in Britain and in
the province.
   Also Tuesday, two buses and a van were hijacked and set afire in
Roman Catholic west Belfast, but no casualties were reported. Four
mortar bombs and 25 pounds of explosives were found aboard a bus
crossing the border from the Republic of Ireland, said police in
Londonderry.
   A police spokesman said two rifles were recovered at the scene
of the shooting that took place at about 4 p.m. (11 a.m. EDT).
   ``The incident occurred when soldiers encountered armed men in a
vehicle and opened fire,'' he said. He said officials had not yet
identified the three bodies. He released no further details.
   A British army spokesman, unidentified in keeping with British
practice, said security forces sealed off roads leading into the
surrounding area where the three men were slain as police gathered
forensic evidence.
   Press Association, the British domestic news agency, quoting
unidentified military sources, said the SAS, the elite Special Air
Services regiment, was involved in the shooting. The army said its
policy prohibits confirming whether soldiers of the SAS took part.
   Local residents reported seeing a military helicopter pick up
four men in civilian clothes and whisk them away minutes after the
shooting.
   A man and a woman claiming to be a brother and sister of two of
the dead men, drove up to the police cordon and the man shouted at
the officers: ``They were gunned down by dogs _ they were set up by
the SAS!''
   The women added: ``They may have gunned down three, but a lot
more will go for them!''
   The police spokesman said Tuesday's shootings occurred on the
main road from Omagh to Carrickmore, a few miles away from the site
of the Aug. 20 bombing which exploded near the British army bus.
   The bus bomb dealt the army in Northern Ireland its worst blow
since 1982, and brought to 26 the military death toll in a summer
of IRA attacks in Ulster, mainland Britain and continental Europe.
   The outlawed IRA is fighting to end British rule in
Protestant-dominated Northern Ireland and unite the province with
the Irish Republic, which is predominantly Roman Catholic.
   The bombs and Czechoslovakian-made Semtex explosives discovered
earlier Tuesday were on a bus owned by the Lough Swilly Co., a
private bus service, when it was stopped and searched at a border
checkpoint, a police spokesman said.
   They were found in luggage in the passenger compartment, said
the spokesman, who also spoke on condition of anonymity.
   He said the bus driver and passengers were being questioned but
no arrests were made.
   The discovery followed a weekend of bombings, shootings, riots
and other violence in Belfast, Londonderry and Newry that was
sparked by the extradition from Ireland to Northern Ireland of a
convicted guerrilla and jail escapee.
   The IRA led the violent protests over Robert Russell's
extradition, police said.
   Security forces in Northern Ireland have said the IRA received
Semtex, a lightweight and difficult to detect explosive, in arms
shipments from Libya. Britain has held discussions with
Czechoslovakia about making it more difficult for the IRA to obtain
Semtex.
</TEXT>
