<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Ghana-American     08-30 0387</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ghana-American,0399</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Businessman, Ghanaians Charged as Parrot Smugglers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ACCRA, Ghana (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American businessman Darrell Marion
Alexander and two Ghanaians have pleaded innocent to charges of
trying to export 2,000 African gray parrots to the United States
illegally.
   Alexander, identified as managing director of Exotic Fauna
International, and Ghanaian wildlife exporters Christian Leslie
Mills and Wabi Bello were held over for court appearances Wednesday.
   They entered pleas Monday before a national public tribunal
where each faced a 25-count charge, including ``acts detrimental to
the welfare of the sovereign people of Ghana.''
   A month ago, the Record newspaper of Lompoc, Calif., quoted
relatives as saying Alexander, 46, of the Los Angeles suburb of La
Crescenta, went to Ghana in November and got all the necessary
permits for exporting the gray parrots.
   They said Exotic Fauna International is a bird import company
based in Los Angeles and sanctioned by the U.S. Department of
Agriculture, the paper reported.
   ``We consider him a hostage, not a criminal,'' Alexander's
nephew Mark, a resident of Lompoc, was quoted as saying.
   At the Democratic National Convention July 19 in Atlanta, about
a dozen onlookers and reporters watched when Darrell Alexander's
family took the podium to urge that he be released from jail in
Ghana.
   Ghanaian authorities said June 13 that Alexander and another
American were arrested after Lt. Cmdr. K. Assassie-Gyimah, a senior
government official, discovered the birds squawking in an airplane
hold. The other American was not identified and was neither
mentioned nor present at the court proceeding Monday.
   Exporting African gray parrots from Ghana is illegal.
   The gpverment accuses Alexander of paying more than 6 million
cedis ($200,000) to the Ghanaians, who are accused of bribing
officials for phony export permits.
   The African gray parrot, once common in West African forests, is
noted for its ability to learn to talk quickly. Excessive trapping
of the birds and destruction of their habitat have made them scarce.
   Alexander's brother Alvin of Las Vegas, Nev., was quoted by the
Lompoc paper as saying he visited the military compound in Ghana
where his brother was held and found prisoners ``chained together
and beaten with hoses, and they sleep in cells with dirt floors.''
   The State Department in Washington said that consular officials
visited Darrell Alexander many times and found him to be all right.
</TEXT>
