<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Eastern-Unions     08-30 0453</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Eastern-Unions,0466</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Labor Says It's Pleased With Judge's Ruling</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Eastern, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines' labor leaders embraced a federal
judge's ruling Tuesday that blocked layoffs of 4,000 employees,
although it allows the company to go ahead with service cutbacks.
   ``We're please at this ruling. It will save 4,000 jobs (and it
rules that) the proposed furloughing is illegal,'' said Charles E.
Bryan, president of District 100 of the Machinists union, Eastern's
largest with 12,000 workers.
   Bryan, flight attendants' leader Mary Jane Barry and pilots
local vice chairman Dan Vician talked to reporters at the Transport
Workers Union hall just off the Miami International Airport as
their attorneys studied the 50-page opinion by U.S. District Judge
Barrington Parker in Washington.
   Eastern, while satisfied that Parker will allow the closing of
its Kansas City hub and the elimination of 140 flights, said it
will appeal his decision that the company cannot make mass layoffs
without bargaining with its unions.
   Bryan called the decision ``an opportunity'' for Texas Air Corp.
Chairman Frank Lorenzo to show he is more than ``the No. 1
union-buster.''
   ``Here now is a chance for him to change his style. The ball is
in Frank Lorenzo's court,'' Bryan said.
   He and the other union leaders expressed willingness to meet
with management to discuss cost-cutting measures that preserve jobs.
   ``We're not here as laborers trying to direct the business of
the airline. We're trying to protect jobs,'' Vician said.
   Ms. Barry said the flight attendants were still willing to offer
a job-sharing and leave plan, rejected earlier by management, to
save jobs and money.
   Eastern spokeswoman Paula Musto said she couldn't comment on the
unions' interpretation of the opinion.
   The union leaders stressed Parker's findings of fact that Texas
Air, which took over Miami-based Eastern two years ago, has been
antagonistic toward unions, tried to spin off assets such as the
Northeast shuttle service and has worsened Eastern's financial
problems by using Eastern resources to pay for its own sale, taking
a non-interest $16 million note from Eastern and taking a $6
million annual management fee from Eastern.
   ``In short, the record shows that Eastern has served as a
lending institution to meet the needs of Texas Air and Continental
(the non-union carrier also owned by Houston-based Texas Air),''
the opinion said.
   ``It confirmed what we've been saying,'' Bryan said. ``This is a
federal judge. It's not the unions anymore or our consultants
talking.''
   Eastern is cutting 140 flights and service from 14 cities, while
reducing its Kansas City hub from 53 to six flights and non-hub
status. Ms. Musto said the company hasn't determined what it will
do with the protected employees.
</TEXT>
