<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Colombia-Drugs     08-30 0500</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Colombia-Drugs,0517</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Panama Participates In U.S.-Backed Drug Sweep</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-International-Drugs, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Panama was among the 30 nations that
participated in a U.S.-backed drug crackdown, even though the
United States brought economic sanctions against the country
because of drug charges against its military leader.
   Colombian narcotics officials, meanwhile, were skeptical about
the success of the joint drug crackdown. They said no major
traffickers were arrested in the operations from Aug. 1-28 and the
amounts of drugs seized were not impressive.
   The U.S. Drug Enforcement Agency had encouraged the 30 countries
to step up enforcement and specifically to cooperate in
cross-border raids, mostly in South America, during August.
   DEA head John C. Lawn praised the anti-drug campaign and said it
showed that international cooperation could eliminate sanctuaries
for drug traffickers who tried to evade capture by going to other
countries.
   Lawn and other representatives made brief statements during a
meeting with reporters, but journalists were not allowed to ask
questions.
   The Bogota meeting coincided with a report in Washington on the
results of the operations by the International Drug Enforcement
Conference.
   U.S. Attorney General Richard Thornburgh said in Washington that
the raids led to more than 1,200 arrests, the seizure of 11 tons of
cocaine and the destruction of 244 tons of marijuana, 118,000 coca
plants and 13 cocaine laboratories.
   The Panamanian delegate to the Bogota meeting, Lt. Col. Nivaldo
Madrinan, said in his statement that Panama participated in the
program even though it is ``suffering the greatest aggression in
its history.'' He did not specifically mention the U.S. sanctions.
   Panama's military leader, Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega, was
indicted in February by two federal grand juries in Florida that
accused him of drug trafficking. The United States imposed economic
sanctions against Panama after Noriega refused to resign and leave
the country.
   Noriega, commander of Panama's Defense Forces, controls the
civilian government.
   Madrinan said the month-long drug crackdown in Panama produced
96 arrests and the seizure of 4.8 pounds of cocaine, $2,084, eight
vehicles and eight weapons.
   Reporters were now allowed to ask who had been arrested.
   Panama, Peru, Ecuador, Brazil, Colombia and Venezuela sent
delegates to the Bogota meeting.
   Colombian officials, speaking with the condition they not be
identified, noted the DEA reported the raids turned up 13 cocaine
laboratories and they said more than 13 labs are frequently found
in a single week in Colombia.
   The DEA report said that of the 11 tons of cocaine and cocaine
base seized, 6.2 tons were found in South American countries. The
Colombian officials said that in one raid in Colombia five years
ago more than 10 tons of cocaine and cocaine base were seized.
   The Colombians also questioned a section of the DEA statement
that said the raids were the result of cooperation among the
participating countries.
   They said cross-border operations between Venezuela and Colombia
were a week late because of border disputes and claimed Venezuela
did virtually nothing during the campaign.
</TEXT>
