<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ShuttleSchedule     08-30 0162</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shuttle Schedule,150</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Launch Of Space Telescope Being Delayed For Seven Months</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NASA's most ambitious scientific project,
putting the $1.5 billion Hubble Space Telescope into orbit, is
being delayed by seven months because of postponements in the
flight of Discovery, the space agency said Tuesday.
   Discovery's mission, the first since the Challenger exploded in
1986, has been postponed five times. NASA is hedging on a new date,
but said it hopes to begin the flight in late September or early
October.
   The space telescope was scheduled for launch June 1 next year
from Discovery. Instead, it has been moved to Feb. 1, 1990.
   The revised payload schedule, NASA said, will enable it to
launch three major scientific probes: Magellan, a probe to map the
planet Venus, in April 1989; Galileo, a cooperative project with
Germany to survey Jupiter and its moons, scheduled for October
1989; and Ulysses, a cooperative project with the European Space
Agency, in October 1990.
</TEXT>
