<HEAD>Amateur Photographer Captures Crash On Film</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Air Show, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos FRA13,15,17,19, LaserColor FRA18</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An amateur photographer took
still photos of the deadly crash at Ramstein during the weekend,
but the pictures were not publicized until Tuesday, after they were
discovered by a developing lab.
   Georg Riedel had a 135mm lens on his camera when the accident
occurred Sunday at the U.S. Air Base in Ramstein, said Max Simon,
photo editor at the Frankfurt bureau of The Associated Press.
   ``He said he just went there for fun,'' said Simon.
   Three Italian jets collided during a stunt show at the base and
one of them crashed into spectators, killing at least 49 people and
injuring hundreds, officials said.
   After the accident Riedel, a government employee who lives in
Karlsruhe, drove home and went to sleep, Simon quoted him as saying.
   ``On Monday he went to a color lab to have the pictures
developed,'' Simon said. ``The woman working at the lab saw how
dramatic the pictures were.''
   Simon said the woman knew the AP stringer for the area and
contacted him.
   ``The stringer then tracked Riedel down, but it took him awhile
to get in touch with him,'' Simon said.
