<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HospitalCloses 1stLd-Writethru a0609 08-30 0355</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hospital Closes, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0609,0362</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Hospitals Announce Plans To Shut Down</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with second, rural hospital closing, more
comment and background statistics</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH SHOGREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A large inner-city hospital and a tiny rural one
Tuesday joined the growing number of community hospitals across the
nation forced to close their doors because they can't make ends
meet.
   St. Anne's Hospital, which has 437 beds, is the 10th community
hospital in Chicago to shut down since 1986, officials said. It
will close its doors within a few weeks after 85 years of service
to the West Side, said spokeswoman Candace Hulsebus-Fong.
   White Hall Hospital, an acute-care facility with 30 beds in
southwestern Illinois, is the sixth small rural hospital to shut
down in the state since 1986, said Kenneth Robbins, president of
the Illinois Hospital Association.
   ``The fact that both of them were forced to close was no
coincidence at all, but the result of conscious decisions of
federal and state governments to underfund the Medicare and
Medicaid programs that pay for health care for the elderly and the
poor,'' Robbins said.
   In 1987, a record 79 community hospitals shut down across the
nation, five of them in Illinois, said Jan Shulman, a spokeswoman
for the American Hospital Asssociation.
   St. Anne's officials said the hospital has suffered from late
and inadequate federal reimbursement for its service to poor
patients.
   Illinois' Medicaid program, strapped for funds itself, owes the
hospital $1.7 million, they said.
   In April, St. Anne's laid off 60 percent of its staff to meet
expenses. Since then, it has used only 115 of its beds.
   About 80 percent of St. Anne's patients rely on Medicaid or
Medicare to pay their bills, Ms. Hulsebus-Fong said.
   ``Another 10 percent of those are indigent, so less than 10
percent have any kind of commercial insurance,'' she said.
   All but about 15 percent of White Hall's patients relied on
Medicaid or Medicare, said Glenn Klein, the hospital's
administrator.
   ``Our board just could not justify maintaining an operation that
lost money every single day of the week,'' he said.
</TEXT>
