<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush 3rdLd-Writethru a0703 08-30 0701</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0703,700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush: Dukakis Would Make Unilateral Cuts in Defense</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: To UPDATE with Fort Campbell appearance and comment about
Iran-Contra, DELETE 4th graf pvs, Later, he...Campbell, Ky.,
INSERTING three grafs after 6th pvs, The vice...President Carter,
and EDITING 7th pvs, The vice...United States, for transition.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROCKY MOUNT, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican presidential nominee George
Bush on Tuesday called rival Michael Dukakis ``another liberal
governor coming out of nowhere'' and suggested the Democrat would
advocate unilateral cuts in U.S. defense muscle.
   The vice president, continuing on the strong defense themes he
has been sounding over the past few days, sought to depict Dukakis
as inexperienced and weak on defense.
   Bush toured a Bendix defense plant where fuel systems are made
for fighter planes, and was shown a replica of the carburetor used
in the World War II fighter plane he had flown in the Navy.
   ``This plant keeps the muscle of our defense strong,'' Bush told
a group of plant employees. He suggested that Dukakis favors
``unilateral cuts in the muscle of the defense of the United
States.''
   The vice president earlier told a $500-a-ticket fund-raiser
that, while he didn't ``want anything to do with tearing down''
Dukakis, ``We should not gamble America's future on another liberal
governor coming out of nowhere.'' That was a reference to former
President Carter.
   Later, Bush repeated his theme in a speech to an American Legion
Post at Fort Campbell, Ky.
   ``If he doesn't want to modernize his snowblower, that's his
concern,'' Bush said, referring to the 25-year-old snowblower that
Dukakis keeps at home as a sign of his frugality. ``But if he
doesn't modernize our weapons systems, that puts the national
security of the United States in considerable risk.''
   And he said he had ``no response, none'' to a new attack by
Dukakis accusing him of being a hypocrite who sat idly by during
the Iran-Contra scandal.
   In his North Carolina appearance, the vice president also warned
against complacency in dealing with the Soviets _ despite recent
moves by Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev toward improved relations
with the United States.
   ``We cannot adopt a naive hope that just because Mr. Gorbachev
looks different and talks different, that there are fundamental
changes, because there aren't,'' he told the fund-raiser.
   And, in his speech at the Bendix plant, Bush said: ``I'm glad
there is change in the Soviet Union. But we better not let our
guard down.''
   The Republican nominee, speaking at a rally at North Carolina
Wesleyan College later in the day, praised his running mate,
Indiana Sen. Dan Quayle, who has come under close media scrutiny
over allegations that he and his wealthy family pulled strings to
get him into the National Guard at the height of the Vietnam War.
   ``I'm proud of my running mate,'' Bush told several thousand
students. ``It's nice to have a running mate going in the same
general direction as I am ... We'll do just fine.''
   At the outdoor campus rally, Bush was flanked by stock car
driver Cale Yarborough, a resident of South Carolina, and
conservative North Carolina Sen. Jesse Helms. ``All states will be
in safe hands with George Bush as president,'' Helms said.
   Bush, meanwhile, shed little light on the subject of
presidential debates, a touchy topic being negotiated in
Washington. Asked whether he would commit himself to more than two
debates, Bush said, ``There will be debates.''
   He also suggested that too many debates would be ``boring'' to
voters.
   The fund-raising brunch earlier in the day was held at the home
of Jack Laughery, president of Imasco, U.S.A., which owns the
Hardee's fast-food chain.
   Speaking to about 150 people outside the house, on a dreary,
rainy day, Bush conceded that Democrats held a solid voter
registration edge in North Carolina.
   ``You're talking to a guy who knows you can't win if you're
outnumbered. You need 51 percent,'' Bush said.
   The vice president said he was encouraged by recent ``polling
things'' showing him to be leading Dukakis.
   ``That's turned around now after our upbeat Republican
convention,'' Bush said.
   ``I think I am more clearly spelling out why I want to be
president,'' Bush said.
</TEXT>
