<HEAD>Ousted Panamanian President Visits Ocala, Buys Horses</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OCALA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The deposed but U.S.-recognized president of
Panama, Eric Arturo Delvalle, visited this central Florida
community to buy horses, a spokesman said Tuesday.
   Alberto Garcia de Paredes, the Panamanian consul general in New
York, said he and Delvalle have been in Ocala since Saturday to
attend the annual open sale of yearling thoroughbreds at the Ocala
Breeders Sales.
   A horseman whose family was a founder of a racetrack in Panama,
Delvalle bought a filly for $30,000 on Tuesday and a colt for
$20,000 on Monday. They will be sent to Panama next March after
training in Florida, said Garcia.
   The United States has continued to recognize Delvalle as
Panama's leader since he was ousted Feb. 26 by Gen. Manuel Antonio
Noriega after trying to fire the military ruler. Noriega was
indicted for drug smuggling in February by federal grand juries in
Tampa and Miami.
   Delvalle, who has been in hiding in Panama, is expected to meet
with U.S. officials during his visit to this country. But the Ocala
trip ``is something completely private,'' said Consul Roberto
Dominguez.
