<1ST_LINE>r i AM-PuertoRico-Drugs     08-30 0232</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Puerto Rico-Drugs,0238</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Coast Guard Halts Two Boats Loaded With Marijuana; One Sinks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PONCE, Puerto Rico, (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. Coast Guard ship arrived in
Puerto Rico Tuesday with one of two boats that were carrying $10
million worth of marijuana, officials reported.
   They said the first boat sank shortly after it was intercepted
Saturday in international waters and was being towed to Ponce on
Puerto Rico's southern coast.
   Coast Guard Capt. Dane Egli said the Honduras-registered,
30-foot boat Kiko was intercepted Saturday 70 miles north of
Colombia by the Coast Guard vessel Attu.
   ``As we towed it (the Kiko) to Ponce it sank. There were no
victims but most of its cargo of marijuana disappeared in the sea.''
   With the Kiko's crew of seven Colombians aboard, the Attu on
Monday stopped the Colombia-registered Grace Carolina 11 miles
south of Puerto Rico and detained its six Colombian crewmen.
Thirteen bundles of marijuana were confiscated.
   ``The two loads of marijuana ... were going to be brought into
Puerto Rico by the smugglers,'' said Egli. He estimated the street
value of the marijuana that was on both boats at $10 million.
   The Grace Carolina and 13 Colombians were brought to Ponce
Tuesday.
   ``We do this to earn a living because we don't have steady work
in our country,'' one of the Colombians shouted from the Attu where
he and the others were detained.
</TEXT>
