<HEAD>Swedish Navy Fires Depth Charges At Intruding Submarine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The navy fired depth charges at what it
believes was a foreign submarine prowling off west Sweden, a
defense spokesman said Tuesday.
   It was not clear if the vessel was hit late Monday or escaped
undamaged in the Stig Fiord, 27 miles north of Goteborg, said Maj.
Per Brissman.
   Patrol boats and coast artillery troops were searching for any
sign of the submarine, he added.
   The navy had been tracking the craft since the weekend, Brissman
told The Associated Press.
   Citing lack of proof, Sweden refuses to name the country it
suspects of repeatedly violating its territorial waters. But
defense analysts and military personnel have said traces left on
the sea bottom indicated the vessels were Soviet.
   Moscow denies the allegations and says its ships have stayed
away from Sweden since one submarine ran aground outside a Swedish
naval base in 1981.
