<2ND_LINE>AM-Yonkers Deseg, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0732,0700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Criminal Charges to Be Filed if High Court Reinstates Fines</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, `Another vote ...,' with 2 grafs to UPDATE
with no change in the council's position Tuesday night. INSERTS 1
graf after 10th graf pvs, ``We must ....' to UPDATE with Jesse
Jackson offer to meet with councilmen.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARLENE AIG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YONKERS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state agency that has taken over
Yonkers' finances warned four defiant councilmen Tuesday that
unless the U.S. Supreme Court takes their side, they will be hit
with criminal charges.
   The councilmen, who have stalled a federal judge's order to act
on a housing desegregation plan, have appealed both the judge's
ruling and asked for a stay of their fines until a decision comes
from the U.S. Supreme Court.
   The councilmen, who personally may have to pay contempt-of-court
fines of up to $500 a day, and the city, whose fines could go up to
$1 million daily, applied for stays to Supreme Court Justice
Thurgood Marshall, who often handles such appeals from the
Northeast. But a court spokesman said Tuesday afternoon the five
applications were turned over to the full court. The spokesman, who
asked not to be named, said he could give no indication when the
court might rule.
   For the third time since the contempt finding, the City Council,
at its regular meeting Tuesday night, refused to endorse the
desegregation plan, which would approve incentives for 800 units of
moderate-income housing throughout the city.
   In a packed Council chamber, Mayor Nicholas Wasicsko asked if
any of the councilmen wanted to change their vote but none of them
did. The mayor is required by the contempt ruling to have a weekly
vote on the desegregation plan.
   U.S. District Judge Leonard Sand, who in 1985 found the city
liable for segregating schools and housing for 40 years, held the
city in contempt Aug. 2 for failing to approve the housing plan.
Sand imposed fines against the city that began at $100 a day and
doubled daily. The fines were later stayed by a federal appeals
court.
   Besides the personal fines on the four councilmen, Sand also
threatened them with jail.
   On Friday, a federal appeals panel upheld the contempt finding
but gave Yonkers a week to take the case to the Supreme Court
before reinstating the penalties. The panel also capped any daily
fine at $1 million.
   The fines are slated to go back into effect Friday; the jailing
of the councilmen would come Sunday.
   Meanwhile, the Rev. Jesse Jackson said in New York City Tuesday
that even if the housing dispute in Yonkers is not a result of
racial discrimination, the city's resistance to the law is
unhealthy.
   ``We must be as intolerant of a class rejection _ because
someone is poor _ as we would be of racial or religious bigotry,''
Jackson said.
   After a meeting with black leaders in Westchester County,
Jackson said he would be willing to meet with the four councilmen.
Three of the four responded they would be happy to meet with
Jackson, while the fourth said, ``Have him call me.''
   At a meeting Tuesday of the Yonkers Emergency Financial Control
Board, its chairwoman said she will notify the district attorney
that the four councilmen are breaking the law. The state watchdog
agency was already in place because of money problems the city had
several years ago.
   ``It's the city councilmen who are defying the law and putting
the city's financial profile at risk, who are putting all the
citizens of Yonkers at risk,'' said Gail Shaffer, the chairwoman.
   Shaffer labeled the recalcitrant lawmakers ``reprehensible'' for
jeopardizing the city financially.
   Criminal charges should ``give them pause,'' Shaffer said of the
four, Henry Spallone, Nicholas Longo, Edward Fagan and Peter Chema.
   Shaffer's remarks came a day after Gov. Mario Cuomo said he
would initiate removal proceedings and urge the jailing of the
councilmen if the Supreme Court refused the stay.
   The financial control board asked City Manager Neil DeLuca to
prepare a detailed phase-out plan by Thursday for the gradual
elimination of city services.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
