<1ST_LINE>a a PM-ReligionintheNews Adv02   08-30 0813</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Religion in the News, Adv 02,0834</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv02</NOTE>
<NOTE>For release Fri PMs Sept. 2, or thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Scholars See Moral Issue In Quayle-Vietnam Furor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Religious ethicists say the central moral
question about Sen. Dan Quayle's conduct as a young man during the
Vietnam War period is whether his actions squared with his attitude.
   Some see inconsistency between his stated support for the war at
that time, while virtually assuring he wouldn't be involved in it
by joining the National Guard when he faced being drafted.
   Several theologians said in interviews that Quayle as a youth
may not have understood the implications then, and that motivations
are nebulous, but his course appears equivocal on the surface.
   The case was termed due for analysis in some ethics courses this
fall.
   ``It borders on hypocrisy, and it's certainly not heroic, but
none of us fully takes the consequences of his or her beliefs all
the time,'' said the Rev. Roger Shinn of New York's Union
Theological Seminary.
   ``There comes a time when the chips are down that you've got to
live up to your convictions and take the costs. But you can't get
involved in every fight that comes along, even if you believe in
it. You muddle through, sit one out.''
   Shinn, a teacher of Christian ethics for a quarter century,
counseled troubled students during the Vietnam War. He noted some
opposed it, paying for it by going to jail, while some supported it
and died in Vietnam.
   ``Either way, they paid the costs,'' he said. ``That's what real
integrity is. Whether you agree with a person or not, acting with
integrity means taking a stand and willingness to suffer for it.''
   Quayle says he entered the National Guard so as to go to law
school. ``I did not join to avoid service in Vietnam,'' he says. He
says he ``supported the goals of fighting communism in Vietnam''
and disliked the ``no-win policy aspect.''
   Ethicists say the issue was not his entering the Guard, which
many war opponents did to avoid the draft, and not mainly whether
he used family influence to do it, but whether he practiced what he
preached.
   ``If you believe one way, you have to act consistently with it
or your ethical stance collapses,'' said Catholic psychologist
Eugene Kennedy of Loyola University in Chicago.
   Th Rev. Paul Simmons, who teaches Christian ethics at Southern
Baptist Theological Seminary in Louisville, Ky., said if Quayle was
``really honest about it, he would come clean that he was dodging
the draft.
   ``The real issue is one of honesty and straightforwardness. If
he supported Vietnam and then tried to get out of it, it was
hypocritical to the core. It was not a matter of conscience, but of
expediency.''
   Moral philosopher Peter Simpson of the Catholic University of
America in Washington said Quayle's course raises ``a small
question mark about his integrity.''
   ``But it's relatively minor,'' Simon said. ``It's not worth all
the hullabaloo. I have doubts about how strong his convictions were
on Vietnam. Maybe he should have sought to go there and help the
cause.
   ``But he chose not to for reasons we don't fully understand. You
can't judge guilt from the outside, but should give a person the
benefit of the doubt. Young men make mistakes. We're all entitled
to be wrong sometimes.
   ``He may now regret it.''
   Catholic moral theologian Germain Grisez of St. Mary's College
in Emmitsburg, Md., said it is not clearly inconsistent for people
to favor ``fighting a war, but not particularly want to be in it
themselves.
   ``Very often people want their dirty work done, but don't want
to do it themselves. I'm not sure it's wrong, and not sure it's all
right either. It's a question of fairness, of being unfair to other
people by shirking.
   ``It's clearly not heroic character, but that does not mean it's
immoral.''
   Rabbi Alexander Schindler, an ethical scholar and president of
the Union of American Hebrew Congregations, said there ``seems to
be quite a distance'' between what Quayle ``professes and what he
does.
   ``Obviously one should not proclaim what he fails to do. If his
words belie his deeds, he becomes a hypocrite. Actions should come
close to ideals. Yet nobody's actions reflect the ideal totally.
Everybody fails it sometimes.''
   The Rev. James T. Burtchaell of the University of Notre Dame
said people may see Quayle's ``strong view of the war as in
conflict with his public action... I don't think he's profound
enough to be hypocritical.''
   Episcopal moral theologian Harmon Smith of Duke University said
``the meaning of actions and statements always have to be
interpreted. I don't know how to say his are consistent, but I
reckon that he does.
   ``Typically there is more than one way to look at it.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Fri PMs Sept. 2.</NOTE>
