<1ST_LINE>a i AM-Pope-Lesotho ADV06   08-30 0729</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pope-Lesotho, ADV06,0747</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv06</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Tue AMs, Sept. 6, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Pope to Beatify Missionary in Kingdom Encircled by South Africa</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>THABA BOSIU, Lesotho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   On his visit to this kingdom
surrounded by South Africa, Pope John Paul II will come here to a
sacred mountain where a French missionary helped native people
threatened by white men more than 100 years ago.
   Later on during his stop in Lesotho on his five-nation tour of
southern Africa Sept. 10-19, the pontiff will beatify the Roman
Catholic missionary, the Rev. Joseph Gerard.
   At Thaba Bosiu on Sept. 14, the pontiff will meet King
Moshoeshoe II on the same spot where King Moshoeshoe I in 1862
first welcomed Christian missionaries to his land, torn by internal
violence and threatened by the surrounding white Boers, the
settlers of what today is South Africa.
   Gerard was one of the missionaries, who traveled through the
mountains on horseback wrapped in wool blankets as the Basotho (the
people of Lesotho) still do.
   Gerard climbed the rocky, natural fortress of Thaba Bosiu _
``The Mountain of the Night'' in the local language _ several times
during the 1865-68 conflict with the white Boers, sneaking past
them to bring food and encouragement to the thousands of Basotho
crowded onto the top of the 600-foot-high plateau.
   The missionaries persuaded Moshoeshoe I to seek protection from
Britain's Queen Victoria. As a result, Basutoland, as the area was
called, became a British protectorate and was saved from annexation
into what was later to become South Africa.
   Basutoland became independent Lesotho in 1966.
   The 12,134-square-mile kingdom _ about half the size of West
Virginia _ has almost no industry, only one-third of its land is
arable, and it relies heavily on the earnings of 140,000 Basotho
men who work in South Africa, which is not on the pope's itinerary.
   The pope will beatify Gerard during a Mass at a racetrack near
here on Sept. 15 before departing next day for Swaziland.
   The pontiff will not go to the summit of Thaba Bosiu, the royal
burial ground, where residents say a large dune of fine, red sand
at the summit contains the spirit of the first king, and like him,
never leaves the mountaintop. When the dune approaches the edge,
upward drafts of wind blow it back.
   King Moshoeshoe I discovered the mountain refuge in 1824 and
gathered feuding, destitute, and some cannibalistic tribes together
to found the Basotho nation. He welcomed the missionaries, and
spent his last years trying to choose whether to become a Catholic
or a Protestant. When he died without making a decision, Gerard
wrote, ``I have never felt such great sorrow in my life.''
   The present king is Catholic, as are 70,000 other Basotho.
Ninety percent of the population of 1,443,853 are Christian; the
rest are animists.
   Gerard died in 1914, after working for 52 years among the
Basotho, establishing schools, a hospital and a church, supervising
the printing of books in the Sesotho language and converting
Basotho to Catholicism.
   His mission at Roma is now run by a French Canadian, the Rev.
Gilles Jalbert, who gave up horseback riding a few years ago. He
supervised construction of a chapel over Gerard's grave, chopped
down trees and prepared rest quarters for the pope's entourage. He
hopes electricity will reach Roma by the time the pope does, so the
Mass at the nearby sports ground can be amplified.
   The pope will visit Gerard's grave, from which local people have
been taking dirt for decades to sprinkle on their crops, homes and
children to bring good fortune.
   Gerard is being beatified, the first step toward sainthood,
because of the healing of a 6-year-old blind girl in 1928, 14 years
after his death. Doctors couldn't cure Florina Phakela, so a priest
at the Roma mission had a bag of soil from Gerard's grave tied
around her neck and told her mother to pray for nine days.
   The girl, who died in 1982, told Vatican investigators she was
visited in the night by a priest who told her she was cured. When
she woke in the morning, her sight restored, she went to the
mission to thank the priest, but couldn't find him.
   She identified a picture of Gerard as the one who had visited
her.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Tue PMs, Sept. 6</NOTE>
</DOC>
