<DOCNO> AP880830-0197 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-30-88 1401EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a i AM-Argentina-Law ADV07   08-30 0691</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Argentina-Law, ADV07,0711</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv07</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Wed AMs, Sept. 7, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Jews and Human Rights Leaders Hail Argentine Anti-Discrimination
Law</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By OSCAR SERRAT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Human rights leaders and Jews are
hailing a new law that imposes fines or jail sentences on anyone
convicted of discrimination based on race, religion or sex.
   They call it a significant advance in the protection of civil
liberties in Argentina.
   ``We think the law has extraordinary social and political
significance for Argentine society,'' said David Goldberg,
president of the Delegation of Argentine Israelite Associations.
   ``There was a gap in previous legislation in that there was no
penalty for those who did discriminate,'' said Goldberg, a medical
doctor whose organization is the largest of several that represent
the estimated 400,000 Jews in this South American country.
   Simon Lazara, a Socialist congressman and a leader of the
Permanent Assembly for Human Rights, said, ``The law is not solely
aimed at anti-Semitism, but also at discrimination based on color
or creed, or against the native (Indian) communities.''
   The legislation was introduced early in 1984 by President Raul
Alfonsin, who co-founded and ran the Permanent Assembly for Human
Rights before he was elected to office in October 1983. His
inauguration seven weeks later ended a harsh, nearly eight-year
military dictatorship.
   As reworked and finally approved by Congress in August, the new
law penalizes anyone who ``arbitrarily blocks, obstructs or
restricts ... the full exercise ... of fundamental rights and
guarantees.''
   Argentina's Constitution of 1853 as amended protects the right
to assembly, universal suffrage and freedom of speech and worship,
although Roman Catholicism is the country's official religion and
only Catholics can hold the nation's presidency and vice presidency.
   The law punishes by jail up to three years anyone convicted of
belonging to an organization that promotes the superiority of one
race or color or creed over another.
   Anyone convicted of a crime or offense committed ``in
persecution or hatred of a race, religion or nationality, or with
the intent to destroy ... a national, ethnic, racial or religious
group,'' could be sentenced to additional fines or prison.
   The law also requires restitution in cases of property damage.
   ``Overall, the new law constitutes a vision of the new democracy
in Argentina, reflecting the conditions that have existed since the
end of the last military dictatorship,'' Lazara said.
   Argentina's century-old tradition of democracy has been
tarnished by six military interventions since 1930, including coups
that ousted Gen. Juan D. Peron in 1955, two civilian presidents in
the 1960s, and Peron's wife Isabel in 1976.
   More than 9,000 Argentines, most of them sons and daughters of
the middle class, ``disappeared'' and are presumed dead following
their arrests in the late 1970s by security forces trying to crush
the Montonero urban guerrillas and leftist political opposition in
general.
   Discrimination usually is not overt, but it is pervasive. Darker
skinned Argentines of Indian descent, while not barred from
white-collar jobs, more commonly are manual laborers. Very few Jews
are in the army. Women are paid less than men for doing the same
job.
   Anti-Semitism in recent years has been reflected by the knocking
over of Jewish tombstones in cemeteries, the painting of
anti-Semitic graffitti on walls and, very infrequently but always
intimidating, the setting off of small bombs in the doorways of
synagogues.
   ``We don't have a very serious problem of discrimination based
on religion or race, but there is, in the background, among certain
sectors, some anti-Semitism,'' said Jose Ignacio Lopez, Alfonsin's
press secretary.
   Angel Grushka, leader of the leftist Federation of Jewish
Cultural Entities, said the new law is helpful, but he added tha
the wished the acts of discrimination that would invoke the
penalties were more precisely spelled out.
   ``We still have to work very hard on the judicial level to make
sure that anti-Semitic actions are punished,'' Grushka said.
   Anti-discrimination legislation in Argentine law dates to 1949.
In 1964, similar legislation that penalized those convicted of
discrimination was implemented, but that legislation was revoked by
the military government that came to power two years later.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Wed AMs, Sept. 7</NOTE>
</DOC>
