<DOCNO> AP880830-0199 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-30-88 1340EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a AM-ReligionRdp ADV02   08-30 0582</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Religion Rdp, ADV02,0602</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv02</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Fri AMs, Sept. 2, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ST. CLOUD, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For years, the long narrow building with
peeling paint, boarded windows and a single lightbulb above the
door has been a favorite hangout for heavy drinkers, pool shooters
and drug dealers.
   But if former hard-drinker Gus Odom and some of his friends have
their way, the Royal Palm Cafe will throw out the bottles and break
out the Bibles. They want to convert the notorious bar into a
church: The Prayer Line Church of God.
   ``We're pulling the devil out and bringing Jesus in,'' says
Odom, 36, who remembers years of drinking, carousing and carrying a
gun inside the Royal Palm. ``Before I started serving God, I used
to drink there myself.''
   Now a weed sprayer for the South Florida Water Management
District, Odom also remembers how drug dealers outside the bar
brought his neighborhood down. He thought of the bar-to-church
conversion one day after getting religion.
   Since his small congregation needed a new place to meet, he
approached Lorenze Holcy, 56, owner of the Royal Palm for 17 years.
Holcy, receptive to the idea, offered to sell for $25,000.
   Church of God headquarters in Cleveland, Tenn., has offered to
provide $10,000 toward the cost, while members and supporters have
to raise the other $15,000. ``With the help of the Lord, we're
going to pull it off,'' Odom said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>GRAND RAPIDS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of the Christian Reformed
Church have approved new, non-sexist wording in a key teaching
document, the Heidelberg Catechism.
   The church's 1988 synod agreed to modify the catechism's male
language, such as changing the questions, ``Did God create man so
wicked and perverse?'' and ``Are all men saved through Christ?'' to
``Did God create people so wicked and perverse?'' and ``Are all
saved through Christ?''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Catholics, Protestants and
Pentecostals are cooperating to sponsor a charismatic
evangelization conference here Sept. 8-10, with up to 10,000
expected for it.
   Called the Southwestern Congress on the Holy Spirit and World
Evangelization, it is a regional follw-up to a national congress on
the same theme that drew 40,000 to the New Orleans Superdome in
mid-1987.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Jewish leader has urged representatives of
Christians, Jews and the film industry to join in a conference
aimed at defusing tensions aroused by the controversial film, ``The
Last Temptation of Christ.''
   Rabbi James Rudin, interreligious affairs director of the
American Jewish Committee, says such a conference could help
``break down the harmful stereotypes and caricatures that have
surfaced during this controversy.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>COLLEGEVILLE, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An internationally renowned Roman
Catholic scholar, the Rev. Godfrey Diekmann, says the church should
admit women to ordination as priests.
   Diekmann, 80, a Benedictine authority on liturgy who helped
draft the worship reforms of the 1962-65 Second Vatican Council,
says the failure of the church to ordain women was based on custom,
not tradition.
   Referring to arguments that priests must ``image'' a male
Christ, he told a symposium: ``Our consistent and really authentic
tradition about imaging Christ finds that image first of all, not
in bodily similarity, but in spiritual affinity.''
   Diekmann, who teaches patristics (writings of the early church
fathers) at St. John's University, cited past ordination of women
as deaconesses to perform liturgical functions, and said:
   ``Pastoral experience, in fact desperate liturgical needs,
similarly cry out for women priests today.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri AMs, Sept. 2</NOTE>
