<2ND_LINE>BC-Weekend TV-World Monitor, ADV 09-11, 1st Ld-Writethru,</2ND_LINE>
<TEXT>
   b0747,0996
</TEXT>
<NOTE>$adv09</NOTE>
<NOTE>$Adv10</NOTE>
<NOTE>$Adv11</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, Sept. 9-11, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 20th graf, ``Hart calls ...,'' to CORRECT overall
funding for ``World Monitor TV,'' $20 million for each year sted
overall. NOTE _ in 2nd graf, Monday is Sept. 12.</NOTE>
<HEAD>`World Monitor TV' Looks Beyond the Headlines</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This will be an easy quiz.
   Two television newscasts, both inspired by newspapers, make
their debut Monday. One show is based on USA Today, the other on
the Christian Science Monitor. One show will cover international
politics, the other will decide how we really feel about our bodies.
   Made the match?
   Even before they hit the air, it's obvious that ``World Monitor
TV'' and ``USA Today: The Television Show'' will take dramatically
different approaches to television news.
   _ Like the paper from which it springs, ``USA Today: The
Television Show'' will be divided into four segments: news, money,
sports and life. Each block will have its own anchor, and the
emphasis throughout will be decidedly soft.
   _ Although the news philosophy of ``World Monitor TV'' is
clearly more traditional, it looks to be the more problematic show.
In an age where ``Entertainment Tonight'' succeeds as journalism
and TV Guide is among the most-read magazines, straightforward
reporting has come to be something of a gamble.
   Still, the makers of ``World Monitor TV'' are hopeful.
Audiences, the show's creators suspect, may need a hard-news fix.
   ``People now who are addicted to information feel uninformed,''
said John Hart, the former NBC reporter who will serve as ``World
Monitor TV's'' anchor. ``I want to know what's true about things.
And I think most people do, too. If you leave people with a sense
that the world is made up of unrelated fragments, I think you miss
something. It's unbalanced.''
   ``World Monitor TV'' will be broadcast weeknights at 4 p.m. and
10 p.m. (PDT) on cable television's all-documentary Discovery
Channel, the fastest-growing cable network, with 32 million
subscriber homes.
   ``I think the Discovery Channel's audience is very compatible
with the kind of news program we want to produce,'' said Daniel
Wilson, executive producer of ``World Monitor TV.''
   The half-hour newscast, produced near the Christian Science
Monitor's headquarters in Boston, will focus on only three or four
stories each night and may remind viewers of public TV's
MacNeil-Lehrer NewsHour, which uses a similar format.
   The program will not, Hart said, make any effort to declare,
``That's the way it is.''
   ``We have the luxury of not pretending to be a broadcast of
record,'' Hart said. ``We're not going to chase every wisp of
smoke. ... We are in the context business. That's our job. We can
tell you what the news means. We can make connections, relate
history. We can do the things you can't do when you're trying to
hit all the bases.
   ``We'll use reporters and foreign correspondents who know the
language and know the culture.''
   While ``World Monitor TV'' will not be a video version of its
newspaper cousin, the newscast will be supported by the Christian
Science Monitor's 22 international and domestic news bureaus. Each
broadcast will also include satellite-fed contributions from
``World Monitor TV's'' news desks in London, Tokyo and Washington.
Hodding Carter III will be the program's regular commentator.
   Don't look for ``World Monitor TV'' to break news stories on a
daily basis. That's not part of the plan, and the newscast doesn't
have the resources to support an investigative unit. ``We might do
a story on day care,'' Wilson said. ``And what we would do is look
at the issue in Europe, the Far East and America. And then we would
make comparisons. We're going to try to do things in depth.''
   It is such thoroughness that drew Hart, a 28-year network news
veteran, to ``World Monitor TV.''
   ``At the networks, the commercial considerations are first,''
Hart said. Hart, a Peabody Award-winning reporter, has also served
as host of ``NBC Saturday Night News'' and ``NBC Sunday Night
News.''
   ``This place is a relief,'' Hart continued. ``Here, we won't
make editorial decisions solely to garner an audience. ... These
people are interested in journalism. And that's it. They're not
caught in the struggle between journalism and marketing. There's
nothing wrong with marketing, but it pulls in the opposite
direction _ toward fantasy, and not toward reality. ... Here's a
show where we can deal with ideas for a change.''
   Hart calls ``World Monitor TV'' a ``modest proposal.'' He's
right. While ``USA Today: The Television Show'' has first-year
start-up costs of $40 million and a staff of 160, ``World Monitor
TV'' has been given $20 million for each of its first five years
and has just more than 100 employees. Network news budgets, for
contrast, averaged $275 million last year.
   ``USA Today: The Television Show,'' meanwhile, is banking that
U.S. viewers want ``entertaining information,'' as the newscast is
characterized by its producer Steve Friedman, formerly of NBC's
``Today.''
   Friedman's show will be broadcast through syndication, appearing
on more than 150 stations across the country.
   ``USA Today: The Television Show'' and ``World Monitor TV'' do
have one thing in common: Neither will try to be a headline
service. Each will try to complement, not compete with, the network
newscasts.
   After that, however, all similarities between the two shows end.
   Thus, if you see ``World Monitor'' looking at the developing
black middle class in Zimbabwe, expect ``USA Today: The Television
Show'' to explain how men's and women's opinions of love differ.
   Which show will be a hit? That's hard to say. USA Today, the
newspaper, has 5.4 million readers. The Christian Science Monitor's
circulation, on the other hand, is less than 200,000.
   Sometimes, though, good things come in small packages.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, Sept. 9-11</NOTE>
</DOC>
