<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OilPrices     08-30 0261</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0271</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Futures Prices Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures prices were mixed after a dull
session marked only by a late technical rally in the near-term
contract for unleaded gasoline.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, contracts for October
delivery of West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S.
crude oil, fell 12 cents per barrel to close at $15.22 on Monday.
Most other contract months fell a similar amount.
   Near-term contracts rose for refined oil products traded on the
exchange. Contracts for September delivery of wholesale unleaded
gasoline rose 0.45 cent to 47.24 cents a gallon. Other months were
lower.
   Wholesale heating oil for September advanced 0.09 cent to 42.76
cents a gallon while longer term contracts declined.
   Oil traders were watching the travels of OPEC Secretary-General
Subroto, who arrived in Tehran for crucial talks on cutting the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries' output in a bid to
stabilize the world oil market and boost prices.
   But traders said there was a great deal of skepticism
surrounding his efforts.
   ``People are becoming jaded because you can't get any kind of a
good move in crude on the upside,'' said Madison Galbraith, a
senior trader at Merrill Lynch Energy Futures.
   The official OPEC benchmark price for crude is $18 a barrel.
   Traders said the market ignored a report by The Middle East
Economic Survey, a respected oil industry newsletter published in
Nicosia, which stated that OPEC's August output totaled about 20
million barrels a day, roughly 3.5 million barrels a day over its
overall production quota.
</TEXT>
