<DOCNO> AP880830-0208 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-30-88 0118EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Primerica-Buyout Bjt   08-30 0866</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Primerica-Buyout, Bjt,0900</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Long-Time Friends, Dealers Make High-Stakes Deal</HEAD>
<HEAD>Laserphotos</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA STOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GREENWICH, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gerald Tsai Jr. and Sanford I. Weill,
two long-time friends known as brilliant businessmen and ambitious
dealmakers, have forged a high-stakes alliance affecting both of
their companies and both of their futures.
   Tsai, the former wildly successful money manager who now is
chairman of Primerica Corp., and Weill, former president of
American Express Co. and current chairman of Commercial Credit
Group Inc., said Monday that Commercial Credit had agreed to
acquire Primerica in a cash-and-stock deal valued at $1.65 billion.
   The merger could create financial services company and help
Primerica, which has had problems with its 1987 acquisition of the
struggling brokerage firm Smith Barney, Harris Upham & Co.
   It also presents a challenge to Weill, who has a reputation for
going into tough situations and turning them around.
   What is unclear is what role Tsai will play in the new company.
   Tsai will be the new company's largest individual shareholder,
with about 1.5 percent of its stock, as well as a director and
chairman of the board's executive committee. Weill will be
chairman, chief executive officer and president of the combined
company.
   Both men shrugged off the role issue in a telephone interview on
Monday.
   When asked who will run the show, Tsai said, ``He (Weill)
does...I feel fine about that.''
   ``They are a terrific team. This is going to be an absolute
powerhouse company,'' said Primerica director Joseph A. Califano
Jr., former U.S. secretary of health, education and welfare.
   Califano said it was clear that Weill would run the company,
even though Tsai wasn't stepping back.
   ``Gerry Tsai is only beginning his career,'' Califano said.
``He's a man with 1,000 ideas.''
   Some analysts unsure of Tsai's role in the new company.
   ``One conclusion is that Commercial Credit will be the owner _
Sandy Weill knows the brokerage business and financial services _
and he will be the one to run the show,'' said Dudley Heer, an
analyst with the brokerage firm Duff & Phelps in Chicago.
   ``Tsai is a dealmaker,'' Heer said. ``I don't know if he has
mellowed out or what. In the investment business there is no
retirement restriction...and he is a very vibrant individual.''
   Tsai, 59, who has been chairman of Greenwich-based Primerica for
just 19 months, has surprised people before. He earned a reputation
as an investment wizard with some of his stock plays in the 1960s.
   He became involved with Primerica _ then called American Can Co.
_ in 1982 when he sold it Associated Madison, which he had acquired
earlier.
   Tsai became vice chairman in 1983 and was named chairman in
January 1987, helping shepherd the company through transformation
from a manufacturing operation to a financial services concern.
Under Tsai's direction, Primerica embarked on a strategy of
simplifying its operations and strengthening its financial position.
   Tsai said he hoped to spend a lot of time on long-range planning
and working with Weill.
   ``Sandy is somebody I have known for well over 25 years. He is a
terrific business manager. I'm very excited about this and I think
the stockholders will be very happy down the road,'' Tsai said.
   Weill, 55, a founder of what now is the giant investment firm
Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc., also talked about his friendship with
Tsai.
   ``I think we have always gotten along well. I don't think we'll
have any problems,'' Weill said.
   Weill also is not worried about the problems at Smith Barney,
which Primerica acquired last year for $750 million.
   Primerica attributed its flat second-quarter earnings to the
weak performance by Smith Barney, which suffered from lower trading
volume, underwriting and commission revenues in the wake of the
stock market crash.
   ``I think there is a really excellent opportunity for Smith
Barney to grow and prosper even in difficult economic
environments,'' Weill said.
   He and Tsai also denied that Smith Barney would be sold; Weill
said the firm was an ``important ingredient'' of Primerica.
   Anthony Pearce-Batten, an analyst with Legg Mason Wood Walker
Inc. in Baltimore, also said he did not believe Smith Barney would
be sold.
   ``He has built a reputation as a strong manager who is able to
turn companies around,'' Pearce-Batten said. ``Commercial Credit
appears to be in the early stages of another success and Primerica
is the next quantum leap forward.''
   ``...Weill has a good eye for a bargain, very strong management
capabilities, streamling organizations and making them more
efficent and at the same time reducing expenses,'' Pearce-Batten
said.
   Weill left American Express in 1985 after failing to become
chief executive officer. He gained control of Baltimore-based
Commercial Credit two years ago and last November was edged out by
his former firm, Shearson Lehman Brothers, in an attempt to buy
E.F. Hutton Group Inc.
   Under terms of an agreement approved by both companies' boards,
Primerica shareholders would receive one share of Commercial Credit
common stock plus $7 cash for each share of Primerica.
   Commercial Credit's stock fell 75 cents a share to close at
$24.50 on the New York Stock Exchange Monday. Primerica lost 62{
cents a share to close at $29.50 on the NYSE.
</TEXT>
