<FILEID>AP-NR-08-30-88 0123EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Canada Bjt   08-30 0793</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Canada, Bjt,0818</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Coming Election Will Determine Fate Of U.S. Free Trade Deal</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BRADLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Brian Mulroney has signaled the
likelihood of a fall election to decide the fate of both the
Canada-U.S. Free Trade Agreement and his Progressive Conservative
government.
   In a heated three-way race, the landmark vote on Canada's
economic future would offer the nation a clear choice between
conservatives, liberals and socialists.
   Mulroney said in a Canadian Broadcasting Corp. interview Sunday
night, after keeping the country guessing for weeks, that he saw no
reason to remain in office much longer than the traditional four
years without a new election.
   Those four years end on Sept. 17.
   ``I've always believed that while the Constitution allows for a
five-year term, that the custom of going about four years _ give or
take a couple of months _ is a sound one, and it's one that should
be respected,'' he said.
   An election call Sept. 17 would mean a mid-November election.
Canadian campaigns normally last about eight weeks.
   If Mulroney wins, the world's two largest trading partners will
proceed with plans to create a North American free trade zone on
Jan. 1, eliminating all tariffs over 10 years and dismantling
barriers to investment and competition.
   If he loses, both the main opposition Liberal Party and the
socialist New Democratic Party say they will tear up the complex
trade deal hailed by President Reagan as ``only a beginning'' in a
global free flow of trade.
   Mulroney, 49, a former corporate lawyer who became leader of his
party in 1983 and scored a landslide victory a year later, has been
waiting for good omens before calling an election.
   But Liberal leader John Turner forced Mulroney's hand by asking
the Liberal majority in the unelected Senate to stall free-trade
legislation indefinitely.
   Turner and New Democratic Party leader Ed Broadbent claim the
deal jeopardizes Canadian sovereignty. ``We have put in potential
jeopardy our cultural programs and our social programs and our
ability to assist our less developed regions,'' said Turner.
   The elected House of Commons began its final debate on the trade
deal Monday. With Conservatives holding 207 of the 282 seats, the
bill should pass easily on Wednesday. The Liberals have 38 seats,
New Democrats 32, with 2 Independents, 1 Liberal-Independent and 2
vacancies.
   The deal must then be passed by the Senate before becoming law.
   The government hopes that pressure from pro-free traders such as
Quebec's Liberal Premier Robert Bourassa and the western provinces
will soften the Senate's stand, especially amid calls for reform or
abolition of the chamber.
   All players will be watching the Sept. 6 provincial election in
Nova Scotia to see if Conservative Premier John Buchanan wins
another term. ``A Conservative loss could be the one event that
could force plans for an election to be put on hold,'' said
pollster Angus Reid.
   A national Reid poll last Friday gave the Conservatives 36
percent of the vote, Liberals 32 percent and New Democrats 30
percent. The latest Gallup Poll showed the Liberals with 35
percent, Conservatives 34 percent and New Democrats 30 percent.
Small parties and independents took up the remainder.
   Such a tight race could result in a minority Conservative
government lacking the votes to pass free trade.
   Historians compare the contest to the milestone election of 1911
when Liberal Prime Minister Sir Wilfrid Laurier offered free trade
but lost to Conservative Robert Borden who pledged ``No truck nor
trade with the Yankees.''
   Despite presiding over a healthy economy and negotiating an
accord to bring Quebec back into the Constitution, Mulroney has
struggled with a credibility problem referred to in the press as
the ``sleaze factor.''
   He lost eight Cabinet members in scandals ranging from tainted
tuna to criminal charges. Liberals gloated this month when a
disgruntled former Cabinet member from Quebec, Suzanne
Blais-Grenier, alleged the Mulroney government was operating ``a
network of patronage and kickbacks.''
   She gave no proof but the controversy swelled when two other
Quebec Conservatives spoke of ``crumbs'' from the procurement table
and information ``that could put a dozen people in jail,'' again
without hard evidence.
   The other parties have their problems, too.
   Polls show Turner the most unpopular party leader, with only 15
percent voter approval. He has struggled for two years to even hold
onto his job in a divided party and is embarrassed by Bourassa's
close links with Mulroney, whose government has pumped money into
Quebec.
   Nearly two-thirds of voters say they like Ed Broadbent, a former
university teacher who claims to speak for ``ordinary Canadians.''
But his popularity may not translate into support for a left-wing
party that has never governed Canada and is committed to NATO
withdrawal and protectionism.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
