<FILEID>AP-NR-08-30-88 0859EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Britain-Stocks     08-30 0185</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Stocks,0192</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>London Shares Sharply Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices were sharply lower at midday Tuesday
on the London Stock Exchange, as participants returned from a
three-day holiday weekend with unabated worries about the British
trade deficit and interest rates.
   Trading was light, as institutional players awaited further
signals on the British economy, dealers said.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index was down 21.0
points, or 3.7 percent, at 1749.7 at 12:30 p.m. local time. The
index opened just 4.6 points lower and plunged to a low of 1745.2,
or 25.5 points down, at late morning.
   ``One is watching the market quite carefully,'' said Brennan
Hiorns, a stock analyst at Kleinwort Grieveson Securities. ``Fund
managers in (Britain) still haven't taken any strategic decisions
yet.''
   Triggering the worries were last week's British trade figures,
which showed a record deficit of 2 billion pounds, or about $3.6
billion, on the current account in July.
   A subsequent increase in banks' base lending rates to 12 percent
from 11 percent left the market speculating that further rate hikes
might be necessary to cool Britain's consumer spending boom.
</TEXT>
