<HEAD>Mark IV Files Suit In Its Bid For Armtek</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mark IV Industries Inc. has filed suit
against Armtek Corp. in its $500 million hostile bid for the New
Haven-based auto parts maker.
   The suit, filed Monday in Delaware Court of Chancery, charges
that Armtek's board misued a variety of anti-takeover measures in
order to prevent its shareholders from determining whether they
want to accept Mark IV's $44-a-share cash tender offer.
   Mark IV has asked the court to order Armtek not to implement
anti-takeover measures.
   John N. Sievers, Armtek vice president of coporate planning and
investor relations, declined comment.
   In a lawsuit filed earlier this month in New Haven federal
court, Armtek accused Mark IV, a holding company based in West
Amherst, N.Y., of violating disclosure requirments of federal
securities laws. The suit seeks injunctions barring Mark IV from
purchasing Armtek stock or seeking control of the company.
   According to a Securities and Exchange Commission filing, Armtek
has set Sept. 1 as the date by which it will exercise its ``poison
pill'' or shareholders' rights agreement.
   Under the plan, the company would distribute a new series of
preferred stock. The new stock can be converted into cash at a
premium rate, raising the cost of an acquisition in an effort to
deter hostile bidders.
   Formerly the Armstrong Rubber Co., Armtek makes plastics and
specialty chemicals used in the automotive and other industries.
</TEXT>
