<1ST_LINE>r f PM-TraderRetires 1stLd-Writethru   08-30 0771</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Trader Retires, 1st Ld-Writethru,0794</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Prince of the Pit' Calls It Quits To Devote Time To Politics</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 7th graf to UPDATE with support for
Dukakis, Babbitt comments; edits 8th graf pvs to conform; picks up
9th graf pvs: Dennis, a native...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Multimillionaire commodities trader Richard J.
Dennis, a legend whose luck turned sour after last October's stock
market collapse, says he is leaving the futures business to
concentrate on his other passion: politics.
   Dennis, 39, known as the ``Prince of the Pit'' at Chicago's
boisterous commodities exchanges, said Monday he was closing his
accounts and selling his exchange seats so he could devote his
energies to ``public policy and political endeavors.''
   ``There is only so much satisfaction and utility to the making
of money,'' Dennis said in a prepared statement.
   He said he would use his personal fortune, reportedly around
$200 million, as a launching pad for his new career.
   ``I am fortunate to have enough assets and opportunities to try
to make a significant impact on our political lives. As I approach
40 years of age, I believe it is time for me to take on this new
set of challenges,'' the statement read.
   Dennis said he would concentrate on writing, speaking and
``active involvement with voters and candidates.''
   He was national co-chairman for the unsuccessful Democratic
presidential campaign of former Arizona Gov. Bruce Babbitt. He also
has made sizable contributions to several other Democratic
campaigns since 1980, including the 1984 presidential bid of former
Vice President Walter Mondale and the 1986 Illinois gubernatorial
campaign of Adlai Stevenson.
   Dennis said he now supports the presidential bid of Democratic
nominee Michael Dukakis and has contributed $100,000 to his
campaign.
   Babbitt believes Dennis could have a large and lasting impact on
the Democratic Party.
   ```His primary concern is the power of ideas,'' Babbitt said.
``He wants to force the Democratic Party to rethink its agenda. He
has a passion for economic reform.''
   Dennis also donated $10 million to establish the Roosevelt
Center, a liberal think-tank with offices in Washington and
Chicago, and is a leading financial backer of People for the
American Way, a liberal group formed as a counterpoint to the
conservative Moral Majority.
   Dennis, a native of Chicago's South Side, began his financial
career at age 17 as a $1.60-an-hour brokerage house runner at the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   After graduating from DePaul University with a degree in
philosophy, he bought his first exchange seat _ on the tiny
MidAmerica Commodity Exchange _ at age 21.
   Dennis owns seats on every major commodity exchange and runs two
companies: C&D Commodities, a futures trading partnership of which
he is managing partner, and Richard J. Dennis & Co., an advising
firm for managed futures funds and accounts.
   His uncanny success as a trader earned him the nickname ``Prince
of the Pit'' on the floors of the Chicago Board of Trade and
Chicago Mercantile Exchange. But his fortune seemed to sour after
last October's markets collapse, in which C&D Commodities
reportedly lost $10 million.
   Two public commodity funds Dennis launched last year in
conjunction with Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. also fell on hard
times. After they lost more than 50 percent of their $115 million
combined initial value, Dennis suspended trading last April in the
funds.
   Both funds resumed trading on Aug. 3 following a vote of
confidence by investors, and each had lost about 3.5 percent when
trading was halted for good on Friday, said Mark Walsh, a Dennis &
Co. spokeman.
   Walsh blamed the losses on ``choppy markets _ the worst markets
we've seen in 10 years.''
   He said Dennis' decision to quit trading was not related to the
funds' losses.
   Several veteran traders on the floor of the Chicago Board of
Trade said Dennis' exit from the futures business had been expected.
   ``I know that for the last several years, his main interest in
life has been politics, not trading,'' said Victor Lespinasse, a
trader with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
   ``He is certainly one of biggest, most successful traders
ever,'' Lespinasse said. ``Over the past year he supposedly had
some rough times but overall he made a lot of money and was very,
very succesful.''
   ``I personally was surprised he stayed around so long,'' added
Jerry Zusel, manager of CBOT floor operations for Balfour Maclaine
Corp.
   ``With the fact that he's made so much money, I couldn't
understand why he'd want to keep risking capital,'' Zusel said.
``As one guy said to me this morning, he's made more money than he
could spend in 10 lifetimes.''
</TEXT>
