<1ST_LINE>r f PM-SmokelessCigarette 1stLd-Writethru   08-30 0305</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Smokeless Cigarette, 1st Ld-Writethru,0315</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>RJR To Begin Marketing Smokeless Cigarette</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Rewrites throughout to bring higher how cigarettes are
different, other consumer details. No Pickup; Version also moved on
the financial wire.</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   WINSTON-SALEM, N.C. (AP) _ A new smokeless cigarette developed
by R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Co. will be test-marketed in St. Louis,
Phoenix and Tucson, Ariz., beginning Oct. 1, company officials said
today.
   The new cigarettes, called Premier, will be odorless and will
generate only a trace of ash or smoke that could irritate people
nearby, the officials said.
   Company officials said the new cigarettes contain a high-tech
packet of tobacco extracts which is heated, but not burned.
   The price per pack will be about 30 cents higher than other
cigarettes, said Betsy Annese, director of public relations for the
Winston-Salem-based company.
   The company will use a variety of advertising messages to sell
the new cigarettes, she said; one advertising approach will tout
the new product as ``Premier _ the Cleaner Smoke.''
   But the company is not making any health or safety claims.
   ``We're not claiming this is a safe or safer cigarette,'' she
said.
   A health claim would invite regulation by the Federal Food and
Drug Administration.
   ``If a product is sold with claims to make cigarettes safer, it
is a medical device'' subject to FDA approval, said William Grigg,
an FDA spokesman.
   Anti-smoking groups are pressing the FDA to regulate the new
cigarettes as a drug because, they maintain, Reynolds is making
implied health claims for its product. In addition, the
anti-smoking groups say the new cigarettes could appeal to
teen-agers, thereby gaining a new generation of smokers as
customers.
   Analysts said Reynolds selected the test markets, in particular
the Arizona cities, because they have numerous older, sophisticated
smokers who may be trying to quit smoking or are seeking an
alternative.
</TEXT>
