<HEAD>Crop Futures Open Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened slightly higher
today on the Chicago Board of Trade in a continuation of Monday's
late surge, analysts said.
   Further support stemmed from a slight pickup in export business
but analysts expected the grain markets to remain in a pre-harvest
lull.
   The corn and soybean crops are past their most critical growth
stages and maturing rapidly, said Cathy Leow, an assistant vice
president in the grain futures trading division of Thomson McKinnon
Securities Inc. in New York.
   ``Nothing really can happen to the crops at this point unless we
have a frost immediately,'' she said. ``Typically, it's pretty
quiet before the harvest.''
   The Midwestern corn harvest has just begun and will get into
full swing in another two to three weeks, while soybean harvesting
will peak near the end of September, she said.
   In early trading, wheat was } cent to 3 cents higher with the
contract for delivery in September at $3.88{ a bushel; corn was
unchanged to 2 cents higher with September at $2.74{ a bushel; oats
were } cent to 3{ cents higher with September at $2.52{ a bushel;
soybeans were 2 cents to 4 cents higher with September at $8.28 a
bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mostly lower in early trading on
the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .03 cent to .55 cent lower with October at
72.72 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .35 cent to .70 cent lower
with September at 81.90 cents a pound; hogs were .70 cent lower to
.07 cent higher with October at 39.30 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .55 cent to 1.67 cents lower with February at 51.15
cents a pound.
   Cattle futures settled mixed on Monday while pork futures were
sharply lower.
</TEXT>
