<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Peterson,0117</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Upjohn Scientist Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KALAMAZOO, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Durey Peterson, a former scientist with
Upjohn Co. who helped develop an inexpensive production process for
cortisone, has died at age 79.
   Peterson, who died Sunday, teamed with other scientists to use
microorganisms to produce the steroid, used to treat a variety of
infections. Before that development, cortisone had to be extracted
from animals' adrenal glands, an expensive process.
   He held 74 patents and introduced the use of a cold hair-setting
process which became the Toni home permanent. Peterson worked for
the pharmaceutical company for nearly 30 years before retiring in
1975.
   A memorial service is scheduled for Thursday in Kalamazoo.
</TEXT>
