<1ST_LINE>r f BC-BadAdvice     08-30 0289</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Bad Advice,0300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jury Awards Rawson $23.6 Milliion From Prudential-Bache</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rawson Food Stores Inc. and its owner
have been awarded $23.6 million in damages in a civil suit accusing
Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. of issuing bad advice on Rawson's
1985 purchase of part of the Pantry Pride supermaket chain.
   A Circuit Court jury of five women and one man deliberated for
three hours Monday before awarding owner John V. Rawson Jr. $2
million in compensatory and punitive damages and the company $21.6
million.
   The lawsuit alleged that Prudential-Bache had recklessly advised
Rawson and his company to buy 43 Northeast Florida and Southeast
Georgia stores from Pantry Pride Enterprises Inc. for $40 million.
Prudential-Bache charged $1 million for its services.
   The lawsuit said the real value of the stores was much less than
what Prudential-Bache claimed it was.
   Rawson Food Services filed for protection from creditors under
Chapter 11 of the U.S. Bankruptcy Code in February 1986. The
45-store chain claimed assets of $44.6 million and liabilities of
$51 million.
   ``We are obviously very pleased with the verdict because it
means the remaining creditors of the estate can be repaid,'' said
Steve Busey, an attorney representing Raswon.
   The day it filed for reorganization, Rawson agreed to sell 33 of
its Minneapolis-based Super Valu Stores for $31.2 million. Super
Valu then sold the stores to Winn-Dixie Stores Inc.
   The remaining stores were sold to other companies but it left
Rawson $15 million too short to pay off its creditors.
   Prudential-Bache had argued it was not liable for damages
because its advise was based largely on information from Rawson's
management team.
   Attorney Mattox Hair, who represented Prudential-Bache, was out
of the office Tuesday and was unavailable for comment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
