<FILEID>AP-NR-08-30-88 1216EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreetNoon     08-30 0325</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street Noon,0340</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stocks retreated today in extremely light
trading, which brokers largely attributed to profit-taking on the
runup of the previous session.
   They said Commerce Department reports released today that
suggested the economy is slowing down, thereby easing fears of
inflation, failed to induce much interest on Wall Street.
   The department said its chief forecasting gauge of future
economic activity dropped 0.8 percent in July, the sharpest decline
in eight months, and U.S. factory orders fell 3.5 percent. The
figures were within expectations.
   ``There's really nothing going on. The floor is very quiet,''
said Charles Eaton, a market strategist at Nikko Securities Co.
International in New York.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks, which rose 24
points Monday in some of the lightest trading this year, had
retreated by 5.87 to 2,035.56 by noon EDT.
   Among broader market barometers, the New York Stock Exchange
composite index of all listed issues was down 0.21 to 148.34. The
American Stock Exchange's market value index was down 0.44 to
294.61.
   Declining issues outnumbered advances by nearly 7-to-5 on the
NYSE, with 693 down, 531 up and 519 unchanged. Volume on the Big
Board totaled 49.69 million shares in the morning session, vs.
41.04 million Monday morning.
   Among the blue chip stocks, Alcoa was off ] to 51, General
Electric was off \ to 40 and IBM was off | to 112}.
   The Big Board's most active issue was Middle South Utilities, up
[ to 13] on volume exceeding 1.3 million shares. There was
speculation the firm was preparing to resume paying a dividend.
   Primerica, which agreed Monday to be acquired by Commercial
Credit Co. in a cash and securities deal valued at about $1.65
billion, slipped } to 28}.
   On the over-the-counter market, Lotus Development fell } to 18\.
A front-page article in the Wall Street Journal this morning
suggested the software maker's market share and profitability were
slipping.
