<2ND_LINE>PM-TWA-Labor,0463</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>TWA Flight Attendants Ask DOT to Investigate Icahn's Fitness</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARJORIE ANDERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The flight attendants union at Trans World
Airlines Inc. charged today that TWA's future and the safety of the
flying public are jeopardized by financier Carl Icahn's proposal to
take the airline private.
   The flight attendants asked the Department of Transportation to
investigate Icahn's fitness to continue operating TWA.
   ``TWA is being managed today not as an air carrier but as an
unsupervised mutual fund benefiting Mr. Icahn,'' Vicki Frankovich,
president of the Independent Federation of Flight Attendants, told
a news conference.
   The IFFA represents about 9,000 flight attendants at TWA.
   The union charged that since Icahn took control of TWA two years
ago, he has ``milked'' the airline's cash reserves and sold off
assets to finance his stock market and takeover ventures, instead
of buying new airplanes and safety equipment for the TWA fleet. The
airline's fleet is one of the oldest in the U.S. industry, with
planes averaging 13.3 years old.
   TWA plans to spend just over 1 percent of its budget this year
on new planes, while most other major airlines usually invest about
15 percent or 20 percent in new equipment, according to union
lawyer David Aronofsky.
   This, the union says, contributes to high maintenance costs and
TWA's accident and incident rate, which according to the Federal
Aviation Administration is the worst among major U.S. carriers.
   Icahn is asking TWA shareholders at a meeting Sept. 7 to sell
their stock to him. The purchase would be financed by the sale of
speculative, high-yield bonds, which the union says would raise
TWA's annual interest payments to $466 million, almost double the
airline's 1987 operating earnings of $240 million.
   TWA referred all questions to Bob Allen, senior vice president
for employee relations. He declined immediate comment, saying he
had not had time to study the news release.
   The union also has asked the Department of Transportation to
freeze TWA's assets while it investigates Icahn's management.
   The TWA machinists union, which also opposes the privatization
and filed suit in federal court last week in an effort to stop it,
is being asked to join the IFFA petition but has not yet had time
to study it, Frankovich said.
   ``We couldn't wait,'' she said, adding that she expects the
machinists to join the flight attendants in asking the DOT to stop
Icahn's privatization effort.
   Unions at Eastern Airlines made a similar request to the DOT
last year. In its findings the DOT said acrimonious relations
between labor and management could lead to operational problems,
and a former Secretary of Labor was appointed to act as a mediator.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
