<2ND_LINE>BC-Russian Aphids, Adv 03-04,0755</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 03</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 04</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions Sept. 3-4 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Russian Scare In American Wheat Fields</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL BATES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WICHITA, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pinhead-sized aphid is giving new meaning
to the words ``Russian menace'' as Midwestern farmers scout their
fields for the insect.
   Leroy Brooks, a Kansas State University entomologist, says the
Russian wheat aphid is a crop pest that has been spreading since
its discovery in Russia around 1900. It was in South Africa in
1978, Mexico by the early 1980s and crossed into the United States
in Texas in 1985 or 1986.
   ``It's relatively rare to find a pest that is a completely new
pest to the United States, or in this case, the western
hemisphere,'' Brooks said.
   Kansas fields first were infested in April 1986. During 1988, at
least 49 central and western counties were affected. As of July,
the insect had spread almost to the Candian border and had been
spotted in 14 states including California and Washington.
   Entomologists estimate the Russian wheat aphid has cost U.S.
small grains growers more than $100 million in insecticides and
lost yields.
   Figures for the 1988 crop aren't yet available, nor are
projections estimating the aphid problems the new crop might face.
But in 1987, about 38 percent, or about 4 million acres, of Kansas
wheat crop was affected, Brooks said.
   Infestation levels were even higher elsewhere. New Mexico and
Colorado officials said all of their small grains crops were
infested to varying degrees during 1987. In Nebraska, infestation
was 64 percent and in Texas, 56 percent.
   In some cases, the aphids are present in enough numbers to kill
plants, he said. Usually, their impact is on yields, turning
potentially high yield fields into riskier ventures.
   The aphid also helps provide shelter for another pest, the
greenbug. When Russian heat aphids attack wheat plant leaves, the
leaves roll up. Greenbugs like the protection this affords and
appear to use it for development, allowing them to attack in higher
numbers, he said.
   Greenbugs and Russian wheat aphids are similar in appearance,
Brooks said. The aphids have a more spindle-like body and don't
carry the dark stripe common to greenbugs. The aphid also doesn't
have the visible cornicles, or tailpipes, the greenbug has, he said.
   The first signs of Russian wheat aphid trouble come when plants
begin to show a green and white streaked appearance on the upper
side of their leaves, Brooks said. Damaged plants have a pink or
purple cast to the undersides of their leaves, he said.
   Driving by a field isn't a good way to survey it for the aphids,
nor is just checking the edges only.
   ``It is only when you get down on your hands and knees a ways
into a field and start looking plant by plant and tiller by tiller
that you can detect these early signs,'' Brooks said.
   He recommends checking about 20 consecutive plants and then
doing the same at about five other spots in the field.
   Sometimes, wheat streak mosaic and other diseases or pests may
mask the presence of the aphids, he said.
   Potential yields have to be taken into account when deciding
whether to hire an aerial sprayer to apply insecticide for around
$8 an acre.
   Volunteer wheat, which often sprouts after a harvest, and
natural grasses make good hosts for the pests before they can prey
on young planted wheat in early fall and early spring, Brooks said.
Volunteer, which also can spread other pests and diseases, should
be controlled to help eliminate problems.
   Some experts are recommending late-fall planting because
early-planted wheat and small grains seem to suffer the worst aphid
infestations.
   ``We really don't have any good documented evidence on just how
important that is right now,'' Brooks said.
   Entomologists fear the aphids could develop a tolerance to some
of the insecticides now being used.
   ``Just a slight increase in tolerance could mean the difference
between successful control and not being able to get control at
all,'' Brooks said.
   Insecticide manufacturers are developing new chemicals that can
replace those currently used if tolerance becomes a problem.
   Also, the U.S. Department of Agriculture is conducting a study
involving the importation of beneficial insects to control the
aphid. Insects are being transported from Russia and Afghanistan
for the research work.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions Sept. 3-4</NOTE>
