<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Asia-Economy     08-30 0521</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Asia-Economy,0543</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Southeast Asian Influence Will Increase In World Economy, Think
Tank Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Southeast Asia's role in the world economy will
expand through the year 2000, while Japanese markets will become
more competitive and U.S. output will decline, a think tank
predicted Tuesday.
   The Research Institute on the National Economy said in a
long-range forecast that Asia's Gross National Product, or its
total output of goods and services, will rise steadily over the
next decade while those of Europe and the United States will shrink.
   Through the turn of the century, Southeast Asia's GNP will rise
5.4 points while GNP in the European Community and North America
will decline 2.9 and 2.5 points, respectively, the institute
predicted.
   Meanwhile, Japan's economy will grow at an average
inflation-adjusted pace of 4.7 percent through the year 2000, the
institute said.
   ``We have to be aware that the Japanese market will become
increasingly competitive,'' the report said. ``This is because
imports will continue to rise because of the yen's appreciation.
   ``The Japanese economy ... will be considered an extremely large
market and direct investment by foreign companies will increase,''
it added.
   The institute said it based its prediction for the economic
growth of Southeast Asia on the recent fast rise in trade among the
countries in the region, including the so-called newly
industrialized economies like South Korea, Taiwan, Hong Kong and
Singapore as well as among members of the Association of Southeast
Asian Nations, including Thailand, Indonesia and Malaysia.
   Steady development in the division of industrial production
between Southeast Asian countries and Japan will help avoid serious
competition among themselves, the report said.
   Economic growth of North America and the European Community has
come primarily from the effects of policies set in motion, the
report said, but the development of the Southeast Asian economy has
drawn its strength from ``autonomous economic dynamism'' itself.
   The report forecast that Japan's economic growth will be powered
by personal spending and private-sector capital investment.
   In addition, investment profits will surge in Japan, with the
outstanding balance of investments in 2000 reaching $1.100 trillion
and profits totaling at least $80 billion a year, the institute
said.
   A characteristic of the Japanese economy toward the year 2000
will be clearly reflected in the country's international balance of
payments, according to the think tank.
   Japan's trade surplus will shrink to $600 million from $94.3
billion in fiscal 1987 ended last March, almost attaining
equilibrium, it said. Exports will increase an average 7.2 percent
in each of the years but imports will register an 11.6 percent rise
due in part to stronger internal demand for manufactured goods, the
institute said.
   However, Japan won't become a net debtor, according to the
institute.
   The institute said the U.S. economy has the potential to attain
growth exceeding 3 percent a year after inflation is taken into
account.
   ``Already, its trade deficit has been shrinking as a result of
economic expansion led by exports,'' it said.
   The U.S. budget deficit also will dwindle because of high tax
revenues, it predicted. By the mid-1990s the so-called ``twin
deficts'' will largely disappear, it said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880830-0233 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-30-88 1352EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a f PM-BusinessMirror Adv31   08-30 0751</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 31 ,0774</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 31</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release PMs Wednesday Aug. 31</NOTE>
<HEAD>Breaking The Credit Barrier</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Every year a new crop of youngsters enters the
world of adult finance, the first requirement of which is access to
credit in their own names.
   This is a credit society, and those who don't have it _ who, in
fact, might disdain it in favor of paying everything in cash _ very
often find themselves in perplexing situations.
   In fact, it has been argued from time to time that credit is a
right, since the possibilities of existing or advancing in a credit
society are greatly lessened for those who pay in cash or are
denied access to the system.
   Having credit is, in a sense, a person's identity in the
marketplace, often being necessary to rent a car or reserve a hotel
room. An absolutely credit-free record might be admired in some
places, but not in the marketplace.
   It is odd, therefore, that there is no smooth, formal,
recognized, accepted, institutionalized way of entering the world
of credit. You must, so to speak, walk through the wall. There is
no door; there isn't even a key.
   At most, there are a few tips, says the Consumer Credit
Institute, to wit:
   _If you haven't already done so, open a checking account and a
savings account at a financial institution. You may then use the
institution as a credit reference, assuming you keep your checkbook
correctly posted.
   _After a couple of months, ask that institution for a Visa or
Mastercard line of credit. Some might offer these cards even before
you apply. If so, take them, and never miss a payment.
   _Investigate ``affinity group'' credit. This is credit made
available to members of a particular group, including alumni of
colleges. Such groups sometimes offer widely accept credit cards.
   _Check on the prospect of using your savings account as
collateral for a loan. Generally, such loans also carry very low
interest rates.
   _Apply for a local retailer's charge card. Small stores tend to
judge you at face value rather than through credit history. They
want your business. If you obtain credit, pay your bills promptly.
You want them as a reference.
   Even if you're successful in all these possibilities, you still
might be forced into having a co-signer for big-ticket items such
as an automobiles. Co-signers often are parents.
   Most of these suggestions are from the institute, a division of
the American Financial Services Association, which represents
companies that lend to consumers and small businesses. But such
suggestion are only the beginning.
   That is, once credit is established, it must be built, a process
that new credit-users have always sought to speed up. It can be
done, although it might cost a small amount of money.
   The technique, used over the years by many entrepreneurs, is to
borrow money and then simply use it and a bit more to repay the
loan ahead of the scheduled repayment date. Pre-payment impresses
lenders.
   On the next visit to the lender you make use of your good
record. You apply for a somewhat larger amount, and because of your
good repayment record you might get it.
   Tyler Hicks, a business executive and author of more than 50
books on grassroots financing, describes a once popular technique
in which borrowers obtained three times as much money as their
financial situation would suggest.
   The technique was simple: Knowing they faced a turndown if they
applied for $15,000, they applied instead for five $5,000 loans at
five banks in the same day.
   To the question, ``Do you owe money to any other lender?'' they
would answer ``no.'' It was an honest answer, since they really had
no big debts outstanding.
   If the person was lucky, and appeared to be reliable and
responsible, perhaps three banks would respond with $5,000 each.
The trick then was to find an investment that would make the
$15,000 grow larger.
   The more conservative of these borrowers would refrain from
using the entire $15,000, but instead would invest $10,000 in an
income-producing property and keep $5,000 in reserve to service the
three loans.
   It was a desperate procedure, but many real estate investors got
started with this or similar techniques.
   They agree it was dangerous to their financial health, but as
they saw it, it was even unhealthier to attempt getting along
without sufficient credit in a credit-based society.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Wednesday Aug. 31</NOTE>
</DOC>
