</TEXT>
<HEAD>/ld hold his own.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   And holding his own might be good enough to be declared the
winner, given the low expectations accorded the Indiana senator.
   ``We're on the wrong end of the expectations game, as far as the
vice presidential debate is concerned, because everyone expects
Sen. Bentsen to do so well,'' said Linda Peek, a long-time Senate
Democratic strategist who is now a private consultant in Washington.
   Other Democrats already are defending Bentsen, in advance of a
debate that may never come off.
   ``The senator is concerned about a debate because his style as a
senator is to get things done and he doesn't engage in a lot of
sparring on the floor,'' national party spokesman Mike McCurry
said. On the other hand, ``It's easy to envision Dan Quayle as a TV
talk show host.''
   Bentsen also must be careful not to bludgeon Quayle and win him
a backlash of sympathy among voters, as has occurred in the recent
controversy over Quayle's National Guard record.
   Norman Ornstein, who studies politics at the American Enterprise
Institute, says the Democrats have reason to worry about Quayle.
   ``He is not a dummy,'' Ornstein said. In past debates, such as
when he defeated incumbent Birch Bayh to win the Senate in 1980,
Quayle showed ``when he was prepared, well-briefed, and focused, he
could do all right.''
   Bentsen, meanwhile, has the difficult task of not wanting to
help the Republicans in their expectations game and also not
wanting to speak well of Quayle.
   ``It isn't in Bentsen's interest to talk about Quayle,''
Ornstein said.
   So while he clearly sees Quayle as a lesser opponent, Bentsen
must focus his attacks away from the man and back to the issues and
Quayle's conservative voting record.
   ``I don't want to get into his personal life. That I don't want
to do,'' Bentsen says.
   Then Bentsen hints about which Republican would have been a
worthy opponent.
   ``I thought it would be Bob Dole, frankly,'' he says. ``It's a
real gamble picking Quayle, and I think it's going to be proven
that way.''
</TEXT>
