<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0295</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Close Sharply Higher On Wheat Export News</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures closed sharply higher
Tuesday on the Chicago Board of Trade with the wheat market leading
the way on news that China and India each were seeking to buy
300,000 metric tons of subsidized U.S. wheat.
   Rumors that the Soviet Union was arranging to have grain shipped
from the United States fueled speculation that the Soviets also
were in the market for U.S. wheat, but that could not be confirmed,
analysts said.
   ``Supposedly they were chartering freight, but we don't know if
that's for business that's already been done or business that's
going to be done,'' said Cathy Leow, an assistant vice president in
the grain futures trading division of Thomson McKinnon Securities
Inc. in New York.
   Corn futures prices got an additional boost from news that a
federal magistrate in St. Paul, Minn., recommended the Agriculture
Department be ordered to extend indefinitely crop price-support
loans scheduled to mature on Wednesday.
   The recommendation, if accepted by the judge hearing a case
brought by several farmers, would delay the release of 400 million
to 500 million bushels of corn onto the market.
   Soybeans posted sharp gains late in the session, mostly on
spillover buying from the grain pits, Ms. Leow said.
   At the close, wheat was 8\ cents to 11 cents higher with the
contract for delivery in September at $3.95{ a bushel; corn was {
cent to 5} cents higher with Setember at $2.78} a bushel; oats were
5 cents to 8{ cents higher with September at $2.54{ a bushel;
soybeans were 14{ cents to 23 cents higher with September at $8.48
a bushel.
</TEXT>
