<FILEID>AP-NR-08-30-88 1620EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-TWA-Labor Bjt   08-30 0637</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-TWA-Labor, Bjt,0656</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Flight Attendants Ask DOT to Investigate Icahn's Fitness</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARJORIE ANDERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Carl Icahn is using TWA as his personal cash cow
to the detriment of the airline and public safety, the flight
attendants union charged Tuesday.
   The union asked the U.S. Department of Transportation to block
Icahn's plan to take Trans World Airlines Inc. private and to
freeze TWA assets while it investigates his fitness to continue
managing the airline.
   Vicki Frankovich, president of the Independent Federation of
Flight Attendants, charged that since Icahn took control of TWA a
little more than two years ago, he has ``milked'' the airline's
cash reserves and sold off assets to finance his stock market and
takeover ventures rather than buy new airplanes and other safety
equipment needed to assure TWA's future.
   Through spokesman Bob Allen, Icahn called IFFA's allegations
``spurious, malicious and erroneous'' and designed ``to embarrass
the airline.''
   ``Today TWA has more planes, serves more airports and carries
more passengers than in 1986,'' Allen said in a formal statement.
   Still, TWA's fleet remains the oldest in the industry; the
average plane is 14.6 years old, the union said. A TWA Boeing 727
that landed on its belly Saturday in Chicago when its landing gear
failed to descend was 24 years old, according to the National
Transportation Safety Board, which still is investigating the cause
of that incident.
   The union criticized TWA's plans to spend just 1 percent of the
gross value of its fleet on new equipment this year while other
airlines are spending about 15 or 20 percent on new, fuel-efficient
planes.
   This, the union says, contributes to high maintenance costs and
the airline's accident and incident rate, which according to the
Federal Aviation Administration is the worst among the top 10
American airlines.
   Old airplanes also cost more to maintain than new ones and TWA
will have to spend more and more to keep its planes safe, the union
says.
   ``This would require a healthy cash flow,'' Frankovich said.
``But according to disclosures in Icahn's own filings before the
Securities and Exchange Commission, TWA's cash flow is not expected
to be sufficient to repay the increased debt to be incurred under
his privatization plan.''
   Icahn, who owns 75 percent of TWA's stock, will ask minority
shareholders at a meeting Sept. 7 to sell their stock to him.
Payments would be financed by the sale of $250 million in
speculative, high-yield bonds.
   This would raise TWA's annual interest payments to $466 million,
almost double the airline's 1987 operating earnings of $240
million, according to IFFA's analysis.
   In addition, for his TWA stock, Icahn would receive $400 million
in TWA assets, including a big chunk of Texaco stock, the union
said.
   ``TWA is being managed today not as an air carrier but as an
unsupervised mutual fund benefiting Mr. Icahn,'' Frankovich said.
   ``Unless the DOT acts now to stop him, Carl Icahn and his
companies will take $650 million out of an already weakened TWA and
leave the flying public, his creditors and his long-suffering
employees to reap the sad and perhaps tragic consequences,'' she
added.
   Icahn, in his statement, said: ``I have no doubt that TWA
employees, the traveling public and the appropriate government
officials will see through IFFA's meritless charges and understand
IFFA's motivation.''
   TWA's machinists union, which also opposes the privatization and
filed suit in federal court last week to stop it, is being asked to
join the IFFA petition but has not yet had time to study it,
Frankovich said.
   Unions at Eastern Airlines made a similar request to the DOT
last year. In its findings the DOT said acrimonious relations
between labor and management could lead to operational problems and
a former U.S. Secretary of Labor was appointed to act as a mediator.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
