<1ST_LINE>u f AM-FactoryOrders 1stLd-Writethru   08-30 0525</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Factory Orders, 1st Ld-Writethru,0542</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Drop in Defense Work Holds Down Factory Orders</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 2nd graf, ``The Commerce,'' to CORRECT figure to 3.5
percent, sted 3.4 percent</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic NY21</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Economy Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Orders to U.S. factories for manufactured
goods fell sharply in July, pulled down by the biggest drop in
defense orders in more than four years, the government said Tuesday.
   The Commerce Department said orders for both durable and
non-durable goods slipped 3.5 percent to $220.2 billion last month.
It was the worst drop since January 1987, when orders fell 3.6
percent.
   But economists were not concerned about the decrease because it
was heavily influenced by the volatile military goods category and
came one month after the strongest increase in total orders in more
than 17 years.
   ``The orders numbers were down because of some fluctuations in
some very volatile categories. They'll be up again in August,''
said Bruce Steinberg, an economist with Merrill Lynch in New York.
   In July, defense orders plummeted 46.6 percent to $7.4 billion,
reversing a 68.3 percent gain a month earlier. Last month's drop in
this category was the steepest since April 1984. The June increase
had been the biggest since December 1982.
   Excluding the defense category, orders were down 0.7 percent in
July following a healthy 2.9 percent gain in June.
   U.S. manufacturing, which languished earlier in the decade
because of the strong dollar, has rebounded. The weaker dollar has
fueled a resurgence in sales of American goods overseas and
businesses have responded by spending more to upgrade and replace
outmoded plant and equipment.
   But demand for U.S. goods has been so strong that some analysts
are concerned that factory capacity will be strained, pushing
prices higher.
   Samuel D. Kahan, an economist with Kleinwort Benson Government
Securities Inc. in Chicago, said that despite the overall drop in
factory orders in July, ``there is very little evidence yet that
the manufacturing sector is moderating.''
   A particular sign of strength, he said, is the category of
non-defense capital goods, which is considered a good indication of
business expansion plans. It was up 0.9 percent to $35.8 billion,
following a 12.5 percent increase in June.
   ``That, I think, is the more telling story. .... Despite the
fact that last month's number was a strong increase, we were still
able to scratch out a further increase this month,'' Kahan said.
   The overall July decline followed a 5.4 percent surge in June,
the biggest since December 1970. Orders were down 0.3 percent in
May.
   The Commerce Department offered these details of July activity:
   _Total orders for durable goods, ``big ticket'' items expected
to last three or more years, were off 7.1 percent in July following
an 8.7 percent gain in June.
   _Orders for transportation equipment, both military and
non-military, were off 22.0 percent after soaring 33.3 percent a
month earlier.
   _Non-electrical machinery was down 4.2 percent, while electrical
machinery jumped 4.1 percent.
   _Orders for non-durable goods rose 1.0 percent after increasing
1.6 percent a month earlier.
   _Shipments of manufactured goods fell 0.9 percent to $216.9
billion, after rising 1.4 percent in June.
</TEXT>
