<1ST_LINE>r f AM-UtilityInvestigation     08-30 0564</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Utility Investigation,0580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Georgia Power, Southern Co. Tax Accounting Investigated</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Court papers unsealed Tuesday show federal agents
are trying to determine if Georgia Power Co. avoided paying
millions of dollars in federal taxes through the way it accounted
for spare parts.
   Besides Georgia Power, one of the nation's richest utilities,
the investigation includes its parent, the Southern Co., and the
Big Eight accounting firm of Arthur Andersen & Co.
   The papers raise the question of whether the companies and their
accountants sought to hide about $61 million in spare parts to
avoid paying $50 million in federal taxes, interest and penalties.
The complicated arrangement deals with whether parts are classified
as being emergency spare parts or for maintenance and when they
become expenses to the company.
   The papers also raise the question of Georgia Power's accounting
for the sale of 5 percent of Plant Vogtle nuclear power plant to
the Municipal Electric Authority of Georgia. In the documents,
officials say the deal was treated as a sale of 5 percent of the
$8.87 billion plant for book value purposes, but as 1.35 percent
for tax purposes, saving the company between $10 million and $12
million.
   The papers include excerpts of taped conversations in which
Southern Co.'s tax chief agrees with a confidential informant that
the company misled the IRS over the tax accounting of the spare
parts, but adds, ``Don't ever say that.''
   The investigation, which dates from 1982, is based largely on
information contained in taped conversations between utility and
Andersen officials and the informant, who is being paid for his
participation and been exempted from prosecution, according to the
court papers.
   U.S. Attorney Robert Barr confirmed the investigation, but
refused to provide details beyond what was contained in the papers
because a grand jury is involved.
   He said the investigation, which is continuing, involves
possible criminal wrongdoing, including violations of the U.S. Tax
Code.
   Although the court papers unsealed Tuesday focus on Georgia
Power, Southern Co. and Arthur Andersen, Barr said other companies
or individuals may be involved. The affidavit says Southern
subsidiaries Mississippi Power Co. and Gulf Power Co. used proper
accounting procedures for spare parts.
   The Atlanta Constitution reported the investigation last week,
after Internal Revenue Service agents executed search warrants at
the downtown Atlanta headquarters of Georgia Power as well as the
home of Tim Fallaw, Southern Co.'s director of taxes.
   The Constitution said other companies being investigated include
Oglethorpe Power Co., which provides electricity to electric
cooperatives in the state.
   In a Tuesday afternoon news conference, Georgia Power chairman
Robert W. Scherer said the allegations ``if true (are) shocking to
me personally and I'm sure to the employees of Georgia Power.''
   Scherer said, ``I want to state as plainly as I can to you that
I will not tolerate wrongdoing and I will not tolerate the coverup
of wrongdoing at Georgia Power Co. and I personally will get to the
bottom of this matter.''
   Scherer said the accounting for spare parts is ``one of those
complex areas in the tax law that is open to legitimate
disagreement among reputable accountants.''
   The chairman refused to take questions.
   Southern Co. spokesman Gale Clappa said the holding company
would have nothing further to add to Scherer's statement. Officials
at Arthur Andersen's Atlanta office had no immediate comment on the
material.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880830-0251 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-30-88 2026EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-AtariSuit     08-30 0353</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Atari Suit,0367</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Atari Files Suit Over Federated Group Acquisition</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Atari Corp. has filed a lawsuit charging
it was defrauded last year when it purchased Federated Group Inc.,
a retail electronics chain.
   In the suit, the personal computer and video game maker claimed
it was defrauded of $43 million when it bought Federated in August
1987 and completed the acquisition in October for $64.1 million in
cash.
   Atari charged that Wilfred Schwartz, Federated's former chairman
and principal stockholder, conspired with other Federated officers
to misrepresent the value of the company's assets.
   Atari also sued Ernst & Whinney, accountants for Federated at
the time of the acquisition, and Goldman Sachs & Co., the
investment banking firm that represented Federated in the
transaction.
   ``We stand behind our work,'' Don Howarth, a spokesman for New
York-based Ernst & Whinney, said on Tuesday.
   A spokesman for Goldman Sachs said the company would not comment
on the suit. Schwartz could not be reached for comment Tuesday.
   Atari filed the suit in U.S. District Court in San Jose on
Friday.
   Federated _ which operated 68 stores in California, Arizona, New
Mexico and Kansas _ was losing money at the time it was acquired.
Atari expected to engineer a quick turnaround of the company.
   However, Federated has continued to lose money, and Atari closed
six unprofitable stores of its new subsidiary. Federated lost $9.6
million on sales of $71.5 million during the quarter ended April 2.
   Joshua Tropper, corporate counsel for Atari, said after the
filing his company's auditors had detected $29 million in
discrepancies in the value of Federated's assets before going ahead
with the purchase. The last financial report before the Atari bid
showed Federated with assets of some $200 million.
   Tropper said Atari went ahead with the takeover after Schwartz
agreed to have outside auditors review Federated's books.
   Coopers & Lybrand, the accounting firm that performed the audit,
reported in February Federated's assets had been overstated by $43
million.
   Following the audit, Atari reduced the value of the Federated
assets by $43 million in its financial report for the first quarter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
