<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Becton-Gloves     08-30 0171</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Becton-Gloves,0178</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Becton Dickinson To Sell Industrial Glove Business</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Becton Dickinson and Co. said Tuesday it will
sell its industrial glove business but keep its medical glove
business, whose sales and profits are booming because of the heavy
demand for gloves provoked by the AIDS crisis.
   The sale of the industrial-glove portion of the Edmont division
represents the last step in Becton Dickinson's drive to sell off
all non-medical portions of its business, a process that began in
1983.
   The industrial-glove portion of Edmont earned $10 million on
revenue of $105 million in the first nine months of its current
fiscal year, Becton Dickinson said. It will be put up for sale
through First Boston Corp.
   The smaller medical-glove portion of Edmont had revenue of $15
million in the nine-month period, up from $11 million in all of
fiscal 1987. Ronald Jasper, the head of investor relations, said
profits had grown as well, but declined to provide numbers.
   Becton Dickinson is based in Franklin Lakes, N.J.
</TEXT>
