<FILEID>AP-NR-08-30-88 1758EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-FreddieMac     08-30 0415</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Freddie Mac,0427</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Home Loan Mortgage Corp. OKs 4-1 Stock Split</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corp. on
Tuesday approved a 4-for-1 stock swap as part of its plan to open
up ownership of its preferred stock to public investors and bring a
more than $1 billion windfall to the savings and loan industry.
   The corporation, known as Freddie Mac, is a congressionally
created entity that buys home mortgages from savings institutions
and other lenders and packages them into securities for resale to
investors, making more money available for home buyers.
   Ownership of Freddie Mac's 15 million preferred shares is
currently restricted to the 2,500 savings institutions who are
members of the Federal Home Loan Bank system.
   As part of an effort to bring new capital to the ailing
industry, federal regulators in July voted in principle to lift
restrictions on ownership of the preferred stock, which has no
voting power.
   The price of the stock, which was $60 a share in early June, has
soared. After Tuesday's announcment, spelling out details of how
the ownership restrictions will be lifted, the stock rose $6.50 a
share to $145 in trading on the New York Stock Exchange.
   Members of Congress, led by Sen. William Proxmire, D-Wis.,
chairman of the Senate Banking Committee, had been pressing federal
regulators to funnel some of the windfall into the Federal Savings
and Loan Insurance Corp., the financially strapped fund that backs
deposits in savings institutions.
   Trade groups have opposed that, arguing it is important to bring
new capital to the healthy segment of the industry, which owns most
of the Freddie Mac stock.
   M. Danny Wall, the top federal S&L regulator and chairman of
Freddie Mac's board, repeated that regulators have decided
Proxmire's plan ``is clearly not going to be done.''
   Freddie Mac said it will offer four new shares of preferred
stock for each old share between Oct. 17 and Nov. 30. Public
investors would not be permitted to purchase the stock until after
Jan. 1.
   The corporation said it has retained the right to rescind the
entire exchange offer if fewer than two-thirds of the shares are
turned in. However, it approved two provisions designed to
encourage the exchange.
   Each new share will be guaranteed at least a fourth of the
dividends paid to an old share, but could receive more. Also, old
shares not exchanged before Nov. 30 could later be swapped for only
3.5 new shares.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
