<2ND_LINE>AM-Construction Contracts,0148</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Contracting For New Construction Falls 5 Percent In July</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Contracting for new construction fell 5 percent
in July after spurting higher the previous two months, according to
a report Tuesday.
   The July decline was concentrated in the volatile public works
sector, the F.W. Dodge Group of McGraw-Hill Information Services
Co. said.
   F.W. Dodge said construction activity has been drifting downward
since last fall.
   ``Expectations for a lasting turn-around, which were none too
high before the latest round of credit restraint, have just been
lowered,'' George Christie, vice president and chief economist of
F.W. Dodge, said in a statement.
   Construction of manufacturing facilities continued to be strong
because of the ongoing squeeze on factory capacity, Christie said.
   The July level came to an annualized rate of $245.4 billion for
contracting for new construction.
</TEXT>
