<2ND_LINE>AM-Timber Strike,0345</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Settlement Said Near In Champion Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Negotiators on Tuesday reached a tentative
agreement that could end a strike by about 2,400 Champion
International Corp. wood products workers in Oregon, Washington and
Montana.
   Bill Hubbell, president of the International Woodworkers of
America-U.S., refused comment on the offer, which is subject to
approval by the IWA and the Western Council of Industrial Workers.
   Ratification votes would be complete and results would be
announced by Saturday, said Hubbell. He refused to speculate on the
offer's chances of approval.
   If the Champion workers settle, only about 1,800 workers would
remain off the job in the Northwest timber strike that began June
6. At its peak, the walkout idled about 9,000 workers in five
states.
   Workers are still striking at DAW Forest Products Inc., WI
Forest Products Inc., Lakeview Lumber Co. and Morgan Products Ltd.
   On Monday, non-striking workers narrowly approved a contract
agreement with Georgia Pacific Corp. in Oregon and Washington.
   In another development, Weyerhaeuser Co. representatives said
they were scheduled to meet with union bargainers in Portland on
Thursday. About 6,000 Weyerhaeuser workers in the region were not
affected by the walkout.
   Mike Draper, executive officer of the Western Council of
Industrial Workers, and Hubbell said the Georgia-Pacific
ratification vote was quite close, but neither official would
release any numbers or percentages on the balloting.
   Dave Odgers, a Georgia-Pacific spokesman, said the new pact is
similar to the recent agreement involving Willamette Industries
Inc., which has produced a pattern for settlements in the industry.
   Odgers said the Georgia-Pacific contract calls for a $1,400
bonus in the first year, with basic pay increases of 11 percent
over the remaining length of the four-year agreement.
   The contract covers 700 workes at mill operations in
Springfield, Coquille and Lebanon and 500 in a two-mill complex in
Martell, Calif.
   Besides Georgia-Pacific and Willamette Industries, other major
companies that have settled with the unions are Boise Cascade Corp.
and Simpson Timber Co.
</TEXT>
