<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Retail,0251</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Shoe Reports $9 Million Loss in Second Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Shoe Corp., currently considering
restructuring or a possible sale of the company, said Tuesday it
lost $9.4 million during its second quarter.
   The retailer and shoe manufacturer's loss in the quarter ended
July 30 compared with earnings of $5.5 million, or 12 cents a
share, in the comparable period a year earlier.
   The company reported sales of $544.4 million, up from $511.1
million a year earlier.
   U.S. Shoe has been hit hard by the slump in apparel sales. The
company has hired Merrill Lynch Capital Markets to suggest ways to
maximize its shareholder value, including the possible
restructuring or sale of all or parts of the company.
   The company, which has been mentioned as a prime takeover
target, said its results reflected a one-time gain of $7.3 million
from the sale of several divisions and $3.1 million in charges,
partly attributable to the closing of stores in Chicago, Atlanta
and Indianapolis.
   U.S. Shoe's 1,700 specialty stores include Casual Corner, Ups 'N
Downs, Caren Charles and Lenscrafters. It also manufacturers shoes
under labels including Selby, Red Cross, Cobbies, Pappagallo and
Socialites.
   For the first six months, U.S. Shoe reported a loss of $6.3
million, against year-earlier earnings of $29.6 million, or 66
cents a share. The 1987 figure includes a $16 million gain from an
accounting change.
   First-half sales totaled $1.07 billion, up from $1.02 billion.
</TEXT>
