<1ST_LINE>r f BC-PMNLayoffs     08-30 0365</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-PMN Layoffs,0377</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Public Service of New Mexico Cutting 19.4 Percent Of Workforce</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUE MAJOR HOLMES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Public Service Company of New Mexico
laid off 656 employees Tuesday, or 15.9 percent of its workforce,
in the latest cutbacks under a major cost-cutting program.
   The state's largest utility had 4,126 full-time positions before
the job eliminations. Tuesday's cuts boosted job eliminations to
19.4 percent of its workforce, and followed the layoffs of 129
union workers from PNM's electrical operations and the elimination
of all 14 jobs in its aviation department.
   ``Our goal is to have earnings such that we can continue
dividends and regain our financial health,'' said Jerry Geist, PNM
president and chairman.
   Geist said jobs were cut from operations across the state and
from all levels of the company, including 30 percent reductions in
the corporate office.
   He said the job cuts would save $28.4 million in salaries, wages
and benefits a year and that non-labor cost-cutting measures would
save $15.4 million.
   PNM officials also announced construction expenses were cut by
$19 million in 1988 and $33.6 million in budgeted 1989 levels.
   Geist said PNM dropped its employee stock purchase plan and
imposed an across-the-board salary freeze until the middle of next
year. Executive salaries and benefits were cut in January, so the
latest salary freeze is an extended freeze for PNM officials, he
said.
   Geist said Tuesday actions would not affect the reliability or
safety of electrical or gas service, but would slow the utility's
response time for things such as requests for new service.
   The utility's financial problems over the past year are largely
due to a huge excess generating capacity. Its share of costs of the
Palo Verde Nuclear Generating Station in Arizona and a unit of the
coal-fired San Juan Generating Station near Farmington are not
included in its rates.
   Earnings dropped 38 percent between 1986 and 1987 and have
continued dropping this year, Geist said. Shareholder dividends
have been cut by nearly 50 percent, he said.
   PNM's stock, which climbed to a high of $39 in early 1987, rose
$1.25 to $13.75 a share Tuesday on the New York Stock Exchange.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
